Dennis Quaid outraged counter-attacks
She wanted to promote a new film, spoke of her private life in an interview - and now has problems with her ex: Hollywood star Meg Ryan has lifted the veil on her adulterous ex, Dennis Quaid.
He skims - and counter-attacks.
A late war of the roses in the ex-couple Meg Ryan and Dennis Quaid: seven years after their divorce, the two Hollywood actors are engaging in an unsightly battle - in full view of everyone.
Last week, during an interview for the American newspaper InStyle, Meg Ryan spoke about the causes for the failure of her marriage: "Dennis has been unfaithful for a long time, and it was very painful."
She may have acknowledged the extent of the deceit only after the divorce.
The reason for baring her thoughts lies in Ryan's media relations for her new film "The Women," which tells a story about adultery.
Dennis Quaid's reaction regarding his characterization as an unfaithful husband emerged clearly: this would be "monstrous", he said to the "New York Daily News', at 54 years of age, "Meg is again rehashing and manipulating the history of our relationship".
Moreover it would be "regrettable", that "the sorrow and the upsets included by a divorce for every child should be rekindled again in public" for their 16-year-old son, Jack."
While Ryan has lived alone since the divorce, Quaid remarried and soon became the father of twins.
His reaction to the attack was: "In any case, my life goes on."
I count myself lucky to have a wonderful family that is at its best".
The airline tickets prices and hotels are dropping
In the first half of 2008, flights and hotel nights were cheaper than the previous year.
In Germany, according to a recent study, the flights would be even cut up to 50 percent.
Flights and hotel stays would become profitable again - that is the result of a study by American Express, the provider of financial and travel services.
The company has analysed the data of bookings in the first half of 2008 and has established, after a rise in prices in the first quarter, a sharp fall in profits in the second quarter.
After the prices on the hotels market have risen for years, the nights in hotels have already reduced in many places.
From January to March, prices rose in 41 of the 48 European cities examined again 6.9 percent on average compared with 2007 in 41 of the 48 European cities examined.
From April to June, prices were already 3.6 percent lower than the previous year.
The trend was clear especially in Paris and Rome, where travellers had to pay by 30 to 37 percent less than a year earlier.
The causes of all that reside for American Express in the weak dollar which has led to a "lower desire to travel from American tourists".
The financial centres such as Frankfurt or London would be even more affected by the decline in prices of hotels than industrial sites like Hanover, Cologne or Stavanger.
In Swedish cities, hotel prices are hanging on, with a rise of 26.3 percent, the record in Europe.
Also in terms of flight prices, the trend was rising in the first quarter:
Due to the increase in the price of kerosene, passengers in economy class had to pay an average of 7.1 percent more than in 2007, long-haul flights, which consume a lot of fuel, have even risen to 29.2 percent.
From April to June, tickets prices in economy class have fallen by an average of 12.5 per cent compared with the previous quarter, in business class and in first class, however, variations in prices have been far less pronounced.
In Germany, prices have plummeted even more significantly than in other European countries.
From January to March, prices had risen by 11.9 percent, in the second quarter, they have brought 23.6 per cent down.
The German domestic flights have even been halved according to this study.
The reasons for this fall in prices would be on the one hand a bending economic growth, explains the firm.
Demand gave way in much of the market segment of airplane travel.
On the other side, there would exist an increased pressure of the competition because of the "Open Skies" treaty that liberalizes air traffic between the United States and Europe.
One sign of the tense situation is the airline companies' elimination of routes that are not profitable, as well as the higher number of airline companies that will have gone into bankruptcy during the first half of 2008 - there were 24 companies in Europe alone.
