Dark matter influences the flight of space probes.
For years, a mysterious phenomenon has been perplexing researchers: dark matter influences the speed of space probes during what are called maneuvers using gravitational pull.
Experts fear that the general theory of relativity is not completely accurate.
For almost 18 years the "Ulysses" space probe has been flying in space.
Because of fuel pipeline soon frozen, the cryogenic death is a threat for her.
For years, a mysterious phenomenon is causing confusion among researchers - the anomaly of the gravity assist.
The gravitationnal support is a space probes' operation, in which they get an extra boost in an astronomical obect's gravitationnal field, Earth, for example.
Thus, the probes can save a lot of fuel.
The Cassini-Huygens americo-european research probe used this physics trick, just like the Ulysses solar probe.
Anyway, this is what surprised researchers for years: the flying objects are not always behaving at 100 percent as we expect according to the venerable gravity laws.
Furthermore, discrepencies appears on the speed level
The probes become unexpectedly faster or slower.
Until now, physicians could not explain this.
They named it the anomaly of gravitational support.
Some experts fear that Albert Einstein's theory of relativity, which described the force of attraction of matter as due to the curvature of space, may not be entirely correct.
American physicist Stephen Adler of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton still believes wholeheartedly that Einstein was not wrong and is trying to explain the anomaly of the gravitational slingshot using the so-called dark matter that astronomers have identified in the universe.
"Black matter might be responsible for this anomaly, matter which is also located close to Earth," he writes.
Researchers in the area of space know about dark matter only for about ten years.
It apparently emanates from it an attractive force whose effect is seen on other celestial bodies.
It is however completely invisible, meaning that it neither sends out nor reflects any electromagnetic radiation, especially visible light.
According to calculations of scientists, the dark matter would still represent a non-negligible fifth of the total mass of the universe.
The tourists kidnapped in Egypt are free.
After ten days in the hands of their captors, the kidnapped tourists in Egypt had to be released and Italy's Minister of Foreign Affairs confirmed it.
The kidnappers in Sudan had demanded a ransom of several million euros.
During the shootout prior to release, six of the hostage takers were killed.
In southern Egypt, five Germans have been kidnapped.
The negotiations concerning the ransom would already have started.
Germans are constantly in the crosshairs of kidnappers.
WELT ONLINE depicts the most important cases.
The European tourists kidnapped in the Sahara are obviously free.
It is what was conveyed in unison by the Egyptian state television, the Arab television channel Al-Arabija and the Italian media.
The Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs Franco Frattini, confirmed the release after news of the Italian television channel Sky TG 24: "Our citizens and the other hostages have been released.
We are in the process of checking out the state of their health," said Frattini.
The five Germans, five Italians and the Romanian and their eight Egyptians companions are doing well and are safe, announced the Egyptian national television.
The 19 participants in the trip in the desert should already be on their way to Cairo.
The circumstances surrounding the shooting before the release of hostages are still unclear: the kidnappers might have been close to ending the abduction, according to an Egyptian security official, a moment before the Sudanese army suddenly killed six of the kidnappers without any warning.
"The problem was solved.
They were in agreement with a ransom", said the agent.
All that was left was to collect the hostage", when suddenly, "this surprise" occurred.
Sudanese solders had shot six of the kidnappers this Sunday in the border area between the Sudan, Chad and Egypt, and had arrested two of them.
The kidnappers had demanded from Germany a ransom amounting to six million euros; the money was to be handed over by the German wife of one of the hostages.
The daily newspaper, "El Masri El Jom" said that, according to the statements of a German mediator, the release of the hostages was delayed because the kidnappers feared for their safety.
According to the article, the kidnappers wanted to free the female hostages after the payment of the ransom.
The men had to be held until the kidnappers had found a safe route to escape.
The German Embassy in Cairo refused to make any comment about this story.
Abuse from a stepfather "which led to suicide."
A court has been informed that years of abuse inflicted by his father-in-law led a woman to commit suicide.
Michael Trerise, 57, of Stithians in Cornwall, has been jailed for six years after he admitted to eight counts of indecent assault.
The High Court in Truro ruled that he regularly tied up his step-daughter, Stephanie Randle, during her childhood, from 5 to 7 years of age.
Trerise wrote in a letter of confession: "I feel responsible for his death."
The tribunal was informed that Ms Randle, aged 34, committed suicide at her place in Mutley, Plymouth, on April 1 2007.
When she was a child living in Coventry, Trerise had tied her up and blindfolded her before forcing her to perform sexual acts, while his mother was working in the pub.
Trerise and his wife divorced in the 1980s, and he went back to live in Cornwall.
His daughter-in-law went to Plymouth.
But the tribunal was told that Ms Randle, industrious volunteer for National Trust, was haunted by the abuses she had to endure twice a week.
Prosecutor Ramsey Quaife said in court that friends had reported that Ms. Randle, who was a good surfer and cyclist, seemed "emotionally dead," since 2006 and "had lost all hope about life."
In April 2007, her true father, Terrance Randle, found her dead in her apartment in Plymouth.
It is believed that she committed suicide by suffocating herself with a plastic bag.
Mr Randle confronts his daughter's father-in-law who had also written a letter of confession, which finished thus: "I tied her up and bandaged her regularly."
"I have not abused her sexually.
"I feel responsible for his death."
The Judge Christopher Elwen said to Trerise: "You are really bizarre as fetishist, your victim must surely be terrorized, especially at the age of 7 years."
"This unpleasant saga ended with the suicide of the victim.
And what is even more surprising, is that if she hadn't made this gesture, its history would certainly never ended in court. "
He added: "I point out in particular, as described by her father and her mother, the effects of your crime committed for years on Stéphanie.
"Without them, she would no doubt be today a young happy woman, promising, and successful."
