The ministerial officer from office staff who had forgotten the top secret documents on a train, in June, will be condemned by the Official Secrets Act, knew the BBC.
The men of the Ministry of Defense was journeying when he forgot two highly classified documents on a train heading to Waterloo.
The documents went through the hands of the BBC before being handed to police.
This is the less serious condemnation of this act, without any insinuation of criminal intent.
The BBC correspondent, Frank Gardner said that this episode had many people from Whitehall.
"They thought this affair would remain between the walls of the Ministry of Defence and the Cabinet Office," he said.
The employee who cannot be named, is accused of breach of Section 8.1 of the act, that is to say of the clause that deals with the protection of data.
