Building societies face B&B bill.
The British companies in the building may have to pay a bill of more than £80 million to cover the rescue of the bank Bradford & Bingley.
The government has provided £14 billion to protect the deposits of 2.6 million Bradford & Bingleys savers.
The interests of this loan will be paid by all the companies that collect money from savers, including 59 societies of the building.
The Director General of Building Societies Association (BSA), Adrian Coles, said that it is "irritating" to know that companies and their members will have to pay the piper...
The loan of £14 billion will be repaid when Bradford & Bingleys' mortgages are redeemed.
But the interest that will increase at the same time, will be debited, each year, to the 700 financial companies that collect deposits.
The financial services compensation scheme has confirmed to the BBC, that the 59 building companies are included in this list.
It is irritating to see that the institutions that had a cautious behavior… must now pay some bills of institutions that were much less cautious.
Adrian Coles, BSA
It is proclaimed that each company must pay an amount proportionate to the deposits that it holds, and that intermediary companies must pay around 18% of the cost.
The Treasury evaluates that the interests of the loan will amount in 2009 to £450 million.
This means that companies will have to find £81 million to pay the first year interests.
Adrian Coles, CEO of the commercial committee of construction companies, told the BBC that this decision seemed unfair to him.
It is "irritating" to see that the institutions which had a cautious behaviour at the recovery of the real estate market, must now pay for the much less careful institutions.
According to BSA, no society failed since 1945, date of the first record.
"We should examine all aspects of this affair during the coming weeks to assess the options to avoid that the building societies and their members pay this bill balloon," declared Mr Cole.
The interests for 2009 span seven months from the end of September of this year until the end of March.
In 2010, one will have to pay the interests of the whole year, which could beside double.
Given that the building societies are organizations without shareholder, their members end up paying the bill either by higher annual charge or by lower interest rates for savings accounts.
