A dark street in the city, often forgotten, and maybe soon for sale.
New York has hundreds of avenues, boulevards, streets and other parallel roads, some famous, others merely functional.
And even some old taxi drivers and long-time local residents cannot provide information to go to Extra Place, because they have never heard of it.
The street is located in the East Village and wanders through the north of First Street- not to be confused with Second Street- between Bowery and Second Avenue.
About 30 feet wide and 120 long, it looks like a dusty alley rather than an active road.
No sign indicates the street.
It is virtually impossible to find it on a standard atlas.
This street however has fans.
For example, there is Avalon Bay, the manufacturer of the recent luxury buildings on First Street.
He would like to repave Extra Place, and create a more fluid passage toward the stores and shops, which should open in the new buildings.
Other admirers, including long-time neighbours, have said to be charmed by this short-cut simply because it is one of the last and oldest streets of the block of houses.
But the Department of Real Estate Conservation and Development of the city that manages the street, has no interest in keeping it.
This month, at a meeting of the neighborhood owners committees, representatives from the city agency and from Avalon Bay outlined a proposal authorizing the building contractor to buy the street.
But the committee prefers that the street remains in city's hands, and asked a new proposal to make next month, said Susan Stetzer, local manager of Committee No. 3.
"There are only a few places left that belong to the city, and we would like the city to preserve Extra Place," she said.
"They could offer to renovate and manage it, which Avalon could also do, but we want to maintain it publically."
Avalon Bay announced several months ago that it wanted to repave the little street and install seating there, some would also be used by a cafe for which the builder will grant space.
The proposal of this potential acquisition was made public at this month's meeting.
Michele of Milly, the spokesperson of Avalon Bay, declared that although the company intends to exploit the street, this does not necessarily mean that it wants to be its owner.
"The main interest of Avalon Bay is to reconsider this abandoned avenue and make it public," she said, stressing that it was up to the city to suggest the sale."
Seth Donlin, a spokesman for the Preservation of Property, confirmed that the city really wanted to sell the street, also stressing that the agency's mission was to develop the property rather than to manage it.
Compared to its more colourful neighbour, Bowery, Extra Place has left a slight mark on history.
Some believe that Extra Place bears this name since 1802, since the estate of the big farm owned by Philip Minthorne's many children was split, leaving aside this small peace of land, wich is still abandoned.
The rear entrance of the CBGB, a punk rock monument closed in 2006, has reopen at Extra Place; the street is certainly more famous thanks to the cover photo of the album of Ramones "Rocket to Russia"
"This place was magnificent," said Danny Fields, the manager of Ramones, who took the photograph in November 1976.
It was full of scrap metal, rags, barrels, posters, leaves and strings."
Some residents, including the bloggers who had already spoken about the gentrification of the East Village, opposed the idea of selling Extra Place, saying that this humble, little property should remain public.
Others have announced Extra Place as a true rarity- a part virtually identical to the city that should be left in peace.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled "The Book of Lamentations: A Bitterly Nostalgic Look At a City in the Process of Extinction") describes the history of the City and Extra Place, published in 1952 in the New Yorker.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a small and narrow cul-de-sac, it was dark day and night, the boundaries were done by the rusted doors of a warehouse and some shutters, full of weeks old newspapers which are blowing away along the gutters."
With few exceptions, the street has still the same appearance.
A rat runs agiley down the back alley, in front of a door that was once the CBGB, which has now become the headquarters of a chic clothing store.
Graffiti on the walls, an empty 22-ounce bottle of beer lies next to some newspapers that have just been thrown out.
A few passers-by said they only rarely thought about Extra Palce, and suggested its enhancement.
For his part, Mr Field said he thought some people underestimated the attractiveness of the street in its current state.
"The best years of my life," he declared, "took place in dark, wet and disgusting places".
The Bilingual Debate: Immersion in the English language.
In this part of the programme of Supervision of Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the stance of the candidates about the bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a former member of studies in California, and former director of the Department of Education in the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book "not as good as you thought: why the middle classes should be able to choose their school."
Winning over Hispanic voters is a complex business.
The proposals of Barack Obama on education are an interesting example.
The campaign of Mr Obama points out that " African-American and Latino students have less chances of getting a degree than white students." It is true.
To fight these differences, the education programme of Mr Obama supports especially, among many other subjects, "the bilingual transitional education" for those who learn English.
However, the question for Obama is whether his desire to establish bilingual education which defends the teaching in class of languages other than English goes beyond his interest in eliminating the differences.
Take for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school of the east of the Los Angeles County.
The students from this school are largely Hispanic, and with low income.
More than one-third of students, comprising many new arrivals, is studying English.
Of the CM1 students, 100% passed the State math exam in 2008, at the expert level.
Similarly, almost 93% of the students took the english language art exam
This incredible success was achieved through another ingredient than the one proposed by Mr Obama.
Sixth Street bets on analyses, experience, a constant skills  assessment as well as an exemplary attitude.
In addition, and this is an example that Mr Obama could copy, reported Linda Mikels, Principal of Sixth Street Prep, this school has introduced the instruction of the English language using the "immersion" method.
The full immersion in English  focuses on the almost constant use of English in education.
Ms. Mikels, opponent of the bilingual education, has declared "we have had a tremendous success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico, 12 months later, if you go to his class, you would have had no chance to identify him."
"This works, she notices, "it worked for us"
Mr Obama should not take the example of the Sixth Street Prep and repeat it in other schools composed mainly of Hispanic students learning English.
The excellent results achieved by this school speak for themselves; but the education policies within his party (the National Education Association has for a long time supported bilingual education) and his enormous support for bilingual education makes it difficult to predict Mr. Obama's response.
Although he is in favor of immigrants learning English, Mr. Obama recently seemed to consider this issue insignificant, when he proclaimed that we all need to stop ranting about drafting laws regarding the English language.
"Instead, he said, 'You must make sure that your child speaks Spanish".
If Mr. Obama really wants to eliminate the differences, he should carefully consider the education models that work, rather than disdaining them or considering them insignificant.
