Rested Gebrselassie surpasses his world record.
Haile Gebrselassie, of Ethiopia, has once again proved to be worthy of his title as best long-distance athlete of the century, having beaten his own world record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday, when he became the first to run 26,2 miles in less than 2 hours and 4minutes.
With a victory in 2: 03: 59 in a race accommodatingly flat, Gebrselassie beat by 27 seconds his record of 2: 04: 26, played last year in Berlin.
At 35 years old, Gebrselassie won the 26th world record of his successful career during which he won the World championship or the world record for any distance, from 1600 metres to marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie had missed the Olympic marathon in Beijing, fearing - maybe in an exaggerated way from today's point of view - that the air pollution would increase his problems of asthma.
Instead, he promised to run in Berlin.
Under almost perfect conditions - sunny weather, 48 degrees at the start, 55 at the finish - Gebrselassie won Sunday, with an impressive average of 4 minutes, 43 seconds per mile.
Trail runners such as Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat, both Kenyan, converted to long-distance runners, contributed to the reduction of the marathon's record time by more than two minutes in the past ten years since 1998, when the Brazilian Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin in 2:06:05.
After the victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the reporters having suffered from cramps in the calf two weeks before, and having missed training for a week.
It's clear that the rest let him stay brilliant, but not rusted.
"I am so happy," he declared to reporters.
"Everything was perfect.
I got back to it last week, and today, I had my doubts; but in the end, everything has gone for the better."
He was reproached- especially in Kenya, the East-African rival of Ethiopia- for having overly orchestrated his races by avoiding the stars of the marathon world, relying on the pacesetters as if they were in a track competition, and valuing world records more than the sense of competition.
But this criticism is not diminishing Gebrselassie high capabilities as a runner.
On Sunday Gebrselassie, preceded by four Kenyans, recorded a time of 1:02:04 halfway.
Two elite Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles kamathi continued to defy Gebrselassie after the front of the field had disappeared.
At a little more than three miles from the finish, Gebrselassie made his final push to get away from Kwambai, who finished second in 2: 05: 36, improving on his personal best record of five minutes.
Kamathis arrived third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, born in Kazakhstan, now a German citizen, ended a remarkable year, achieving the seventh best time ever with a time of 2:19:19.
The English Paula Radcliffe holds the world record of 2:15:25.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko surprised everyone by winning the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She could not participate in the Beijing Games because of potential harm to her back, but promised to win in Berlin, improving on her third marathon, her personal best of under five minutes.
She ran using a clever strategy, letting the group of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners take a substantial lead, then passing them about 18½ miles later.
Askale Tafa Margasa from Ethiopia came second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop, Kenyan, finished third in 2:25:01.
In a City apart, Pride and the hardships of Black Life
Hidden in the development of its great park, from a few miles of the sunny, shiny and gigantic Orlando, there is a quiet town, where are born the pride and the complications of the African-American experience.
"Eatonville, the first entirely black city to integrate, childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston," this description that she wrote in 1935, is not so simple these days. "The city with five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 dark skins, 300 good swimmers, lots of guava, two schools and no prison."
It has now become a city of pilgrimage
Alice Walker, Tony Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the Zora festival that takes place each year at Eatonville to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And in different ways, the city that she describes - has become a landmark thanks to its inclusion in the tourist guide to Florida published by The Depression- era Federal Writers' Project- remains a place apart.
It is as independent, dignified, and private than it was already in the 1930s, when Hurston said that the black rural population of Florida was often reluctant to share its true thoughts with the white man, who "knowing us so little, does not know what he loses."
Even if it is the election year of a black president, Senator Barack Obama, who has invoked an open dialogue on the subject of race, many here remain wary of the view from abroad.
"We are very careful about how to tell the story," said Hortense Jones, 59, a longlife resident and the city's oldest parishioner.
"It must be in line with reality.
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and fighting.
It is both a historic model of a takeover from black people and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
This is a central point but also an example of rural black southist culture - once scorned, other times acclaimed - reminiscent of the birth of slavery in America.
Which would explain why residents are both proud and protective.
The interest in the image of Eatonville which started with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She presented her home-town worldwide through sincere, full of dialect books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the guide to  Florida transform this city, located right on the exit of Route 17, a road that runs through the centre of Florida, often forgotten, which leads to a chapter of Black history and the human tragedy.
Bold as a bass drum in life as in literature, Hurston led readers to the store property of the first mayor of Eatonville, Mr. Joe Clarke, which was then divided into several private parts.
"go past the road on the left" she wrote, "you will find the modern brown and white public school, with its  ordered gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller has always taken care of, although he can barely read and write.
She mentionned also Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells any kind of drinks and everything that can serve coming people.
So, in scarcely about one hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with a self government but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Of course, Fodor was not this way.
This was not actually a portrait that everyone appreciated.
Zora has described the reality well" said Ella Dinkins, 90 years old, one of the young girls of Johnson that Hurston has immortalised, cited in the songs without colour, interpreted by men who have recognised their beauty."
She added: "Some people did not appreciate."
You always remember Hurston as a living and eccentric person, who was frequently coming back after his family had moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that Hurston usually arrived in town without warning, in a big Chevrolet, with a cigarette in her mouth and wearing slacks, here where, even today, we are proud of traditional clothing.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr Franklin said, while many were laughing at her.
"People were always happy to see Zora" he said.
But he adds further, swinging in his chair of the back patio which got a view on Sabelia Lake, where Hurston was certainly baptised, "she never stayed too long."
On the death of Hurston in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of production.
Eatonville and the whole world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was a star in the field of literature, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an ordinary grave in Fort Pearce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville, no great celebration, and no commemorative plaque for the public.
I do not think that they understood the contribution or the legacy that she left to the world," said Valérie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A crucial moment occured in the 1980s.
Orange County public officials want to build a five-lane highway downtown to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's two-lane main street.
The development of Orlando has already extended Interstate 4 until the west angle of the city.
The proposal was made while Eatonville was just recovering from a difficult period of its history.
A forced integration, among many other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the dispute about the mix of races have led hatred to the doors of the community.
"At this time, a bunch of young caucasians came to throw oranges or objects on the people sitting on the side" said Mr Franklin.
"A woman even died."
They threw a watermelon from their car."
In a letter from 1955 addressed to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston casts doubt on the request of the Supreme Court aimed at forced integration, characterizing its decision in Brown v. Board of Education as "insulting rather than glorifying for my race."
Residents now proclaim that the elimination of racial segregation in schools, although positive in some respects, has diluted the cohesion of Eatonville and has weakened the confidence of the young.
"Black children were used to be kissed - I remember well - we kissed our master in the morning, and in the evening too," said N.Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins' daughter as well as head of community of Eatonville safeguarding, a non-profit group.
That lasted, she added, till the time when the teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You do not kiss your white teacher because he is white - I mean that there is here, a cultural line of demarcation," Ms. Nathiri said.
The civil rights movement, moreover, helped make room for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who moved beyond prejudice, as she did, armed with cheerful confidence and personal mottoes such as: "How can they deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company!"
It is beyond me. "
In 1975, the writer Alice Walker went on the anonymous Hurston grave and began to struggle to revive his reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography on Hurston carried out by Robert E. Hemenway, a real best seller, reintroduced her to the American cannons in that way.
The project of the motorway arrived just when the most famous girl of Eatonville had found her appeal back.
And this time, the old neighbours of Hurston regard her as a savior.
The community has begun to organize a Hurston festival to demonstrate the catastrophic consequences this highway would engender.
Hundreds of fans came to the inauguration of the festival two years after, and many are returning in January, to celebrate it.
After many years, the county rejected the proposal of the motorway.
"The fiasco of the motorway with five lanes, very fast, a real civique pride" said Miss. Nathiri.
Ms Boyd summed up everything declaring that "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the motorway project allowed him to change his own image.
Non residents, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has come to our church since 1993, began to come in large numbers, and residents were beginning to reconsider the past.
Eatonville is classified historic town since 1998.
A single-subject library (renamed Hurston, of course) opened in 2006, on the magnificent, repaved Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly in Florida: six miles from Orlando, it feels at all times like an old-fashioned back street on a rainy summer day, small as it was when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1800s.
(there are today 90 percent of blacks)
Foreigners who come to discover Eatonville's history, its raison d'être, are still treated with caution.
We must ask permission for most of the interviews, and some things - such as the walls of Eatonville's old church, painted by the white men, illustrating black men in the fields - should not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms Jones, a courageous teacher with a soft spot for bright red, are still afraid that their insular community is not well understood.
However, given the festival Hurston expansion, a certain level of local pride appeared.
The young in particular, tend to view Eatonville the way Hurston viewed her entire race: beautiful, problematic, neither better nor worse, but proud, creative, hardworking, crazy and mixed, just like the other ethnic and racial groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection we hear in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who expects to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or for the police force, which needs additional personnel.
And even the youngest, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have correctly learned the description of Eatonville.
"Most people passing through that area will think: 'Oh, this city has nothing, compared to others' Alondra Kenon said after Mass last Sunday.
But if you stop and take time to contemplate history is a very beautiful city. "
Here in New York, all speak fluent finance.
Still, nothing has changed.
If the tourists in Manhattan stayed far away from the newsstand and the giant television screens in Times Square, they would not realize that they are in the eye of the cyclone.
They never would believe believe that, in the glass-enclosed beehive of offices above their heads, the bankers and hedge fund managers who rule New York are experiencing "the worst office workday" since the Crash of 1929.
Delivery men continue to slip on the pavements, with their trolleys and their shelves of muffins for morning meetings.
The Latinos still drag themselves along between the residential buildings, like mules, with about 50 fancy shirts hung from yokes on their shoulders.
Office workers continues to be queuing up to buy their morning sandwich from retailers, and it is always impossible to find a taxi between 4PM and 7PM in week.
I had not felt the crisis despite the completely pessimistic stories until this afternoon when I decided to go open a new savings account.
Fortunately I had planned to work in the late afternoon, because I discovered at my local branch of JP Morgan Chase, about twenty people queuing.
Neither in front of the cashiers' windows nor to withdraw cash or to make a deposit, but before the customer service window, there where the usual customers ordered their checkbooks, tourists requested the directions for the Macy store, and new customers opened accounts.
Most of those in front of me, I would learned that later from Starr, my "personal allowed banker ", were all queuing up for the same reason as me.
Not in the same way, because they had already withdrawn their economies from the smallest banks, such as those of New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They have withdrawn their money from the savings accounts of called thrifts (such as a building society), credit unions, and the kind of local savings banks and their subsidiaries which only function in a state, and which say they are treating their customers like their family.
In a recent past, 15 of these banks have gone bankrupt.
These days, Washington Mutual, a bank with capital of $327 million went into trusteeship, and while New Yorkers were returning home for the weekend on Friday evening, another bank, Wachovia, with savings accounts of a value of $440 million, desperately searched for a buyer to save it.
The office and shop attendants who stands in front me, fearful of another potential collapse have transferred their money to a bank that seems more reliable to them, the one which made most of bailouts in Wall Street.
The ordinary New Yorkers have become very familiar to the world of finance in the last weeks.
"I heard a woman in my local Chinese supermarket, speaking on the telephone about Lehman Brothers, the bank that just bankrupted, and his meagre CEO Dick Fuld, with the same familiarity that she could have to criticise a colleague.
And Lyn, the doorman in uniform of my building, has changed the subject of our usual conversation about Brad and Angelina or the shipments of my fruit and vegetable merchant.
She said to me, after my visit to the bank, "I put all my savings in the monetary fund market.
"I have changed, I do not want to take risks".
Desecrated Muslim graves, while Austria oscillates toward the right.
Heinz-Christian Strache, who abandoned the right-wing of the Austrian Freedom Party, and Filip Dewinter, from the Belgian-right Vlaams Belang, are taking part in a demonstration for the organization of "Cities Against Islamization" in Antwerp, on Thursday, January 17th, 2008.
They carry road signs showing mosques crossed out in red.
The police accuse the far-right extremists of having desecrated an Austrian Muslim cemetery, the weekend of the far-right political parties' victory in the country's general elections.
More than 90 graves were severely damaged at the cemetery of Traun, near Linz, between Friday night and this morning; it is, according to the police, an organized action.
The offenders painted on several graves, Jewish symbols such as the Star of David; the detectives think however that that could have been done to disguise the extremists' feeling of hatred towards Muslim immigrants.
This accident could be somehow linked to the elections.
A spokesperson of the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" at the announcement of this desecration, which occurs right during the religious month of Ramadan which nears its end.
Austria think seriously about to get its courage back, following its oscillation towards the right at the parliamentary election yesterday.
The two right-wing parties that have won almost 30 percent of votes, the Freedom Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, led a anti- immigration campaign. Some of their slogans were even seen, according to critics, as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Freedom Party who won more than 18 percent of the votes, launched his campaign against wearing headscarves and burkas, and has even expressed his opposition to the food halal.
During his final race in Vienna, he spoke of "a European brotherhood" to prevent the rise of Islam.
The two parties try to prevent the construction of mosques and minarets, declaring that they would be a political symbol of the Islamization of Austria and Europe.
The polls and the analyses carried out just after the elections, have defined the extreme right as the most powerful political bloc of  the country, which is demonstrated by the majority of young voters who made the difference, as anxious about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter forbidden to travel abroad.
The courts have banned the glamour rock star, Gary Glitter, accused of sexual abuse on children, of expatriation in France and Spain.
The magistrates imposed a ban on Glitter six months after he had expressed to the officials in charge his intention to travel to Spain from France.
Police in Kent had established the travel ban last Thursday after having proved to the judges Glitter's culpability of child sexual abuse.
Glitter, or, to use his real name, Paul Gadd, was not present at the hearing before the court of limited jurisdiction in Ashford, but was still represented by his law firm, Corker Binning.
A court spokesman said, "Thursday, 25 September at the Ashford court, police in Kent has asked for an application to prevent Mr Paul Gadd to travel in France and Spain until March 25.
"Paul Gadd was not present".
Glitter, 64ans, has informed the authorities that he wanted to go abroad, even if he has to be recorded in the lists of people accused of sexual abuses.
He must inform the authorities if he wants to go abroad for more than three days.
He must also inform the police, 7 days before his departure date.
If he does not announce his movements to the authorities, it could face a sentence of up to five years imprisonment.
The Kent police has declared that they will not discuss individual cases nor any potential Glitter displacement in the county.
A spokesman of the police of Kent has said "the police of Kent will do everything necessary to protect our children as well as those from abroad.
"We believe it is easier to monitor someone who remains in the United Kingdom because we have devices capable of managing any potential risks much more efficiently".
"to protect the people of Kent is the most important thing to the Kent police, and we are closely monitoring the behaviour of those who are accused of sexual abuse in the region, in order to minimise the potential risks to the public."
Glitter returned to the United Kingdom last month, having spent 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for having abused two little girls, respectively 10 and 11 years old.
When he was released, Glitter took a flight to Bangkok from where he should have boarded on a flight to London.
But he said not to be feeling well, and refused to head to London.
The Thai authorities stopped him at the passport control checkpoint, and at the end, he went to Hong Kong.
The Chinese authorities have refused him entry into their territory, and so was forced to return to Bangkok; Thai police and immigration officers have insisted that he goes back to England.
He finally arrived at Terminal 3 at Heathrow Airport on August 22nd, and remained there while his lawyer, David Corker, went to court of limited jurisdiction in Uxbridge, West London, to register on the list of people accused of sexual abuse, as required by Scotland Yard.
In the past, Glitter had already served a sentence of four months in the United Kingdom, for possession of child abuse pictures.
A source of the Interior Ministry said that Jacqui Smith, the minister of the Interior has been reassured and happy to know that Glitter had been forbidden to travel in France and Spain.
"I photograph the master out of the stage to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer.
Neither heels, nor carol clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tension to get the relaxed look of the man or the woman.
On one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in privacy, in these times, unknown to the public, where we discover intimate gestures and stolen looks of artists who do not care about getting up on stage.
In Flamenco - People, German Günther Bauer mixes the theatricality of some stage sets including singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming for the Month of the Flemish Photograph, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day," explains the creator, clarifying that "Flamenco - People"..."it can be any of them, but after having seen the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists able to transmit on stage the passion, the sadness, the joy... in captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists one should not take photographs on stage.
They have unique personalities and character.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere, which would allow me to catch with the camera some personal moments of the flamenco stars."
With the festival called "Chant Populaire des Mines" in 1997, Bauer began a long trip to photograph singers, guitarists and dancers with a camera that used photographic plates.
These are portraits, which, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, call to mind classic photography.
The implementation of various styles breaks away from the classical  image,by giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception  of the flamenco, according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that is changing and that surprises every day."
It is not dancing nor singing itself, but the personality and the character of the artist which captivate the public with his art.
The search for essence and for magic has been the constant in the work they are presenting nowadays here in the gallery El Fotómata.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from around 70 artists photographed.
The project has turned into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a album of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits has led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people," the photographer admits that he loves photographing the portrait of people, getting to know them and being able to enter their life for moment more or less.
I believe that in photography, portrait is the most difficult.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that you sometimes do not know or who only give you a few minutes to make a photograph of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try that my ideas become reality".
This collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco dancers  entitled "Flamenco-people", is on show at the El Fotómata gallery, located at 20 Mata Street (the streer parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule) through next 16 October.
Vargas Llosa confesses that the novel he is writing is "real courage."
The novel takes place in places that no one knows and deals with unfamiliar subjects, but once again, Mario Vargas Llosa is determined to move forward with the new project he is working on, a novel whose main character, Roger Casemant, an Irish nationalist who lived for twenty years in the Congo and traveled through the Amazon.
The favorite to win the Nobel Prize in Literature confessed yesterday at the Hay Festival Segovia, that the novel which is currently keeping him busy "is very daring" and that "all shows that he should not write it."
"If I was reasonable, I would not do it, but I will do so and I hope to finish it," – he concluded in his speech at the festival of exchange of ideas and thoughts that for four days saw in the city of the aqueduct  hundreds of writers, of historians and journalists and thousands of people.
The author of "the city and the dogs' was the most awaited person of the third edition of the festival and has fulfilled its contract.
Vargas Llosa, who won the Hay Festival prize by a majority vote of the participants, had attracted a full house in the Juan Bravo theater.
The host of the festival, Felix Romeo, has been faced with a public fascination that has not been seen since the last time during which the Peruvian, with a phenomenal memory and with a large dose of humour, has described the birth of his literary career, which is due to "his desire to read" and "to Live from New experiences"; how he wrote "a very methodical way" thanks to the hard work of documentation, correcting and rewriting a part of the text to face its "lack of inspiration"; how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas have influenced his vocation, and how his memories inspire his novels.
The hispanic-american novelist acknowledged that "there is no way" to measure and whether books can change life. "but I refuse to believe that literature is pure amusment, a fleeting experience" said Vargas Llosa, who underlined that it "has an effect" and "makes people less similar" because it demands that writers  "do not to stoop to the frivolity" and live up to their vocation.
The bad weather spoils the Pozoblanco fair.
The festival of banderillas which concluded the Pozoblanco fair's bull races was suspended yesterday morning after the mounted toréadors had verified that the arena was unworkable.
In this way, the organizing committee, in agreement with Fermín Bohórquez, Pablo Hermoso de Mendoza and Leonard Hernández, has decided to suspend the celebration of the race of the bulls.
The bad weather has been hard on this circus, as two carnivals out of three could not take place.
On Saturday, it's the rain that prevented the planned celebration of the second bull race.
On the poster, were José Luis Moreno, Curro Díaz and Juan Bautista, who would have had to come face to face with one another in the arena in Castilblanco.
Thus, only the festival on Friday took place
On Friday, the winner was Daniel Luque who cut off three ears and who was carried aloft in triumph, after having made tasteful, graceful arms gestures to the bull.
The afternoon even Alejandro Talavante concluded on two banderillas planted on the back from the bull and a cut ear that the steps discovered applauded more than its combat in itself with the bull.
Even worse for El Juli, who entered the arenas of Los Llanos without pain or glory.
For his fight with the second bull, after a much better fight, he got booed by most of the public.
Inspection by police of a van in the province of Alava: two thousand kilos of hashish found
Ten minutes to five in the morning.
Traffic control by the police of Euskadi (Ertzaintza) at the border of the town of Armiñón (Alava).
The policemen stop two occupants of a van and these last two run away.
Its cargo, more than two tons of hashish, enough to arrest them.
The police followed them and have arrested one of the two occupants, a 28-year-old man, identified as A.A.J., according to information disclosed by the Department for the Interior of the Basque government.
The person arrested was accused of drug trafficking and falsification of documents.
The incident took place when various officials from the Traffic Unit of Alava performed vehicle inspections on the N-1, at the border of the town of Armiñón.
They were about to stop a van to inspect it when the driver disobeyed orders and suddenly accelerated, and then the inspection began.
The policemen began their pursuit until the vehicle stopped two miles further on the slow lane, where the two occupants got off to flee in a forested area.
The Basque police have finally arrested one of the two occupants and have seized the 2,178 kilograms of hashish that they were carrying and which they found after having inspected the van, an Iveco Daily.
The rear part of the car was loaded with haschich bundles. Then, they proceeded to its transfer to a police station to do complete inspection and weigh the drug
Moreover, officials noted that the license plate had been "falsified" because it did not coincide with what was written on the van's grey card, that is also why they have charged the detainee with the crime of falsification of documents.
The Ertzaintza continues the investigation to stop the other suspect, who has managed to escape and to determine the origin of the seized drug.
The detainee, A. A. J., 28 years old, has been placed in custody for the various steps and will be judged in the following hours.
Actress Heather Locklear arrested for driving under the effect of a drug
The actress Heather Locklear, the famous Amanda in the TV series Melrose Place, was arrested this weekend at Santa Barbara (California) for driving under the influence on medication.
A witness viewed her doing strange maneuvers trying to get out of her garage to Montecito, according to what a spokesman of California's police patrol told to People magazine.
The witness said that around 4.30 p.m., Locklear "pressed down on the accelerator, making a lot of noise, and in going backwards several times while trying to get the car out of the garage, it rolled over his sunglasses."
Shortly after, the witness, who earlier had not recognized the actress, saw that Locklear stopped in the middle of the highway and got out of her vehicle.
This person, at this moment, called the emergency services because "she was concerned about Locklear's life."
When the police patrol arrived it found the actress sat inside her vehicle, which was partially blocking the road.
"She looked disoriented," which is why agents led her to the specialist centre in drugs and alcohol for a test.
According to a spokesman for the police, the actress was cooperative and alcohol abuse was discounted from the beginning, although "according to the observation of police officers at first sight, we thought that Locklear was under the influence of a drug."
Locklear has been arrested having been suspected of driving under the influence of a substance that has not been specified, and has been imprisoned around 19.00 hours and released a few hours later.
Two months ago, Locklear came out of the clinic in Arizona where she was interned for care after a nervous breakdown.
Llamazares has asked the Andalusian federation of the United Left to assume its responsibilities in the Silva case
The general coordinator, deputy of the Gauche Unie, Gaspar Llamazares, said today that the regional federation should take a decision on the former advisor to Youth and Sports of the city of Seville, Francisco Manuel Silva, who resigned last week after being accused of having special treatment to the members of his family.
"In these cases, I am really federalist, and the Andalusian organisation will have to shoulder its responsibilities by itself" said Llamazares regarding the political party's conduct that it will adopt in Seville's city council.
However, the leader of the United Left has requested that the investigations show proof of "transparency" for the irregularities that Silva could have committed, "The United Left has always defended this kind of case that has a maximum degree of transparency".
He also stressed that the political party has "very strict ethical codes for all officials."
"Sangre de Mayo," Garci's gamble
Based on Benito Pérez Galdós' stories, José Luis Garci recreates the famous battle of the Spanish against the French in "Sangre Mayo," which is the most ambitious film of his filmography with nearly 15 million budget.
The filmmaker has tried "to stage the many characters and to illustrate the social analysis," that he has always admired in the implementation of the famous novelist, he explained today during the presentation of the film, with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría at the head of the long list of players.
The film "Sangre Mayo" that lasts more than two-and-a-half hours will be released in cinemas next Friday and will then become a TV series of more than four hours for Telemadrid.
Big fan of the literature of Galdós, José Luis Garci asserts that with this filming he has accomplished "a child's dream" thanks to Esperanza Aguirre, who asked him,  three years ago, to film a commemorative film for the two hundred years of the 2nd May madrilene, something he has always accepted when the narrative stuck to the historical facts.
The 15 million Euros provided by the municipality of Madrid are for Garci "a unique opportunity" to reproduce with the appropriate decors and clothing the atmosphere of "a Spain which chose the wrong leader for the battle, since the fight for independence led the people to rebellion under the reign of Ferdinand VII," he pointed out.
But the filmmaker regrets not having secured as much funding as he did for the films "Captain Alatriste" and "Goya's Ghosts" – more than double that secured for "Sangre de Mayo" – because he was not able to film a few of the scenes in the script written by Horacio Valcárcel, with whom he has collaborated for almost his entire career.
The director of "Volver a Empezar" has influenced his usual way of working, his staging of the actors, with whom he rehearses before filming, and his doing no casting, since that seems "humiliating" to him and he believes that "the role of the director is to go to the theater and to movies to keep himself informed."
Many actors in "Sangre Mayo" rehearse in front of the camera, like Miguel rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Nominated four times for an Oscar (he has won one), Garci believes that the three films that represent Spain this year before the Hollywood Academy, "Sangre de Mayo," "Sept Tables de Billard Français" and finally, the winner, "Les Tournesols Aveugles," are not representative of the young Spanish cinema, "which deserves to be better known," he said.
Garci does not expect a prize from this film.
"At the beginning you believe you are working for posterity, then you realize you are working for prosperity, and now you are happy just to make one film more," explains Garci after more than 30 years of a professional career.
Isabelle Bayón gets into the skin of Seville dancer Tórtola Valencia
One Sevillian dancer will pay tribute to another Sevillian dancer.
Carmen tórtola Valencia, daughter of a Catalan father (florenç tórtola Ferrer) and an Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the District of Triana and at the age of three years went on living in London with her family.
She was a dance free dancer and expert in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life as a pioneer of the liberation of women, as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was vegetarian and Buddhist, and advocated the abolition of the corset which forbade the free movement of women.
The life of this woman who left her mark in the history of dance in Europe between the two World Wars has fascinated Isabelle Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she offered me to interpret the Seville dancer Tórtola Valencia, and it seemed unbelievable to me".
According to the dancer, "we're not trying to tell his life but to bring his thinking.
The titles of his dances made me think about flamenco.
Thus, "the dance of the butterfly" reminded me of a popular Cuban dance and "the dance of the snake" of some tangos.
Her dancing was sensual and they told me that my way of dance was similar to hers", she says.
The staging is thanks to two outstanding contributions: Miguel Poveda who will sing once more Isabela in one of his performances, as he had done at "The puerto abierta"; and that of the professor Matilde Coral, who was unusually willing to colaborate with the one that was her pupil.
"Matilde transforms Tórtola into a mature character.
I am pleased because she has agreed to play a role in my work and it honors me. "
The staging is also due to the musical compositions and to the guitars of Jesús Torres y Paco Arriaga, to the folk song of Michael Ortega, el Pulga y Moi of Morón; to the percussion work of El Pájaro, as well as to the viola of Rafa El Viola and to the collaboration of an actor, Juanfra Juárez, "who plays the role of the long-time companion of the type of artists who were regarded as divas."
This work also tells, in a certain way, about the life of this woman who had exhibitions in such faraway places, especially for the time, as India, the United States, and Russia, but also throughout Europe, since she usually lived in London.
"I wanted to memorialize her because I believe that it is women who have an enormous influence in their time and nowadays, no one knows and values her body of work," affirms Bayón.
The show will begin at 8:30 p.m. at the Lope de Vega Theatre
The publication of "Diary of a recently married poet" concludes the Triennat
The presentation of the first illustrated edition of "Diary of a Recently Married Poet " in the church of St. Stephen' in New York, where Juan Ramón Jiménez was married to Zenobia in March, 1916, is part of activities planned by the Ministry of Culture of Andalusia, to celebrate the "triennium of Zenobia and Juan Ramón '(2006-2008), held to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the concession of the Nobel Prize for literature and their deaths.
In this way, the "Triennat Zenobia and Juan Ramón" is coming to its end with the republishing of this work with, the International Congress that took place in New York, with the restoration of the Nobel Museum and with the touring exhibition « Juan Ramón Jiménez: this poplar of light » who was inaugurated in May last year and who, after having travelled across various Andalucian province, will go to New York at the International Conference.
Similarly, the Ministry of Culture of Andalusia bought eight hundred copies of "Diary of a recently married poet", published by Pedro Tabernero and illustrated by Jacobo Pérez-Enciso to perpetuate the work of one of the most famous Andalusian poets.
America pleases less without Paul Newman
"Sometimes God creates perfect people
Paul Newman was a part of it. "
This sentence is from actress Sally Field, who has worked with him in "Lack of Mischief" and clearly illustrates the despair of the American cinema, and the whole of America, with the striking idea that Newman is not part of this world anymore.
He had a hard time getting an Oscar
He was no longer acting since 2007.
Everyone knew that he was ill.
It was a blow to everyone.
"Sometimes what one feels exceeds any expression, and now I have lost a great friend," Robert Redford began crying, 'my life and my country were better, thanks to his existence ".
No one was afraid to get ridiculous or to exaggerate.
One of the fathers of cinema and the country died during a particularly dark time, when terrorists and stock markets are frightening, the Americans' self-esteem has fallen very low, while desperately searching for reasons of dignity.
When times are so tough and without reason to live, only admiration is left to human beings and it is not necesseary to be Luis Cernuda to like Paul Newman.
It was for everyone an ideal of beauty and truth.
He was an enemy of Richard Nixon and a defender of lost and defeated causes, like the foundation to fight drugs created in honor of his older brother who died from an overdose and the creation of his own brand of organic food.
This was a victory for a country which has been struggling to assert itself against a suicidal food culture.
This expanding wave of admiration swept across Hollywood without caring about the nationalities or the passports.
The latest James Bond, Englishman Daniel Craig, has ascertained that no James Bond has died before him.
Another Englishman, the Oscar-winning Sam Mendes, said that work with Newman marked the pinnacle of his career.
The bad boy coming from Australia, Russell Crowe, dared to name Newman as his greatest inspiration.
"He set a high standard for us", noted George Clooney, who is perhaps the only person today who tries to break though onto the screen as did Paul Newman: by being very honest and having a serious private life away from the camera lenses.
It is still not easy or possible in the media jungle nowadays.
But there is he who tries, and Paul Newman is one example.
After a divorce, he was married for fifty years to Joanne Woodward, to whom he was faithful even though he did not lack for opportunities not to be.
"But why should I eat a hamburger outside my home, if I have a beef in my fridge?", he used to joke.
In the sky, he proudly attends the his daughters' meeting with his fans on earth, something which is unusual in America.
"Among all major roles that he interpreted, he was very proud to be the providing husband, the father in love, the caring and philanthropist grandfather ," they say.
Madrid in the race for the organization of the 2016 Olympic Games
And yes, the dream of many of us is for Madrid to hold the Olympics, after the failure in 2012, it could come true in 2016.
But I wonder if we are ready.
If we take the example of yesterday's race: We are not!
They call it 'the perfect race', but to me, it was the worst race in which I have ever participated.
If they had taken into account any errors that occurred during the race, they would have received a pass mark.
But let us look at everything in detail and from the beginning.
The errors begin with the withdrawal of the jersey numbers, which force you to go ahead.
This is not bad, but if they make you move it would be better if they give you everything (including the electronic chip to shop).
Well no
They made you go there only to get the players' number (first mistake, traveling just for that) and (after a long queue) surprise!, there were only size S jerseys (second mistake, because I need a size XL).
In what world are we living?
Is it because of the economic crisis they have decided to buy only tiny tops with less fabric that are therefore cheaper?
Well, this is nothing compared to what happened the day of the races.
Apart from the fact that you have to go there very early to have the electronic chip taken out, the line is 15 minutes long and, what's more, you have to leave your knapsack at the entrance.
The wait lasted more than 35 minutes, which is incomprehensible since 11,000 people are expected for these races.
Since there was a long line, the competitions started and we still had  not left our knapsack at the entrance, although once that was done, getting it back was even worse.
Moreover, the rain has accompanied the wait of more than 40 minutes during which rebellions and assaults of the barrack took place.
I believe that about 500 people will have pneumonia tomorrow, and some people like me will not even be counted in the classification with the exact time, because I think the chip they gave me did not mark the beginning correctly.
Of course, if they were asking me to cite one example of perfect race, this one would certainly not come to my mind.
And I believe that we will always be able to dream of becoming the host city for the 2016 Olympic Games.
Microsoft is seeking a receptionist (virtual).
At the MIT Microsoft conference on emerging technologies, a new system of image recognition and human interaction has been presented; it's a kind of artificial intelligence, not very smart but able to perform a few basic tasks, such as calling a taxi (or in the Microsoft case, a shuttle to move around the company campus) in response to what it was asked during a talk.
Thanks to a movie camera and a system of recognition of forms and faces, this "receptionist" can know how many people there are in place, who they are - including remembering what positions they occupy - and listen and hear the keywords of their conversations.
But also to pool them according to conversation groups
In the presentation video, the receptionist detects a third person but she understands that she does not belong to the group that is speaking with her and that she is not part of the company.
She asks him if she is here to visit someone and she tells him that she will answer him shortly.
All this with no blue screen.
Impressive.
But of course this represents the future.
Now the company has other businesses to focus on, for example on the next version of its operating system, Windows.
This week we also discussed about a strategy change at Microsoft.
Windows 7 will be lighter and it will no longer have as many associated programmes.
Steve Ballmer found that if the computers were sold with the necessary instead of unnecessary applications, they would be five times faster.
This represents a discovery since Microsoft, version after version, has not stopped adding features and "extras" to Windows.
The strategy change is welcome.
Microsoft is right, its operational system loses importance, but so does its software.
When Google Chrome came to the network, I was one among those who joined the theory that Google Chrome was the first step for Google to compete with Windows.
Several people have rightly pointed out that a Web browser is not an operating system.
The operating system will always be necessary since it is the essential base for the hardware and software to understand each other.
It stands for your wife or husband whenever you have something to tell your mother-in-law.
It is true.
It will never disappear but we must see the "death" of the operating system not as an absolute truth, but as a relative truth.
Ballmer confirmed the idea this week.
People are less and less paying attention to the operating system but increasingly to the navigator.
We switch on the computer only to use Firefox, Explorer or Chrome and every day, people spend more time browsing the Internet than browsing windows.
To whom do half the applications submitted with the system serve?
He who can do more, can do less
And Windows 7 will contain fewer applications, much fewer than Vista.
Less heavy, less crowded, less complex.
For now, Microsoft is more interested in launching its own online services so that they ultimately become an alternative to Google.
They desperately need this, indeed, and I'll show you an example.
The picture in this article, was taken at the beginning of this month in one of the rest rooms reserved for Microsoft's employees, in Redmond.
On the distributor of drinks, a poster asks them to use their own search tool -- "Your research. Our future."
In 2006, a study concluded that 66% of Microsoft employees used Google to seek information on the Internet.
Last week a delay occurred in the new version of Windows Mobile 7.
It will not be released at the beginning of 2009 but towards the end of 2009 or even in 2010.
Microsoft will surely try to lauch on the market, at the same time Windows 7 and Windows Mobile 7.
The telephone, after all, resembles a computer more and more.
But the launch of Android being late and the iPhone being already on the market, this will be expensive for them.
The Stunning Marcel
Pablo Picasso wore it on the Côte d'Azur, Leonardo di Caprio wore one in Edward Zwick's "Blood Diamond," the same as Al Pacino in Francis Ford Coppola's "The Godfather" and it is part of the classic uniform for muscular gays.
And if we try to list all its appearances, it could also cite the strapping moustached which created the weight in a travelling circus.
It is not simply a men cotton undershirt, tight and sleeveless.
English people call it 'tank' but the stunning Marcel of Brussels stands out among all the others.
First, by his flamboyant name - although he is known by the name of "Marcel" - which has to do with sports because, according to legend, he took the name of boxer Marcel Cerdan, one of singer Edith Piaf's lovers.
The "Marcel" differs from others in its excellent cotton, it its single-sex cut, in its distinctive logo and in the small (barely recognizable) Belgian flag that these most well-known undershirts have at the neck.
But be careful, because the Belgian brand does not only produce tank tops.
But it also produces sweat-shirt, old fashioned boxers, cardigans in Kashmir, cotton trousers, babies, mini-shorts...
Clothes designed for the underwear comfort.
Even if it is a shame to wear them only as his underwear.
They have too much charm.
"I want to become a young mother; the candidate does not worry me"
Her huge resemblance to her sister has not prevented her to develop its own personality.
Monica Cruz is small, but full of vitality.
Currently the Cruz sisters take very seriously their new activity in fashion.
According to Monica, they are not only beautiful and famous girls who are lending their names.
She was present at the promotion the Mango brand has done in Paris at its new headquarters but also at the presentation of the most important fashion awards that the Spanish company sponsors.
Monica is warm and timid.
Tell us what you are doing in Paris.
I came to present the new collection that my sister Penélope and I created for Mango, for the new Fall/Winter season, as well as to attend the presentation of the second edition of the "Mango Fashion Awards" and the dinner of the Opera House in honor of Valentino.
A very intense, but at the same time exciting, day awaits us.
What is your new collection created for Mango for this fourth season based upon?
The cinema of the 1950s and 1960s dazzles us and we learn much from it for our collections.
I very much like to stroll around downtown and look at the women to see how they are dressed, how they coordinate their clothes. I do it often.
Dancer, actress and draftwoman, you are a very versatile woman: aren't you?
I think yes but ultimately everything is joined, and these activities have much in common.
Since I was very small clothing pleased me; I desired to go to my grandmother's house to look in my aunt's closets and to see her clothes.
It was brilliant, almost better than going to the amusement park.
Then, when I became a dancer, I was always trying to take care of the way I dressed.
Dancers like a lot being well dressed for the classes and the tests, in order to look themselves in the mirror and to feel good.
And in the role of an actress, when you wear her clothing, it is at this point that you really dive into the skin of the character.
As a result, everything is connected.
You were not long ago 30 years old: Was it hard for you?
Not at all.
I feel better than ever, my 30 years of age delight me.
I think that the woman is more mature, has more experience and enjoys life with fewer problems.
The biological clock do not scare me.
I have done all the things that I wanted to do since I was very small and this has given me a lot of inner joy.
So, do you think about becoming a mother?
Of course, I want to become a mother because my body is asking me for it and, moreover, I want to become a young mother; I do not want to lose this.
Regarding the candidate, I do not worry.
What I will do is give my son a great deal of happiness and raise him with a great deal of love.
Let's come to the cinema, you're waiting for the different films you made last year to be released.
It is true, I am looking forward to them coming out.
I, who am a woman stemming from theatre, am very anxious and worried, I would like to have everything now but of course that is not possible.
I look forward to the release of the films 'The última Hora' and 'En busca de la tumba de Cristo'.
To see what you would think of it...
A few days ago you started on the footbridge with Naomi Campbell, did not you?
Don't say that!
I did not climb up the footbridge to do the mannequin.
Quite simply, Naomi Campbell has called me, I know for some time to invite me to participate in London a parade of charity for its association with the support to women and the clothes that we exhibions - I have exhibited two clothes from our collection created for Mango – were auctioned off to collect money for the NGOs to Naomi.
The people that Naomi is a person with a tender heart.
They say so many things about her, I do know her, many things are not true.
Moreover, such a good side of Naomi fascinates me.
She asked me to parade for such a noble cause, but if she had asked me to do a handstand, I would have done it anyway.
The important thing is to make life better for women in the third world.
Repeat offenders of drink-driving will have to install the system 'alcolock'
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative sanctions for blood alcohol count, has to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the car from starting when drunk, or if he does not exhale.
The initiative was already announced last June, and since then it has appeared in the report of the Minister of State that this initiative is seen as a pilot project that will last a year.
His goal is the reinstatement of the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The State Minister responsible for road safety but also the General Management of Road Safety and the Technological Institute Foundation for the automobile Security will take part to this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for having driven more than once in a state of intoxication, drive again.
The alcolock would prevent this because it is a device plugged on the vehicle which measures the alcohol level in the breathe and prevent the car ignition when the driver does not blow before; or if the driver's alcohol level is higher than permitted.
Its cost is higher than 1,000 euros and is at the driver's charge.
In this respect, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 indicated that the vehicles equipped with this system reduced up to 65% of offences during the first year of installation.
And in Spain, we believe that this could save the lives of 115 people each year.
This measure confines itself to administrative penalties for two reasons: to cope with these behaviors before they become criminal offenses.
And facilitate its implementation, since judicial reform can be made in uncomplicated ways while penal code reform, however, requires reform of the existing law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and official vehicles already have experimental ones.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress members will vote for an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party, which proposes to set up in the school buses this system, as has been done in France.
In Mexico without 'peep-toes'
