Sarkozy at the meeting of angry fishermen
Before taking off to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a detour via Brittany.
Faced with the strength show of the fishermen who disrupted severely the access to several ports in Brittany and Normandy on Monday , the President of the Republic decided to go on Tuesday morning to the port of Guilvinec in Finistère, to meet their representatives.
The latter have promised to welcome him "in a constructive spirit" and hope that he "will come with concrete proposals."
A presidential visit comes at the same time as the General Assembly's "crisis committee" created by fishermen in Brittany to take action against the soaring price of fuel, which has reached a record of more than an average of 1.14 Euros per liter.
According to spokesman of the Elysée David Martinon, the president "will discuss with them about the solutions that can be conceived to help their businesses regain competitiveness and to secure the conditions of employment and pay of the seamen".
Nicolas Sarkozy is expected resolutely by the fishermen.
On Tuesday morning, they have conducted truck out operations in the Morbihan and Calvados, causing almost 10 km of traffic jams .
Quiberon's marina was also blocked, but the ferries to Belle-Ile had not stopped.
A dam filter was put in on the peninsula of Quiberon.
The sailors have already shown their determination on Monday by burning, from dawn, tyres and pallets in front of the fuel warehouses in the harbours of Brest and Lorient, while the demonstrations took place in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement has spread to other ports along the Atlantic coast and the English Channel, like Sables d'Olonne, in the Vendée, where the trawlers have stayed at the quayside, or at Le Havre, where some twenty or so boats have blocked the movement of cargo ships.
The fishermen from La Turballe and Le Croisic, Loire-Atlantique, have stopped in the evening the blockade of the major Total refinery of Donges.
Those of Boulogne-sur-Mer have decided to wait for the holding of the Wednesday meeting at the Department to decide upon any action.
In Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" should indeed decide on Tuesday on the follow-up to the movement and on its participation in the interview scheduled at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fishery in Paris.
But some fishermen from Brittany do not want to be represented by leaders of the national committee of fishing, which has not supported their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "the fishermen will not give up" and "do not want to move to Paris', has for example announced Liliane Cariou, president of the committee of Lorient fisheries.
Professional fishermen, who pay no taxes on diesel, currently pay about 50 centimes per litre but they asses that the threshold of profitability of a boat can only be reached with a diesel below 0.30 euros per liter.
