Embraer maintains its delivery forecasts in 2008
The Brazilian aircraft manufacturer counts on 215 airplanes being delivered this year despite the threat of recession that looms over the global economy.
The fourth worldwide aircraft manufacturer, Embraer, is maintaining its delivery forecasts for 2008 with 215 aircraft delivered, reaffirmed Fredrico Fleury Curado, its President.
In the first half, the aircraft manufacturer delivered 97 planes.
The Brazilian manufacturer has high hopes for the Chinese market especially for airplanes running the gamut from 30 to 120 seats.
To date, Embraer has delivered 41 planes to Chinese customers in eight years.
AIG would be considering giving away more than 15% of its assets
The insurer American International Group, which the American monetary authorities have bailed out, considers to give more than 15% of its assets to repay the 85 billion dollars which had been advanced to them, according to the Sunday edition of the Financial Times.
AIG is ready to explore the sale of most of its businesses beyond its international life insurance business and its retirement business in the United States, says the newspaper which quotes sources close to the project.
The Board of AIG met on Sunday evening to review possible transfers, according to the FT.
No confirmation could be obtained from AIG.
The assets that AIG is planning to sell includes its subsidiary in air leasing International Lease Financial Corp., its participation of 59% in the reinsurer Transatlantic Holdings and its property portfolio and its investments in the private equity, adds the FT.
No final decision has been taken on these cessions, the FT continues.
AIG must rapidly get its hands on some cash to repay the 85 billion dollar loan the Federal Reserve made to it or the American authorities could take 80% of its capital, cutting proportionally the holdings of the current shareholders.
Analyzes Paris Historique of the meeting Historical Morning Meeting Morning Meeting
The New York Stock Exchange had a record drop on Monday after the House of Representatives rejected the Paulson plan to rescue the banks: the Dow Jones lost 6.98%, a never before seen loss of almost 800 points, and the Nasdaq 9.14%.
The Dow Jones industrial average (DJIA) plunged by 777.68 points to 10.365,45 points.
In terms of points, the biggest fall in its history (684.81 points) had previously been recorded on 17 September 2001, the resumption of trade after the terrorist attacks of September 11.
The Nasdaq index, predominantly technological, has given up 199,61 points to 1.983,73 and the broader index Standard & Poor's 500 8,81% (or 106,85 points), to 1.106,55 points, according to the final closing figures.
Already depressed at the start of the session, Wall Street has thrown open after the unexpected reject by the House of Representatives, of the bank rescuing plan which was supposed to regain stability in the markets.
With 205 votes for and 228 votes against, the representatives denied Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson the resources he was asking for.
Almost two Republicans out of three rejected his plan.
"It is a bad signal sent to the market, which sees Congress unable to adopt a plan", reckoned Lindsey Piegza, of FTN Financial.
"It shows how far the market counted on that plan", she added, fearing that a project adopted within several days would come "too late."
"If the project is effectively dead (...) then the baton will be quickly passed to the Fed (the American central bank) and the other central banks to handle the crisis, which would further tighten credit conditions," said Brian Bethune, chief economist at Global Insight.
And accentuating further the sense of urgency, "every day that goes by  brings the fall of a financial institution" in the United States, pointed out Mrs Piegza.
After the collapse of Washington Mutual on friday, the authorities have organised the takeover of the banking activities of Wachovia by its rival Citigroup.
In Europe, the crisis has sharply accelerated, leading to emergency measures to banks in the United Kingdom, the Benelux countries, Iceland, and in Germany, a sign that the markets are "not only to an American crisis, but a global crisis," added the analyst of FTN Financial.
The bond market has strongly risen.
The yield of a Treasury Bond for 10 years has fallen to 3.632%, against 3.827% on Friday evening, and the one for 30 years to 4.161%, against 4.357% the previous day.
Obama, winner on points of the first televised duel
The first debate on Friday between the two candidates for the White House was followed by another to know who, between John McCain and Barack Obama, won.
Not surprisingly, the headquarters of Republican and Democratic campaigns have declared their own victory in this televisiual duel which would have been followed by a third of American families.
Political analyst David Gergen believes that John McCain's delivery, while honorable, has not been "brilliant" enough to allow him to halt his decline in the polls five weeks before the presidential election.
The Gallup institute, whose opinion poll published on Saturday gives an advance of five points to Obama (49% to 44% for McCain), thinks it is the Democrat who has come through it the best.
Among the undecided voters, who are those who count, Obama has emerged the winner for 39% of respondents, while 25% of them grant the victory to McCain, according to a CBS poll.
Obama should be able to confirm his advance on Thursday with the good performance expected from his running mate, Joseph Biden, during the first and only public debate with his rival, Sarah Palin.
"It would be a mistake to underestimate her.
She has good instincts ", has, however, warned Bill Clinton this weekend.
The septuagenarian McCain has been putting forward its indisputable experience concerning foreign policy, while stressing the "naive" of his opponent on these issues which were in the heart of this first showdown.
"Senator Obama does not seem to understand that..." he accused several times.
"I do not believe that Senator Obama has the experience and knowledge needed to be president", has he also said.
An angle of attack hammered since yesterday in the Republican TV commercials.
Obama has stressed that he represents the future.
Undaunted, he was concise and accurate.
He highlighted his ability to make good decisions, and to restore United States image around the world.
"McCain hasn't understood yet, while Obama has," said this weekend, a Democrat tv ad, which accused the Republican not to have grasped the impact of the crisis on 'Joe the plumber. "
"During the 90 minutes of the debate, John McCain had much to say about me, but nothing about you," Obama criticized yesterday, in front of 20,000 people assembled for an election rally in North Carolina in a driving rain.
He has not even uttered the words "middle class" or "workers." "The financial meltdown clearly benefits Obama, who is considered by Americans as the most likely to save the declining economy.
"The coming week could be a turning point," said yesterday, the influential Democratic Senator Charles Schumer.
The Democratic Representative Rahm Emanuel, a former Clinton administration official, compared the "good economic instincts" of Obama to those of Bill Clinton during the financial crisis of 1998.
For the Democratic candidate, the current debacle "is the final verdict of eight years of bad economic policy implemented by George Bush and supported by Senator McCain."
Reiterating that he would manage to reduce taxes for 95% of Americans despite the unpredictability of Wall Street, the senator from Illinois has also indicated that the achievement of the country's eventual energy independence by promoting renewable energy was his first priority along with the establishment of a system of health insurance.
McCain sought to build a set of 45 nuclear power plants by 2030.
Carefully, both candidates ducked the questions about the financial rescue plan of $700 billion (470 billion Euro) adopted last night by the Congress and extremely unpopular.
In Minsk, "You have noticed that there was an election, haven't you?"
Young and opponents demonstrated Sunday evening on the main square in the capital of Belarus to reject the general elections results in advance.
A few hundred Belarus met on Sunday evening after the polling places on the central square in Minsk had closed to protest against the fraudulent nature of the election.
While no result had yet been announced, many young people came to demonstrate against the regime of President Alexander Lukashenko: "the dictator, resignation."
Some admit to not even having voted: "What's the point, as they will do what they want with my voice," a young says.
They do not believe that the government which has been looking good to foreign observers in order to resume discussions with the European Union is ready to carry out a democratic turn.
The sanctions, including the visa ban for 40 Belarussian leaders and the freezing of some assets, could be lifted if these elections were considered clean by the observers.
They have not been according to the opposition.
"We have been excluded from Electoral Commissions and our observers were unable to participate in the counting", lamented Yuri Potemkin, the spokesman of the Union of Democratic Forces, a heterogeneous grouping of twelve parties.
"It is a cosmetic change, says Alexander Milinkevich, former opposition candidate in the presidential elections of 2006 and leader of the pro-European movement, because the important thing is who counts the votes, and for us, it is the executive power.
If MPs of the opposition enter Parliament, it is that they have been appointed, not elected.
But their entry to parliament can mean space on television, meetings in the regions and some draft laws."
The opposition must enter the political game because "we must initiate dialogue with the European Union.
Because if our economy, which is heavily indebted to Russia, enters a crisis, and that we do not reform ourselves, we will be at risk of becoming a protectorate of Russia.
And yet we want to be independent.
The opposition fears that the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe that has followed the election process will not recognize the validity of the ballot.
It underscores the fact that the participation figures seem too high, and that the general practice of voting in advance (26% of the voters in Minsk) has opened the voting to all sorts of manipulation.
"You have noticed that there was an election? the Social Democrat leader Alexandre Kozouline asks, one of the two remaining political prisoners released in August this year.
There was nobody in the polling stations.
And there will be at the maximum five opposition parliament members, those best suited to power."
The silence of the night falls back on the October place.
On television, President Lukashenko and the members of the Central Election Commission are congratulating one another on their success.
Interview - Blood become safe again.
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding, and its President, Dr. Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the world's safeest and most effective suppliers of blood.
And above all, he has regained the public trust, which had been seriously dented by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Transfusion Service of the Canadian Red Cross were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Facing this tragedy and the public discontent, the Canada's government  has set up in February 1994 a public inquiry, chaired by judge Horace Krever, which was intended to shed light upon the circumstances which led to such a tragedy and make recommendations to make sure that such a disaster will never happen again.
While judge Krever was long to submit its report, some provinces have established a committee aimed at planning a new system of blood management in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee has fulfilled this term.
Following the Délineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Company of blood to supply all the other provinces and the two territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, barely 38% of people still trusted the system of blood in Quebec, the Dre Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Because of consistent efforts to improve blood products' safety and field work during the last years, we have returned to public confidence ", she said before proudly stating that in early 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population trusted Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary nevertheless keeps in mind the fact that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its creation, on September 28 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of precaution.
At that time, there was in Europe a sudden increase of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the woman in charge since the organization's founding in 1998.
"And we did not know at all if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
We then relied on one of the key recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we don't know and it may result in a serious illness, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that leads inevitably to death, we establish a process of elimination.
So in April 1999, they refused the blood of people who had stayed more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
But a few years ago, it has been proven beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode has this shown us that the precautionary principle that we applied made sense."
In 1999, there appeared on the market a much more sensitive technique for testing the start of HIV: nucleic acid testing (NAT), which can detect the presence of the virus right in the donors' blood, rather than antibodies against the virus, which is what was done in the tests used till then.
NAT allowed us to shorten the silent period, which extends from when the person was infected to when the first viruses can be found in the blood using our techniques, the specialist explains.
One could reduce this period to less than a week.
We have this way substantially decreased the risk that some donors are infected without knowing and without possible detection.
These improvements have helped to considerably lower the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person out of 12 million is put at risk of receiving HIV contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million of blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes each year between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products, it will take over 24 years before that occurs a case of HIV transmission by a blood products.
I think we can feel at ease today about receiving or prescribing blood transfusions to restore health," asserts the head of Héma-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must always be vigilant," continues Dre Décary before emphasising that in addition to a safety supply, Héma-Québec must also provide an adequate supply.
"Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
The anticancer treatments being more aggressive, patients often need a recharge of red blood cells or blood plates.
The ageing population also has implications for the network of blood donors who averages only 3% of eligible Quebecois to donate blood. "
Any healthy person, aged 18 and older who meets eligibility criteria, can give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer to give blood are not accepted, because they are suffering from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled in a country where there is malaria, they will be excluded for a period of a year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this network of donors as they get older and can no longer give blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donor.
Life today is so unbridled, one rarely finds the time to spend an hour giving blood," Francine Décary laments.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, the eyeballs and skin which is used almost exclusively for serious burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec which also runs the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
The umbilical cord which was once considered as a biomedical waste is full of blood rich of stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukaemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood, and we predict we will get more than a thousand per year.
We should begin to offer it for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dre Décary who described this programme of umbilical cord blood collection as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed not to be able to have access to it," because Héma-Québec cannot afford to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
Soccer - The Impact in semi-finals.
The Montreal Impact has qualified for the play-off's semi-final round of the USL's first division, thanks to a score of 3-1 (4-3 in total goals) against the Sounders of Seattle, yesterday, during the second and decisive match of the series quarterfinals in total goals, at Saputo Stadium.
The midfield player Antonio Ribeiro scored the winning goal in the 90th minute of the game.
After a first half without a goal on either side, midfielder David Testo and Rocco Plancentino scored the other nets of the Montreal team.
Roger Levesque was the only one to foil Matt Jordan for the Sounders.
Reminding that on the first match of the away-home series, on Friday, Impact suffered a 2-1 defeat in Starfire Sports Complex, in Tukwila in suburban Seattle.
The Impact will go up against the Vancouver Whitecaps in the semi-finals.
Saturday night, Minnesota, the Thunder has filled a deficit of 3-1 in the return match to win 4-3, but nevertheless the Whitecaps acceded to the round semi-final 5-4 goals in total.
Impact team should face the Whitecaps Friday and Sunday, but the series' details will be confirmed today.
In short - Victorious goal of Kovalev
The number one trio of the Canadian is ready to begin the season.
The unit composed of Alex Kovalev, Tomas Plekanec and Andrei Kostitsyn has enlivened the attack in a Canadien win of 3-2 on penalty kicks against the Panthers from Florida, last night, at the Bell Centre.
Kostitsyn, the star of the match, scored a goal, Plekanec got two assists, and Kovalev pocketed a pass in this victory, the fourth of the French in six preparation matches.
Kovalev gave the victory when marking the unique goal of the shooting.
"I am not ready yet, the Russian warned.
I must have another match to feel comfortable."
"He tried to do too much in the first period, noted Guy Carbonneau.
But I think he appreciated the end of the match.
He had a nice ovation."
Charest is betting on the Northern Plan
The prime minister does not exclude to trigger elections before the end of the year
Immediately after the end of the Liberal party's main council, Jean Charest came yesterday in Jean-Talon in Quebec, where the new health minister, Yves Bolduc (left), is trying to get elected in todays by-election.
"Push the limits of our last great frontier of the North": such is the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented with visual force while remaining entirely in the broad outlines, at the end of the General Council of the Liberal Party of Quebec, in Lévis, yesterday.
During his speech, a sort of picture mill was projected behind him.
Turning in loops, on three huge screens, there were spectacular snapshots of hydro-electric dams, of mining, of Quebec seen by "Google Maps, of maps, etc.
Great resources as in an election period.
Besides, during the press conference, the Prime Minister refused to rule out that he would trigger the elections this autumn, although he pointed out that his time-sheet was very busy.
The "Plan North" "is the fourth part of a "vision" that the prime minister claims for Quebec, one of a new economic area, which includes an agreement on the workforce with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the speech of the prime minister recently, the opening to the North - the territory North of the 49th parallel - had never been introduced.
The prime minister, however, restricted himself to explaining why the North was "a jewel with enormous potential," but did not set a specific time, state the investment amounts or disclose the precise priority of the future projects.
At most a few avenues which could be developed further: notably hydroelectricity, the forest, but over all the mining sector, led by the growth of developing countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds," according to Mr Charest's enumeration.
This "territory twice as large as France," it is in our homeland, it is in Quebec.
Not only is it home, but it is within us," he insisted, as if to show well that he was soliciting a national myth.
Quebec has much built itself in its relationship with the North, he said: the gold rush in Abitibi, the Quebec engineering, Bay James.
"It's up to us, it's our future", he added, after having made a dramatic pause to contemplate the vast map behind him.
The North, 70% of the Quebecois territory, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the prime minister said at the press briefing.
"This is a traditional position that all governments have reiterated.
There is a line on which there is not an agreement for a very long time and, when the opportunity arises, I repeat that position on the name of the government ", he said.
Besides, "with climate change, we must rethink our view of the North," he said speaking of the Northwest Passage, which is open all year because of melting ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister believes that occupying the territory is a duty.
And the inhabitants of the territory, the First Nations and the Inuit?
The prime minister said that the government of Quebec would pay great care to them and that the project would benefit them, especially young people.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (a former member of the Parti Québecois in Ungava), have already begun consultations with about thirty communities.
An interministerial committee which is chaired by Benedict Pelletier and in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) plays an important role has begun its work.
The prime minister does not exclude the possibility of a great meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a moment where "we will have a common vision".
The development of the North would beside be in conformity with the principles of sustainable development.
The North Plan will be "concerted, methodical and environmentally friendly," he promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as being in continuity with that of the liberal Prime Ministers who preceded him.
"As the liberals who preceded us, we thought differently to transform the challenges into new opportunities of growth and development."
This has been one of the recurring themes at the end of the week, which began on Friday with a great cocktail event to highlight the 50th anniversary of the arrival of Jean Lesage as head of the party.
One of the resolutions adopted proposes to rename the Beauharnois plant to Adélard-Godbout dam.
"From Godbout who created Hydro-Québec, to Lesage who manufactured the quiet revolution of the nationalization of hydroelectricity, to Bourassa who made the Bay James, our party has been able to shape the future," said Jean Charest.
At the press briefing, he cited another reference, conservative, this one, the "Roads to the North" programme of John Diefenbaker, prime minister from 1957 to 1963.
While addressing the project of the hydroelectric dam of Eastmain1a-Ruper, Mr Charest stressed that its commissioning was scheduled for 2012.
"That remains between us, but I expect to be there," he confided to his supporters, prompting their sustained applause.
Indeed, the prime minister, who said in April that there would be no election in 2008 and probably not in 2009, has not eliminated the possibility to trigger an election this autumn, what the law allows him.
He underlines that his schedule is full, especially by a Federation Council's mission in China and a summit between Québec and New York.
The general Council of the weekend has given to the liberal leader a platform containing nationalists resolutions, in particular « constitutional aspirations » which have gone without a hitch: the PLQ especially calls the recognition the « specificity of Quebec » in the Constitution.
He also hopes Quebec will appoint Canadian broadcasting and telecommunications council members and that these would have a veto on decisions taken in Quebec.
From the side of the opposition, the outlines of the North Plan were welcomed with scepticism.
The head Péquiste, Pauline Marois, has brought forth again the policy for the development of the Nord-du-Québec that the Landry government  launched in 2001.
According to her, the liberal government, coming to power in 2003, has renounced to apply it.
If it had done it, "we would be further ahead today," commented Mrs. Marois alongside her candidate, Françoise Mercury, in Jean-Talon (balloting which is taking place today).
The ADQ said it supports government adoption of the Northern Plan.
"But what we hope is that it will not be just a spectacle," commented leader Sébastien Proulx, replacing Mario Dumont, who is returning from vacation today.
Letters - A disgraced country
It is Mr Vic Toews, former 'Justice' Minister (ironically) in the Harper Cabinet, who last summer made bold to say about Louise Arbour that she was a "disgrace" to Canada.
To cast shame like that on this woman who has conducted an unending struggle for justice and who deserves all our admiration says as much as on the entourage of the Prime Minister as on Stephen Harper himself.
We are facing a government which is the only one, of all the Western countries involved, not to have brought back its national locked in the concentration camp of Guantánamo.
A government that takes no account of the fact that Omar Khadr was a young teenager at the time of the crimes of which he is accused.
The only government that, despite the fact that Canada has signed the Geneva Convention, denies his own word and leaves a child soldier languish in inhumane conditions.
The only one that relies on a parody of justice to assess the guilt of the accused.
Let's remember, for the record, that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association, in particular, are calling for the repatriation of Omar Khadr, so that he can have a fair trial in Canada.
This same government that condones torture: it matters little that a young adult is now psychologically destroyed, probably forever after years of abuse.
We are not aware of it yet, but we are currently undergoing a rampant erosion of our rights, our freedom and our "democracy", this word Harper keeps waving and which sounds so hollow in his mouth.
Now is the time when no moral no longer exists: we can bully, torture, arbitrarily imprison a Canadian citizen according to the goodwill of a government leader so far in the minority (What will be then after October 14...).
A number of voters believe that they will find salvation in a party which extols virtue, law and order: they do not see that this government has abandoned the basis of our country's reputation and dignity.
The shame, Mr Toews, it is here, in this renunciation, and not anywhere else.
Free opinion - Barrick Gold's orwellian speech
In its edition of September 17th, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian sort of logic, he says that the largest gold mining company in the world has brought a defamation suit of six million dollars against three authors and a poor, small publishing house in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of libel prosecution, but the law.
Not surprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to its own?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and the editor of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable amounts to prepare their defense and to fight, with quite unequal strength, against an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining industry.
The tactic, in these uneven struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a gentle settlement which muffles opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is before the public opinion that it would had to present his vision of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in several of the countries in which Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally exchanges of ideas and not truncheon blows.
It was enough for the mining industry to open its books and its files and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and with funding for independent research teams that could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and dismissing out of hand the petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can, at the same time, request a "public" debate while mistrusting the views of this same public?
In the Vice-President's world, it seems that this word only means highly paid lawyers, and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What does not understand - or does not want to understand - Barrick Gold, is that the public who supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does it primarily because it rejects the brutal manner of the mining.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but based on a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag action (while pursuing a "public debate," Barrick Gold moreover has just filed an injunction against the authors of Black Canada notifying them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr Garver's surreal speech, suing Barrick Gold is a direct attack against freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, which are essential to a democratic society.
She denies completely the right to quote credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations, which is the basis of even brain work.
If it is impossible to study and to discuss issues that do not like the rich companies in this world in a country like Canada, for fear of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do this?
If Barrick Gold really wanted to a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The academic environment, which we belong to, knows for a while how to deal with the debates and desagrements and to solve conflicts.
The excessive legal action by Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the academic world, as it is for public debate in Canada; and it is time for governments to establish regulations limiting these kinds of malicious lawsuits.
Operation Rescue for Wall Street – Democrats and Republicans agreed
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats have finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic recovery plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion dollar plan aiming to curb the financial crisis affecting Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both chambers of the Congress.
It includes especially: better control by elected representatives of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money involved, new clauses to control the number of foreclosed homes for non-payment, as well as a right of inspection on the salaries paid to executives from the rescued companies.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and the Republican representative at the table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, after marathon negotiations lasting two days.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement which will be effective on the markets," declared the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
"Everything was done in order to shelter the real economy and the ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis in Wall Street," said the Democrat.
"It is the fundamental point: If we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said the Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned into a sprint in the last few hours by fear of the effect that would cause another failure on investors mood.
The deadline that was agreed upon was the opening of the markets this morning.
Brought into the negotiations late, the two US presidential candidates were rather favorable to the agreement, without failing, however, to express their dissatisfaction that it had to come to this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has blamed the addition of certain provisions in the agreement, particularly the proposal to allow homeowners to keep their homes and that the pay of executives of companies rescued by the state.
"When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be proud of.
But these measures are necessary, " he commented on the american television waves.
Questioned on another chain, on whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, said: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The outlines that I have read that it is something that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable, he said.
The $700 billion plan to buy up with taxpayers' money the bad debts, risky and unsellable assets of the American financial company.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of the real estate bubble which first led to the collapse of sub-prime mortgages before spreading to other, more widespread forms of asset-backed commercial paper (ABCP) and leading to a liquidity freeze and the failure of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had killed the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed we are out of this impasse since Democrats have agreed that some "toxic" assets of companies in trouble are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to cut corners for everyone in Congress, they have also added a provision stipulating that if the government should take losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes aimed at helping recover its outlay.
The new plan provides for the expenditure of a first tranche of $250 billion to which another 100 billion will be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be ratified by another vote in Congress.
In exchange for its assistance, Washington will receive shares in the rescued companies which will pay dividends in case of profit and which it will be able to sell once the storm has passed.
The federal government will take the opportunity to delay the procedures of foreclosures on homes attached to the real estate loans covered by this plan and set limits on pay and redundancy payments paid to executives of affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted for a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
Indeed, voices continued to be raised yesterday against this project, both on the Republican and Democratic side.
"Obviously, Washington is not hearing you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the Finance Committee of the House of Representatives, said to his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one which consists in taking advantage of taxpayers".
Leader of a small group in Congress nicknamed "the caucus of sceptics", the Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred prominent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to tell us: we are asking the Congress not to hurry and to carefully consider the way to follow", he said yesterday.
Meanwhile, in Europe, we had once again the proof of the crisis' global nature.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three countries of the Benelux announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion Euro (16,3 billion Us dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had become necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was abandoning the acquisition of its drowning rival since it lost 2 billion Euros (2.9 billion US) during the mortgage crisis in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is part of 20 major European banks and the ten biggest insurers.
"This is not wasted money, said yesterday the Dutch Finance minister, Wouter Bos.
In exchange, they get a vote in the bank and influence.
This is precisely something that savers and households enjoy now that the time looks uncertain."
Meanwhile, across the Channel, the British government seemed on course to nationalise another bank mauled by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government will resume its accounting of all the existing loans at the Bradford and Bringley, Bank, of which more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) are mortgage loans.
The Spanish bank Santander made it known yesterday that it would buy the branches and the customer accounts of the British bank.
The Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after the Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - death of a committed icon
Her blue-eyed beauty was her trump card for a long time, some would say her weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissist's mirror, the American actor with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, his sensitivity and a talent which was obvious also have taken him away from the register of power that is giving birth to the real sacred monsters.
But what a great long-distance runner!
Paul Newman, deceased on Friday, at 83 years old, because of a lung cancer in his ranch in Connecticut, remains one of the last icons of the American cinema of the prosperous years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he ressembles and was a long time rival on the screen, more cautious in his game, certainly more fragile, but also a great champion of freedom and the bursting of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often brings forth beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, of a German Jew father and a mother with Hungarian origins.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without huge ego, the ultimate mark of quality.
Because was projected in him a whole country in love with the self made man, the Pacific war fighter, wounded in action, who in the early 1950s studied theater in Yale and then attended Actor's Studio in New York, before succeeding at the theatre, television, soon in movies.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also the race car driver, who came in second at the 24 hour mark of Le Mans in 1979, and was a sex symbol, albeit half of a model couple together with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
There also disappear with him the shadowy areas of this secretive, discreet, committed star, allergic to the glitz of show business whose enigma no one has completely unraveled.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the term.
This weekend, the death of Paul Newman made film lovers' heads swim, as memories of all his major roles collided on their mental movie screens.
More than half a century of an always changing American seventh art  stream around him.
The cowboy charm of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) and the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Tin Roof, adapted from Tennessee Williams in 1958, come racing back into memory.
Closer to us (1990), his sensitive Mr Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage which did not fulfil all its promises.
Many other Paul Newman went to history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Somebody Up There Likes Me (Marked by Hatred), by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, resumed after his death, which really launched Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic thug in the brilliant The Sting (The Scam), Oscar for best picture in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiards player in Robert Rossen's magnificent "The Hustler" (1961), he played the role again on his return in Martin Scorsese's "The Color of Money," which won him in 1987 his only Oscar after nine nominations.
This face throughout the ages, it was him.
Him, again
The eras are jostling throughout his career.
Young people know him especially from George Roy Hill's cult film Slap Shot (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, coach of a rather unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him again in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy from the Coen brothers.
With a final role of Irish Mafia godfather in the Road to Perdition of Sam Mendes in 2003, we had come full circle.
As opposed to several film legends who left the business rather early, Newman stayed in the saddle for a long time, all the while denouncing Hollywood, its wealth, its ostentation and its compromises.
The French film-maker Bertrand Tavernier regarded him, not without humour, "as a living challenge to 'underplaying' judging his performances as too forceful".
The profession has not always been kind to the wonderful Paul Newman whom the roles fell a long time all cooked in the tooth.
He played however less often young successful people than those on the fringe: neurotics, alcoholics, bastards or the desperate, whose perfect traits reflected mindless drifting and rebellion.
As a director, Newman revealed little known aspects of his true modest nature.
His Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (from the novel of Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the main role, drew a fine female portrait of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated his movie Harry and Son to him in 1984, a modest and sad work.
Among the deluge of tributes to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (they had acted together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said, very sadly: "His presence made my life and this country better."
Generosity and love of life are vibrant features of the deceased actor.
Beyond his legendary career, we are losing a great campaigner for civil rights, ecology and independent films and an opponent of the excesses of Hollywood.
We have seen much of its face standing on vinaigrette pots, sauces, biscuits and other foods, as a process of poor taste, albeit a joke at the beggining.
The profits of these sales were nonetheless paid to his Foundation for children in difficulty.
Newman, rather than resting on his laurels, will be committed until the end.
He left to his five daughters a letter containing these words: "Always and until the end, your father has been incredibly grateful for his lucky star.
It was a privilege to be here."
And a privilege for us to have followed the path of such a coherent and generous American artist.
Model citizen, in short and above.
What could anyway produce Zuschlag & Cie in their bills factory ?
Soon, on the 8th of October, will start the proceedings concerning the ongoing criminal procedure, against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud in the form of permanent and regular criminal organization, having led to rather sizable damages. Other charges have been brought against them, such as forgery and use of forgery.
According to the public prosecutor, money from subsidies, was spent for personal gain, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money from the State and the municipalities, approximately 65 million HUF in total, was going on the one hand in the funds of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and, on the other hand, in the pocket of some people.
Their method, made also public by the authorities in charge of the inquiry, was to take the money of the subsidies received by issuing expense bills, for which no real provision was given and thus, the associations have never met their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the bills were forged.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they produced the stamps at Kiskunhalas.
As for the names of societies that were included on the bills, they were decided, among others, during tours in the province of North Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, on the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the testimony of the latter, he was supposed to identify inns and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he called for a bill, modeled on which they wrote other bills that they would introduce, among others, in the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the city hall to get subsidies.
The majority of bills was created by István lados and his accomplice Mr András Őri who, according to our information, was involved in files drafting needed to qualify for subsidies.
During a "circuit identification", one of the choices of Lados was a bistro.
According to the two bills issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place has assured the catering for a group of 90 people, members of the Biztos Pont Egyesület association.
However, according to what the manager said, it would have been impossible that so many people fit in this place, at the same time.
Similarly, during summer 2002, the bill on behalf of Jobb Jövőért foundation which will bear the name of Együtt in Harmadik Évezredért, was full of style and spelling mistakes.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, had in fact only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night there. However, the bill was mentioning one hundred and thirty clients.
Invoice providers with overflowing imaginations plunged into excess, when they said that the company Pigal KFT also belonged to the HORECA sector. In their accounts, neither the name of Jobb Jövőért nor that of Hoppá appears, according to the information given to the prosecution.
Győző Farkas, the manager of the company, said to the site hvg.hu that when the public prosecutor summoned him and showed him the bills, he knew immediately that it was forgery.
"The name of our society and our tax number were placed in the wrong spot on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the look of it, the fact that according to the bill,  a hundred people stayed there did not make sense either, since this establishment had only eleven bedrooms, which did not have enough space.
Moreover, the bill mentions meals too, and our restaurant is closed since long ago."
Zealous issuers of bills were also not well informed about Budapest's travel agencies, which were constituting a part of their choice, but only organizing trips abroad. Thus, naively, they said some stays in Hungary on the bills were to be paid for in cash, which also runs counter to the accounting practices of the agency.
Also, as it emerged during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while the benefits on the travel activities, which the destination is outside the European Union, are charged without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four bills made out in the name of the Hotel Révfülöp to the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's allowances do not cover a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. In addition, employees of the hotel issue only printed bills, while the false ones were made out by hand.
The prosecutor's investigation reveals that the "issuers" also erred in stating as the delivery cost highway transportation for the merchandise, which the company issuing the bills could not have performed, since it was only serving as the investment counselor.
Moreover, it is also for procedural defects, such as inadequate kinds of bills and false stamps, that bills issued by Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont turn out to be wrong.
Just as in the case of the Ravenna Bt. company or the sports resort in Kunfehértó, both of which deny being responsible for invoices issued in their names.
The forgers also did not pay attention to the fact that the HIB Kft. company, located in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (2001) when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group was supposed to have had a meal on their premises. According to our information, this is the reason why the company's liquidator denies having issued this bill.
Invoices set deliberately
Another category of issuers of bills was composed of those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue false bills.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták group, wrote an invoice to the order of the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Foundation, for a sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of the company Collab Kft. was asked to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, in cooperation with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued bills to the order of the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, amounting to around five million HUF, but for which no services have been rendered.
No financial movement took place, either, given that the invoices were cancelled afterward, but the organisms avoided carefully to mention this in their accounts.
The following category of companies which issued bills is that of companies directly linked to the accused.
Thus, the administrative deputy to the executive director of the Delta Trió KFT. enterprise which trades in fuel and cars, whose headquarters were located in Budapest, but where he was nowhere to be found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December of 2005, this company has issued several bills for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to about 18 million HUF.
According to the investigation, such equipment would have been purchased by the company Cash Investment LLC of Kiskunhalas, which was in liquidation since September 14, 2005.
This company's director was a man from Romania, whom Iván Kubatov would also have sent documents relative to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
According to what we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued bills on the orders of the Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány companies, and that he pocketed their exchange value.
It is precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian builders have created the Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment BT companies.
In reality, none of these companies were really operating, which the accused explained was due to the fact that they were not getting any work.
He even used those companies, because at maestro Zsolt Szente request, codefendant and editor of compagnies foundation acts, he established bills on behalf of associations reporting to Zuschlag, as Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations.
Kubatov gave agencies a total of 15 bills, issued by the Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade companies, with a value of 14.2 million HUF.
The public prosecutor believed that 10% of the pointed accounts on the bills as well as VAT were going in Kubatov's pockets.
The man even used the Szi-Beri Bt. company to establish fictitious bills that were used as part of the request for a subsidy for Biztos Pont.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció Association and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért applied for a grant from the public utility body of the socialist party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (MRI).
They have achieved this subsidy for the sum of twice 500 Huf , but these amounts were not used for the objectives pointed in the demand.
In order to prevent it from being known, five fictitious invoices received from the Works Team Kft. company have been presented to the TMA.
Moreover, these are bills that have been found during the raid on the office of Arpad Kemecsei, the Minister of Education.
At the hearing, part of the accused will explain bills production method, as it had already done in front of the public prosecutor earlier.
What could be really interesting would be that the main defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
Until now, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has promised repeatedly to tell the details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in their interest, or perhaps eventually the Socialists would together conclude that in exchange for reimbursement of a large part of the 50 million HUF, Zusi would wear only the hat.
Today, this one is probably annoyed, since the requests for his placement under house arrest, on a basis of a reduction of its detention conditions, keep continuing to fall in deaf ears.
While those who have caused much more important damage, and the culprits of irreparable economic crimes, walk freely or at the least, await in their own home the end of the procedure. He does not have this possibility.
The psychology of the bidding war: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
The researchers in neurology and economy of the University of New York managed to update the neural and economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be outbid in this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, which is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
These studies have tried to set a neural pattern of this kind of "game" with the help of auctions experiments.
One of the groups of volunteers was playing lotto, while the other group was taking part in a playful auction, during which, with the aid of a process of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), researchers were analyzing the active brain areas of the experiment's subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction whose a key element is higher bid by a third person, all the elements situated under the brainstem, called striatum, were intensively moving at the loss of the day.
This part of the brain, in addition to having several other functions, plays a role in the "auto-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
This is why, according to researcher, the rise in prices is explained by the leak before the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economist members of this group of researchers have pursued analyses of financial supervision.
During these, three groups were outbidding facing a partner, in various circumstances.
They have simply informed the control group of the real value of the product in question, and they have thus made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if they came out winners of the game too, then they would receive an additional $15, as a reward.
While the third group received the same $15 from him before the auction, the members of the group also lost this money if they lost the bid.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was put with one on victory, while with the other, on failure.
By demonstrating the assumption of neurologues, members of the "against failure" players team were willing to higher bets than those made by the control group and the "for victory" group.
"These results cannot be proven by any economic theory that already exists.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena noticed during auctions by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only the neural imaging methods have helped remove the contradiction between the two theories, leading on a third explanation. "- found Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when do we have to see a doctor?
In the world, around half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated that 100 thousand patients are carriers of the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven thousand are treated. This is due to the fact that often patients do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogenic agents and the diseases caused differ from one another.
The hepatitis viruses, in the manner of pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and the other viruses through blood and organic liquids (sperm, vaginal secretions, saliva).
For travelers, it is anyway recommended to be vaccinated against the A and B virus. There is no vaccine against the C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated food, in most cases, accompanied by a poor  general condition, weakness, upset stomach and nausea.
Then there develops on the skin and white of the eye a visible yellowing, the faeces become lighter in colour and the urine, darker.  Recovery could take two to three weeks.
Throughout the world, every year, a million people die of the most serious form of this disease, as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that according to estimates, only one patient out of ten receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know if they are infected by the virus, because the  pathogenic gene silently destroys the liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
Consequently, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who have tattoos.
Currently, we figure 200 million patients suffering from a chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine check in a laboratory, it is advised to consult one's attending physician from the note of unknown origin symptoms.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, this way the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is averted.
On 30 September is the world day of hepatitis, organised for the first time in 2004 by the organizations representative of patients from around the world.
His aim is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, on the causes of its development and on the importance of an early illness diagnosis.
Does someone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of recent research, religious beliefs funtion as a kind of analgesia, which would have already made the deaths of the Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British newspaper "Telegraph" published an article stating that researchers at Oxford University have had an interesting experience while analyzing at what level the belief in God could influence tolerance to pain in human beings.
In this rather weird experience, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists have been subjected to electroshocks, while each one of them was looking at a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, the faithful Catholics have been able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of the human brain examination, we were also able to discover that Catholics had been able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating the pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiments, to which academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians take part from different departments of the university.
Specifically, the experience is as follows: an instrument that emits sparks and broadcasts the electroshocks is set on the left hand of the experimental subject.
Researchers asked the participants in the experiment to keep looking for a long time at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th Century and the other, the Lady in Ermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th Century.
Researchers who initiated this experience hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary tells a sort of state of faith among the believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, was on its calming effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scan, and during this time, received 20 electrochocs in four consecutive parts, while either watching a painting on a religious theme or the one with a more general theme.
Catholics have said that at the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe", like someone who is "taken care of" and they "calmed down, and peace invaded them."
At the sight of the religious-themed painting, they have reported 12% less pain than when they watched the work of Leonard.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the experience himself, believes we can achieve the same effects for atheists with some other sort of powerful image, provided we find the appropriate photo.
"We should find a picture toward which they respond very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, has welcomed the results of this research.
"The practice of the faith should change and in many cases, changes effectively our personality," added Wright.
After these excellent results, all that remains is the question of the effect on the pain regulation of the subjects if believers were shown a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by another painter of the same caliber?
Would the sight of a better quality Virgin Mary yield better results
You are what you disclose about yourself
On the occasion of its tenth anniversary, Google asserts that one can find them at the bottom of people's pockets the same way you find sky above their head. It knows where they have spent their vacation, which experts they consult and what their interests are.
This is still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, who is one of the influential people in the organization.
While as to the sceptics establishing a parallel with Orwell's vision of horror, they do not properly see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt said, not long time ago, to the Financial Times that Google's main ambition is to gather even more information about its users. This is necessary so that Google's founders can keep to their original goal, which was as follows: "Let collect all the information in the world in a system!".
According to the executive of Google who was interviewed, after ten years of worldwide upheaval work, they are still only at the initial stage of their targets of being able to deal with all sources of information.
To the question: how is it going to be in five years? Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions such as "what could I tomorrow?" or "Which job is most suitable for me?". However, software won't be able to answer to this type of question, simple at first sight, until they know enough about users.
It is not perfectly clear to all Internet users that the words used when performing Internet searches, the IP address of the computer that launches a search and the pages which are then consulted by the people involved are precisely recorded.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own historical research and can see what they have sought, what they have clicked on. Through this, on a long-term, Recommendations, a program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more intimate answers, and we will submit products and services based on our previous statements and our saved preferences.
"What happens if someone uses my data against me, if he looks at what I'm working on?", ask the users who worry when they see the extent of the information on Google.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can arouse fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, the desire for freedom or a possible revolt against power that can arouse a counter-reaction among internet users.
It is, however, a known fact that the terms being sought are not only registered, but in some warranted cases, they are sent to a third party, and in this type of case law, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most resounding example of these times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian paedophiles, in which Google has sent the Brazilian government information that was collected on the public page called Orkut, thereby allowing identification.
Internet users concerned about human rights could heave a sigh of relief last May, when Google, arm in arm with the organization of legal electronic protection EFF, has proved its right to the court in front of the FBI. According to the pronounced judgment, in the future, Google will still not be bound by any point of the constitution to disclose information on the secret FBI demand, of whatever kind.
(Meanwhile, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 Web addresses and 1,000 research terms it gained because of the stronger child protection law, passed several years before. But ultimately, it failed to acquire the lists from investigations of individual users, or the entire list of Internet sites and keywords from the past two months.)
The judgment of Google is therefore quite inconsistent: it is attacked by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think their inner world and their private sphere suffer when they are starting to use the services of Google. Therefore, they argue against them in the spirit of revolt that protests manifest against multinational companies that take pride in their conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and its "wild boys" gathers the passionate, activists and enthusiastic computer users which emerge in many countries, consider Google as the next big businesses generation, "the trendy corporation", opposed to his rival, Microsoft, classified as a world invader because of Windows, even if both companies are fighting for the same goal.
This may be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft,   ask users neither for an identification code, nor do they ask for money for its applications. The documentary code and the package of programmes, are continually updated, are more accessible, younger and cooller, when faced against the official giant of software.
The reason may also be that the geeks see exactly what is the problematic relationship between the individual rights and the Internet, and what the Web 2.0, the most proclaimed key word in recent years, just got behind him.
Indeed, the Web 2.0 does not relate to anything other than collaboration, the fact that we intentionally leave tracks behind ourselves, and that we make use of communication channels available to us, and while the size of these changes one by one, the essence remains the same: it is exposed.
Any young person, in general, can have a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link them to other services, such as at Twitter or Last.fm, listing his musical preferences. Then he can connect those to a friend-following site, like FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also have blogs, on which their most recent photo galleries kept on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
While you may know of many examples, such as the girlfriend who understands on viewing photos in the morning,  taken  with a circle of common friends, with which her unfaithful boyfriend  has spent the evening, or the society that has dismissed one of its employees, for the honest opinions that he wrote on his blog about the top management, we can be sure of one thing:  private life needs to be  completely reconsidered these days.
He who lives a life online is whatever he shows about himself, and that is how we can define the principle behind the behavior of today's young people.
Somebody who is hiding something, or at least, wants to try to circumvent Google's monopoly, can do it (starting with, for example, Scroogle, using Google's searching system, but, at the same time, leaving no sign intentionally).
The number of people who deliberately, not register themselves on public pages in order to make it impossible to locate them, is not insignificant. Google online services, from the text treatment to the image treatment, and information reading can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not linked to a huge range of servers and witch does not  collect our best profile, having been to date.
The public expects, without really hiding it, when Google will reveal his true nature.
The company, with its current value of 156 billion dollars, is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars). The advertising domains AdWords/Adsense threaten the turnover of advertising agencies, while the benefits introduced at increasingly great speeds are causing severe headaches, not only to Microsoft, but to many other creators of computer programs.
However, the criticisms finds, in addition to all that, contradictions with worrying effects: for example, the top management of the society has declined, in its entirety, the protests of employees, after it has doubled the price of the kindergarten company and after the company found the multiple daily food at any time of the day, too expensive. All this seems insignificant compared to the fact that already in 2006, Google has acquiesced in front of the Chinese government and according the terms of their agreement, the company detects all the results that offends the good taste, and the interests of the Chinese regime too.
According one of the society’s internal rules, new services are not announced while they can be used. What is certain, is that in the coming months and years, they will change the world on new points. While some believe that Google’s project of digitizing and archiving of books and magazines takes so great dimensions that society will soon faced the Supreme Court of United States, others fears its Health system, because in this one, we can build a complete medical benefit from our previous analyses results, our doctors and our problems.
The fact that Google is setting up a genetic database can give a good raw material for the next generation of science fiction novellists. Cory Doctorow's novel, writing with orwellian semitones, described a future in which a man could be approached in a horrendous way only through Google's data.
Two minors helped to remove clues of Ózd double homicide
"The police summoned two minors to interrogate them in the double homicide of Ózd. According to well-founded suspicions, they helped to remove traces of the crime." - declared the spokesman of the police station of the Department of Borsod.
The young people have admitted the facts they are charged. At the moment, they are accused of complicity.
The two minors, who, according to the information of MTI (Hungarian Telegraphic Agency) are young girls, are defending themselves freely.
Accessory to murder can result in a prison sentence of up to 5 years.
The suspect in the double homicide of Ózd, a young local man aged 23, was remanded in custody, on Sunday.
The charges brought against him are multiple homicide, committed with premeditation and by interest.
During the inquiry, it has been revealed that the young man aged 23 years owed a large sum of money to a 53 years old man.
The suspect did not want to settle his debt and this is why he drew his lender, last Wednesday, in an area in Ózd where he killed him as well as the man's little girl, aged 9 years old.
According to information from the MTI, the young man has premeditated his crime. The weapon with which he would commit his crimes and which was hidden on the scene of crime proves it.
The police examines the weapon and the circumstances of its use with the help of specialists.
The Warsaw Stock Exchange made a proposal for the purchase of the Prague Stock Exchange
The stock exchange of Warsaw has proposed two hundred million euros, about five billion Czech kronor, for the purchase of 100% of the package of shares of the stock exchange of Prague.
Ludwik Sobolewski, president of the Warsaw stock market, confirmed this proposal that the Poles have made, despite the fact that the Czechs had previously excluded the Warsaw stock market from the circle of potential new owners of the Prague stock market.
The cause of this exclusion is that Warsaw's stock market is owned by the government.
99% of the shares are owned by the Polish State which wants to part from more than 60% of its actions within a few months of activity.
According to the Czech business newspaper E15, the proposal of Poles represents the most high which was made to date for the purchase of the Prague Stock Exchange.
According to the Czech press, the Vienna Stock Exchange, the NASDAQ Transatlantic Exchange, the New York Stock Exchange, the London Stock Exchange and Deutsche Börse made ​​an offer so far.
Koblic Petr, director of the Prague Stock Exchange, said last week that among the interested parties, the Warsaw stock market would be the the least good new owner , and has not ruled out the fact that this could lead to the disappearance of the Prague Stock Exchange in the future.
The value of the Prague Stock Exchange is estimated between 5 and 10 billion Czech crowns by market specialists.
On the basis of an agreement between the shareholders, some 90% of the papers would be sold.
The biggest owner of the Prague Stock Exchange is the investment bank Patria Finance, with about 25 percent of shares, followed by the 14.7 percent of the bank Ceská Sporitelna and Tiger Holding Four S.a.r.l. with 13.5 percent.
The financial crisis from the point of view of the European press
In their comments Tuesday dedicated to the international financial crisis, which worsens day to day, the leading newspapers of the European press already evoked a "second 11 September."
"The global financial disaster, we owe it to the American president," accuses the Rome daily La Repubblica. "The president has not even been able to form a bloc within his own party to get behind a quickly improvised bill aimed at bringing aid to a desperate situation."
Instead of a new Pearl Harbour, as evoked by the billionaire Warren Buffett, it is more appropriate to talk of a second 11 September.
A part of the Madrid press also sees the scapegoat in Washington.
According to the view of the daily newspaper El Mundo, it is the lack of political leadership there which led the world economy to the brink of collapse.
The danger of the collapse of the American financial system is growing every day; and afterwards, the whole world will pay dearly.
Bush's plan was far from perfect, however, according to the vote in Congress, there is a real threat : that Washington does not suggest a political tool to curb the crisis.
The world economy hangs in the vacuum, just at the moment when in the history of capitalism, one of the biggest changes is taking place.
We cannot ignore the threat any longer – underlines the Tages-Anzeiger of Geneva.
Some states can still offer a lifeline to their staggering financial institutions, and thanks to their own taxpayers' money, they can save them from bankruptcy.
Of course, if more banks collapse like dominoes, then neither money nor new improvisations will not be sufficient.
In the long term, we need members of the European Union to mind less their national self-interest, and centralize control over the financial markets.
Just Monday, the weakened financial institutions have received more than 100 billion euros - recalled the Viennese daily, Der Standard, which adds that fears that European taxpayers also will have to pay, very much, similarly to Americans in order to remedy the crisis, are becoming more and more realistic.
So far, the EU has not really dealt with the crisis, which, like a tsunami, crosses, from side to side, the old continent.
The "rescuers" should not give away 100 billion Euros right away; on the contrary, it would be wise to think about the cases in which it would be reasonable to use taxpayer money with the goal of preventing more serious damage.
The smart car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
Which method would be better to develop technologies apt to avoid an obstacle, if it is not the imitation of a sensor for obstacles that already exists in nature?
As for example, the one of bees.
For the amazing design presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, buzzing bees first gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea which inspired them as to how they had to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini  robot car, a bio-inspired, auto-robotized command system, model BR23C, which it has equipped with the capabilities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee is its own space, ovally shaped, which in reality is very similar to our safe protection hulls, said at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the Department research and development and brand's technology public relations.
The multifaceted eye of the bee plays an important role, as it is able to see in all directions, in a 300 degree angle.
To mimic the functions of the compound eye, engineers came up with the idea of using laser telemetry.
It identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, it assesses the distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor board, who turns it into avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a split second. Then, the mini-robot, imitating the movements of a bee, immediately alters the direction of its wheels at an angle sufficient to avoid a collision.
Unlike any system that currently exists, this maneuver of avoidance happens entirely with an instinctive fashion.
"If it was not thus, the mini robot car could not respond quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and of the robotic car project.
It must respond instinctively and instantly, as this technology is correspond to the most vulnerable and most internal layer of the protection wrap, a layer where for the moment collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process should reflect what the bee do to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a trice.
As opposed to bees, the difference is not to be able to go upwards, downwards or on the diagonal, it can only have two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this manner, instead of the endless combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, one could use only rotary movement, speeding up and slowing down like maneuvers available from a mini robot car.
The BR23C uses polymer lithium batteries which are lighter and whose  energy capacity is greater, what makes their spanlife longer than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction which is essential, not the data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism must treat with just some incoming signals per second, and deal with them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with the intuitive logic based on data from previous games. In this way, it uses continuously only a few dozen kilo-octets of memory.
We do not need gigabits memory capacity, or even megaoctets.
It is the first step towards the concept of a technology for instant avoidance. According to estimates from Nissan, this system will make its entry into serialized cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its inclusion in the GPS satellite navigation system, so it can guide the driver to his destination and avoid the obstacles on his way.
A name has even been given to the overpriced baby.
The written version of the economic recovery plan of $700 billion, to redeem the troubled loans from banks, and to be used several times, is ready.
In the first round, half that amount will be spent.
Reuters announces that in the course of new debates which went on until after midnight local time on the East Coast Saturday, the leaders of Congress came to an agreement on the controversial issues that have gone on for days and days, related to the rescue plan amounting to a total of $700 billion.
"We have taken a serious step forward", said Nancy Pelosi, Democrat president of the US House of Representatives, according to whom it only remains to put the agreements on paper.
The compromise, born from the plan, is supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
The US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, said in commenting on the results of the compromise that the programme will work and will be effective, however other measures still need to be implemented. According to Pelosi, it is not question here, of the the rescue of Wall Street, but to turn the workings of the economy in the another direction.
The written version of the plan was made public before the opening of the Asian markets, on Sunday night at 8pm local time in Washington (i.e., on Monday at 2am, according to the local time in Central Europe), but has not caused a dramatic rise in the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill, the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008. Then, its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday evening, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, then the White House has also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"We are satisfied with the progress that was made last night and we very much appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and to protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, the White House spokesman.
Moreover, the program diverges from the original proposal made by the Bush administration, which said that the $700 billion should be spent all at one time, for buying back mortgages related to some of the questionable loans.
Henceforth, a maximum of half the sum of $700 billion can be spent. The first 250 billion will be issued immediately after the adoption of the law by Congress, probably on Monday. This initial amount will be used by the Treasury Secretary to buy bad loans from banks, while the use of $100 billion more will be left to the discretion of the President.
The programme will be overseen by an independent organization, in which the president of the Federal Reserve will take part too.
The spending of the second half of the 700 billion depends on a new decree in Congress.
Under the terms of the law, the Department of the Treasury will be able to put a combined strategy into place: it can, at the same time, buy dubious debts, titles on mortgages and dubious mortgages, as well as other types of toxic debt.
Experts from ministry said that bailouts can take place during an auction, but also directly.
The rule allows the companies concerned to take part in an insurance program, in which the Treasury Department guarantees the instruments which are the basis for concern, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson stated that the law provides the required tools to spend $700 billion for the financial system urgent needs such as the huge buyback of dubious claims, their insurance, or to avoid the risk of the system triggering the collapse of one or another financial institution.
"We shall take the necessary measures, in order to be ready for the enforcement of the law, as soon as it will be passed," he added.
In contrast, banking executives finding themselves in bad positions and awaiting aid from the government can expect that their severance packages, called "golden parachutes" on the other side of the Atlantic, will be limited by the government.
The wages cap is mentioned only in specific cases. Moreover, restrictions depends on the way the Treasury Secretariat proposes its help to the company.
The capping provisions state that if the Treasury Department does the buyback in the form of an auction, it will levy an additional tax on the golden parachute, unless the president of the discredited bank retires.
Immediately after the purchase of the bad debts, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amounts paid to top executives will not be excessive.
For the image to be complete, we still need to add that the existing golden parachutes are not modified. The cap only concerns new contracts, thus motivating the participation to the plan.
This is the first time in the United States history that legal ceiling limits will be in effect regarding the directors stipends - commented the commission president in charge of financial deliveries of House of Representatives, the democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the state reserves the right to buy shares in banks taking part in the plan. This way, the risk that face taxpayers diminishes, because they can even gain from the deal as soon as the economy accompanied by the saved banks get back on their feet.
The draft law says that within five years ahead, the president must submit to Congress a proposal that will rule on how the losses will be returned to taxpayers, from the financial sector.
On both sides, there were obviously those who had expressed doubts about the plan.
This is not why the American citizens commissionned us , this does not protect the dollars of taxpayers - said the Republican representative of California, Darrell Issa.
His Democrat colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur thinks that the people who are pushing the measures are the same that those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices have continued to rise
In August 2008, prices for domestic manufacturers have increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month and 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 - communicates the Central Statistical Office in Hungary.
Export sale prices have increased by 1.1 per cent compared to those of July 2008, whereas they fell by 3.9 percent compared to those from a year ago.
As a result of the fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial producer prices rose 0.7 per cent compared to those of the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to those of the previous year.
The domestic manufacturing sale prices have only progressed to a lesser extent: of 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sectors have undergone only a small increase, on the order of 0.1 percent as compared with July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the manufacturing sector of shoes and other leather items (2.8 per cent), with the manufacture of bags and belts in first place with an increase of 4.6 percent for the month, then the production of shoes with a 2.5 percent increase for the month.
The level of higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials has led to a significant monthly increase of the price of products and raw chemicals manufacturing industry (1.6 per cent).
A deflation has resulted of it in the sectors of oil processing (1.4%), in machinery and electrical equipment manufacturing (0.9 per cent) ones, and also a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1%).
The prices for paper production, the activities of publishing and printing have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry have recorded an increase between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, representing a significant amount of the national industrial use, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices put in place by the authorities from July 1st.
Compared over a 12 month period, taking into account domestic sales in the transformation sectors, it is the price of oil processing sector that has experienced the most significant rise (32.4 percent).
In the metal products manufacturing sector, there has been an increase in prices of 13.2 percent, while in the major area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices have gone up 11 percent.
Price cuts took place in the production of textiles and textile products (2.5 percent), and in the manufacturing of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 percent).
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, the price rise has fluctuated between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
In the whole manufacturing industry, prices have risen 10.2 percent over the last year.
The prices of electricity, gas, steam and water have exceeded by 18,7 percent higher those of the previous year.
Among the internal trade groups and according to sectors allocation, in August, these are the founders of profit on investments that have shown the monthly price rise the most significant (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices rose by 0.3 percent, while those of the energy producing sectors and raw materials aimed at subsequent conversion did not change as compared to the preceding month.
In August 2008, as compared to the same month in the preceding year, we witnessed the most significant increase in the areas of energy production and raw materials destined for subsequent conversion (16.8 percent).
In the sectors of production of consumer goods, an inflation of 6.8 percent was measured, while for the profit initiating sectors, a reduction of 1.4 percent.
The sale prices for export industry, in HUF, rose by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they have suffered a drop of 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In a month, our national means of payment is weakened by 1.7 per cent compared to the Euro, and 7.1 percent against the dollar. Compared to the month of August 2007, it has increased by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
Next year, will there still be need visas to go to United States?
Kinga Göncz thinks there are good opportunities so that on 12 January, the agreement American-Hungarian visa waiver to enter into effect. This is what the foreign minister said in Chicago, before the leaders of the local Hungarian community.
According to her, "now, everything depends solely on the moment during which the entry systems and electronic control across the Atlantic will be put into service. "
However, she drew attention to the fact that in the new system, there will be no entry visa, but the tourists will have to register before departure.
The head of Hungarian diplomacy will be in negotiations from today, in Washington.
He will meet the Secretary of State, Condoleezza Rice, whom he will award the Hungarian Republic's Commander's Cross with the Star of the Order of Merit, and will meet with foreign policy advisors for the presidential candidates, Democrat Barack Obama and Republican John McCain.
Barack Obama and McCain support both the plan to rescue banks
On Sunday, Barack Obama and John McCain, the two major US parties' candidates for the presidency, both expressed their support for the 700 billion dollar government rescue plan. However, some politicians are demanding the resignation of the US Treasury Secretary.
After marathons negotiations, which have lasted for days and days, the Congress representatives and the Administration have finally announced, on Sunday at dawn, that they had reached principle agreement  on the banks rescue plan.
The financing plan, aimed at thawing the crisis on Wall Street and the paralyzed credit market, became the central issue of the presidential campaign.
Obama and McCain even present themselves, each as more capable than the other, to lead the country out of the economic crisis.
According to the most recent surveys, by putting economic issues at the forefront, Obama has once again succeeded in getting himself a bit of a lead. McCain's lead, achieved by his naming of Sarah Palin as his running mate just after the Republican convention, has melted away.
During a campaign rally in Detroit on Sunday, Obama expressed his hope that Congress would vote soon on the legislation for the $700 billion rescue plan.
He stressed that the proposal contains the passages of consumer protection that he also supports.
"This is now that we have to go ahead, with responsibility (...) a danger is threatening your work, your savings, the entire industries and the stability of the whole economy", he told in front of a crowd of 35 thousands people.
He has not failed to describe the economic ideas of McCain as outdated.
In an interview given to ABC, McCain said: "We will all have difficulties to swallow it (...) but doing nothing is not a possible path".
The Republican senator said that the proposal included the creation of a commission to monitor the Treasury and the capping of severance pay for senior leaders, and that he, personally, had very strong positive feelings about these items.
Obama has told the CBS that McCain has had no role on the negotiations' substance, while he had a daily contact with the Treasury secretary.
Nancy Pelosi, president of the House of Representatives, said Sunday that there are serious hopes that the House will vote the bill on Monday.
The press review of the German language territory
The right wing is intact, it is only at the heart of the party that voters have become more aware - this is how the Der Spiegel is refering to the low score of the Bavarian Christian Social Union in Bavaria.
Haider is ready to govern Austria, to prevent the coalition of red and black.
Der Spiegel (spiegel.de.)
In the Internet edition of the German left-wing news magazine, Franz Walter analyses the causes of the dramatic defeat of the CSU in his article entitled "The revolution in Bavaria devours its fathers."
According to this acknowledged political scientist, the erosion of the CSU started long before the sad Beckstein-Huber duo took office.
Christian Socialists have transformed Bavaria for decades and now, these are the same modern citizens who are turning their backs on it.
This change of era is simultaneously the problem of all Christian democracy, and thus, the one of Angela Merker too.
For the CSU, the failure was not a complete surprise, but on Sunday, there came to an end a process that was likely just ten years before: the undisputed hegemony of the national party ended.
Ten years before that, in 1998, the CSU won with 47.7 percent, and, for the first time since the 1950s, with a total that was below 50 percent.
It was repeated three years ago, during the Bundestag elections of 2005, which is to say in the time of the much talked-about Stoiber.
The cause can be attributed to the modernisation "devouring her parents', put in place in the region so consistently by the CSU.
It has been 40 years since sociologists have announced this but they have been greatly mistaken about the pace. However, secularization, the impact of education and the immigration of Germans from the north and from the east into the region of Bavaria, in full swing, could not fail to have consequences for the loyalty of CSU voters.
An update goes hand-in-hand with increasing opportunities, and the consequences of such a policy are also visible.
The right-wing camp is intact, it is only in the core of the party that voters have become more aware, more critical and more stubborn.
It is equally astonishing that, in recent weeks, it was precisely the academic groups which were rather distant from the CSU, such as the self-employed, the artisans, the college graduates and those with post-graduate degrees.
In these groups, support for the CSU has fallen below 40 percent.
Die Presse (diepresse.com.)
In his article entitled "who ? with who ? the party chairmen remains elusive when faced with questions of the coalition" the conservative Austrian newspaper is dealing with the situation of confusing domestic policy which settled after the Austrian elections.
The Austrian Socialists of the SPÖ want to talk with the Conservatives in the ÖVP.
The ÖVP forbids the SPÖ to meddle in its internal affairs.
The populist party BZÖ is open to negotiations. The greens do not want to agree yet over the coalition.
The elections took place, now everything revolves around the coalition; during the debates on public television, the party leaders hardly showed their cards.
Werner Faymann, SPÖ president, confirmed that he wanted to discuss with ÖVP.
The SPÖ wants to show that the cooperation of both parties is indeed possible - it is what already exists in some regions and in the socialist partnership.
The question according to whether he would picture a coalition with Wilhelm Molter, the current president of the Övp, as vice-chancellor, remains open from Faymann.
As he mentioned, Schüssel-Molterer direction was, in any case, rejected.
A copy of this combination is out of point.
Molterer reacted with caution to the proposals from the red.
As he has already said, a collaboration will surely be a failure if Faymann tries to interfere with the internal affairs of the ÖVP.
In his party, the choice of opposition or entry into the coalition is for the moment an entirely open question. These points absolutely must  be debated within the ÖVP.
Jörg Haider, BZÖ president, is open again to all proposals.
"To avoid the coalition of the red and black, we are ready to assume government responsibilities," Haider said.
Járóka said: We need to break the vicious circle of poverty and segregation
Today, began in Paris, the European Summit for Equal Opportunity, of which France is the host, representing the current presidency of the European Union.
In her speech before the plenary assembly, as one of the main spokespersons of the counsel of experts, Lívia Járóka, MEP Fidesz European People's Party, drew attention to segregation in education, because this is a violation of law which most affects Roma children, and is therefore one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French presidency, this high level conference was opened in part by Xavier Bertrand, the French Minister of Labour and Social Affairs, and in part by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Work, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among the invited people to take part in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most prominent legal protection representatives and European civilian agencies, in the area of equal opportunities.
According to the public relations office of the deputy Fidesz from the Populist Party, Járóka warned that in addition to the discrimination that occurs during hiring, the Roma are disappearing from the labour market primarily due to their poor qualifications.
"An overwhelming majority of young Romani have no high-school qualifications, and as a consequence of a poor quality basic education, only a tiny part has the opportunity to obtain a high education degree."
Furthermore, Járóka has insisted that education as a fundamental right of human beings plays a key role when one has to assert the other fundamental rights.
Investing in early education of Roma children means strengthening the economy of the European Union countries.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these reports in the widest possible circle, equally between the Roma and the non-roms.
Indeed, the earlier a Romani child starts school, the more it increases his chances of becoming a productive member on labour market; by the tax paid from his income and his consumption, he is involved in the government budget.
"by their membership in the European Union, the Roma must be assured of their right to a quality education, and to be protected from a poor quality, sectarian education," Lívia Járóka emphasized.
According to the deputy, a European Union collaboration geared towards a goal and an action is needed for an immediate acceleration of the process of school desegregation. For this, abiding by the anti-discrimination directives in existence and in preparation is of paramount importance.
"We need to break the vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment. We must give Roma children the opportunities assured by democracy, so that they can participate in the future of Europe as citizens with full rights" Járóka demanded.
On behalf of "Année Européenne pour l'Égalité des Chances" guaranteed for all, the summit's aim for equality in Europe held every year since the summit in Berlin last year, is to ensure a unique platform to support the measures taken in favour of equal opportunities and for the fight against discrimination, targeted at European level and within individual countries.
CSU: Pardonned for a transition period.
It is in October that will be taken the decision on the fate of the fallen duo Huber-Beckstein
Despite this pathetic electoral failure, heads have not fallen off yet, and the debate on personal issues at the summits of the Bavarian Christian Social Union has been postponed.
The party's president, Erwin Hube and the regional government leader, Günther Beckstein, can still hold their place. The question is: When will end the grace?
The fate of the tandem, having suffered a catastrophic loss of poll of 17 percent, will be on the agenda of the special party congress, held during the last weekend of October.
Members of this heavily criticised pair have made felt that they didn't specifically wanted to hold their seats.
Thanks to this, they endeavored to appease the angry members of the group and of the base, which a day after the "Bavarian tsunami", demanded personal consequences for the loss of the absolute majority.
Five years before - admittedly still under the leadership of Edmund Stoiber at the very peak of his career - the Christian Social Union garnered 60.7 percent, while today, a year after the coup against Stoiber, only 43.4 percent of their strength remains.
During 46 years, the CSU has been the "only ruler" of Bavaria giving 18 percent of the German GDP.
But, conservatives have always had a strong presence in the southern region, which is an important key to the Hungarian economy. In the future, they will be forced to join the coalition.
As one of the first signs of an internal restructuring of the party, the vice president and the federal minister of agriculture, Horst Seehofer, presented as a possible successor to Huber, also received a place in this small reconnaissance group, which initiates discussions to feel the way ahead with the liberals of the FDP as well as with the Free Electors, long trained in the values of the right, about a possible coalition government in Munich.
A strange nose-thumbing was the help of the list of electeurs free, to enter the Gabriele Pauli into the legislation, whose the action taking against Stroiber served as a possible putsch by the duet Huber-Beckstein, to then  give a short shrift to the very ambitious municipal politics woman.
Now, leaders of the CSU put all their energy to stabilise, one way or another, Beckstein.
In this transition, Stoiber, who until now pulled the strings behind the scenes will also be given an active role. The former head of the regional government and ex-chairman of the CSU, has called September 28th the bitterest day of his political career.
Monday, Huber launched ascerbic remarks against the CDU. According to him, they would have earned a lot more support from their sister party.
Other CSU politicians have interpreted the defeat as a warning for the CDU and also for Angela Merkel.
Following the Bundestag election, which will take place in September 2009, Merkel will only be able to be Chancellor again if they restore in one way or another, with a joint force, the CSU, having played an important role in the national success of 2005.
According to Merkel, barely concealing her disappointment caused by the fiasco, the loss of ground of the CSU shall not negatively influence the grand coalition in Berlin.
Which is relative, however, because it will not be easier to manage the damaged CSU, and the Social Democrats' crisis is still ongoing.
Since 1946, the SPD has reached its worst results with 18.6 per cent in Bavaria.
Lukasenko - opponents 110 - 0.
No member of the opposition party gained any seats in the Byelorussian Parliament during Sunday's elections.
According to the Russian observers, this is explained by a country led by Alexander Lukashenko, who assures its prosperity and stability, while according to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), this is explained by illegalities committed during the counting of the votes.
The OSCE, having sent 450 observers from 43 countries, does not approve the elections.
Although the legislature composed of 110 people in this country of 10 million inhabitants does very well without the opposition since many decades, before the elections yesterday, the opposition uniting its forces under the name of United Democratic Forces (ODSZ)seriously hoped that Lukashenko, renewing his mandate as president for the fourth time during dubious elections, in the footsteps of the modification of the constitution in 2006, "would allow" this time the presence of some members of the opposition in parliament.
In this way, the ODSZ backed off from the boycott originally planned.
The fact that Belarus, increasingly economically dependent on Russia, wanted improve its relations with the EU, where because the political order of Belarus is classified as undemocratic, Lukashenko and several senior politicians do not receive entry visa, was one of the expectations of the opposition. Belarus had to take a loan because of the reduction of Russian natural gas imports, always more expensive, and thus contributed to the Beltransgaz enterprise, owner of the gas pipelines crossing the country, passing into Russian hands.
The fact that the OSCE, during the evaluation of the campaign, put the emphasis on the positive changes rather than on shortcomings, such as for instance the ban to run for a third of candidates of the opposition, made reference to a prior appeasement.
However, the OSCE communiqué on Monday challenged the campaign, during which most of the opposition candidates could not appear in the media, and particularly the fact that the opposition could not be present for the vote count.
Despite all this, the opposition still feels an sensible improvement in the political regime: the political detainees have found freedom, and Minsk is ready for small confrontation with Moscow, while still refusing to recognise South Ossetia and Abazzia that have been split from Georgia. Yet, Russia and Belarus ,who form a federation on paper have considered the two territories as independent for a month now.
"We have taken two steps forward, and a step backwards, but most important is that the dialogue has been initiated between Belarus and the EU" - said Alexander Milinkevich to our newspaper.
According to the opposition candidate in the presidential election of 2006, it is desirable for it to stay like that, despite the fact that the powers that be are afraid in this parliament which has no sway, to let in even a single opponent." 
The opposition does not foresee protest actions in light of the results. It is rather trying to get its message across on the need for economic reforms to the voters.
"We obviously have a lot of concern in this area: we need to print opponents newspapers in Russia, local authorities put up obstacles against us with regards to distribution, but I can see that there are an increasing number of people supporting the elections, even among elderly people," said Milinkevich, referring to the fact that in the current regime of Lukashenko, who considers social security as its main outcome, the segment of the officially most supported retirees no longer consider it as appropriate.
"Because of the country's indebtedness and the rise of the trade deficit, the collapse of Social Security, 'evoking the silence of a graveyard', is just a matter of time" - think Milinkevich.
Unlike the opposition politician, the Russian observers certified the  elections as democratic.
Sergei Lebedev, leader of the Commonwealth of Independent States, told the Russian news agency RIA Novosti: "People do not believe in words, but in deeds." Thus, the absence of the opposition is only proof of the maturity of the Belarussian voters.
Brunetta said: "From today, breakfast before work".
Never in the history of the Chigi Palace have we had revolving doors for the entry and exit of employees.
But from today, is in effect this new measure against the smart asses, against who they clock out and then go to drink coffee at the pub during working hours.
The new anti-idlers plan was presented today by the Minister of Public Administration, Renato Brunetta, and by the Secretary-General of the Council Presidency, Mauro Masi.
"The revolving doors - tells Brunetta - are a tool to work better, with more productivity, more attendance and more services" says the minister.
Now is starting a new season of responsibility and transparency.
"It is reformism" also stresses Brunetta.
The installation of the council presidency in every building is completing with the Chigi palace.
According to Masi, "the choice of revolving doors is important, even from a symbolic point of view.
No resistance from the employees has been recorded, the secretary general assured: "It is a process shared by employees, and we have had the cooperation of all."
In short, no more breakfast during working hours: no more coffee nor croissant.
Promise of Brunetta, suggesting with a smile, "a good 7 o'clock cappuccino in the morning is a good and healthy resolution".
During a Public Administration High School conference.
from Rome, the minister tells us that "in three months, illness related absences of public employees has been reduced by 50%, that being 60 thousand more workers in a year".
And he adds that it is essential to make the public administration more efficient.
Italian, "whose wage dynamics over these past 8-10 years - explains the minister -  have doubled in comparison to those in the private sector, and well above the rate of inflation.
Meanwhile, thousands of civil servants, united to challenge the standards of the Brunetta decree by making use of Codacons.
"while the minister of Public Office spreads today data regarding the decrease in absenteeism in the workplace because of illness - writes the consumers association- the "active lazy" people continue to rise.
Indeed, in Italy, thousands of correct and productive employees of the public administration, gathered to declare war on illegitimate standards, contained in the decree.
In particular, in Tar, we question the prohibition of extra allowances in case of service disability; the extension of ill worker’s  house working hours, during which there are inspections, and other aspects of the new rules proposed by the minister.
Accidents in the workplace, Napolitano: "prevention is crucial."
Every day, in Italy, one day, there are 2,500 work accidents, 3 deaths and 27 people who are disabled permanently.
INAIL's data confirms, in fact, that in 2007 there were about 1,200 white deaths.
The figures indicate the gravity of the phenomenon, which remains one of the main causes of death, and causes almost twice as many deaths as homicides.
To focus the attention of institutions, social forces and sources of information on this dramatic issue, ANMIL celebrates today, in all Italian provinces, the 58th national day for victims of accidents at work, established as the second Sunday in October.
"The disturbing information provided by ANMIL, as well as the tragic events of recent days, confirm the importance of prevention in the workplace," says Italian President Giorgio Napolitano in a message sent to Pietro Mercandelli, President of ANMIL, the national association of those who have been injured and disabled in the workplace.
The head of state expressed his "sincere appreciation for the collaborative ongoing effort with respect to prevention in the workplace, protection of injured workers, assistance to families of victims and sensitization of public opinion."
"Naturally indignant, everyone hit the table to put an end to such tragedies which, by their size, raise the rest of media and the participation of people opinion, even if the daily reality presents the dramatic and even repetitive cases in their dynamic.
Napolitano does not deny that "there is certainly a problem as to resources: it is essential to invest in training and information."
The many initiatives promoted in the schools bear a special significance for greater awareness of the young people entering the work force.
It is our duty to keep attention focused on this phenomenon, not to underestimate the alarm about its societal importance, implement and improve the legislative standards.
For its part, the president of the Gianfranco Fini House has pointed out how much "this phenomenon of white dead is a real social emergency, who insult each of us conscience, and requires all institutions, to make a real effort to end it quickly".
The data of people injured at work appear to indicate a slight positive trend, but that does not prevent that the number of white deaths is still impressive" has the president of the Anmil Pietro Mercandelli later underlined.
"We do not want that this 'trend toward on the cheap' actually translates into diminished attention because it is precisely when attention relaxes that tragedy occurs".
"We believe that in general, we are not doing enough to contrast the phenomenon of accidents and this contrast can be done through multiple actions."
"We believe - Mercandelli emphasized - more checks and inspections are necessary, like greater intervention into the training of workers, from school onward."
He added "that yet another effort must be done concerning communication and raising public awareness.
"But the more important, a greater sense of responsibility from employers facing a phenomenon that represents a social emergency."
"Mercandelli subsequently denounced 'the safeguard conditions progressive deterioration of the work victims compensation' and 'the assistance drift where the system is moving last years'.
"The objective thus, is for giving the worker the guarantee of insurance – he added - so that the fate of anyone who has an accident, should not depend on the spontaneity or the widening of the legislature."
Finger pointed at MP3 players, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for a protracted period using portable music devices, such as MP3 players, can cause permanent damage to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission announce, in a statement circulated in Brussels, quoting the Scientific Committee on the unexpected and recently identified health risks in EU(Csrseri), published today.
"From this scientific report - let us read in the footnote - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, during a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable music devices, for more than one hour per day per week, risk a permanent hearing loss."
"I am concerned by the fact that a significant number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at full volume may unknowingly damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data - the responsible Ue continues - it is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters most is to raise the awareness of consumers and to make public this information.
We need to check again the existing control systems, given the scientific opinion, in order to make them entirely effective and that can follow new technologies. "
Brussels has asked the independent scientific committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"The scientists - concludes Ue executives - confirm that there are good reasons to worry, and that the European Commission will now examinate with the member countries and other interested parties, which measures could possibly be adopted to protect children and adolescents in a better way against exposure to noise from portable music devices and appliances.
There is already a European standard for security, which limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100db, but the concern is growing about the hearing damages that could come from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to adequately limit these data making use of solutions like reduction of levels and of the duration of exposure to noise.
The EU Scientific Committee pointed out that users of portable music devices who listen to music at full volume (over 89 decibels) for five hours per week are exceeding the limits currently in force as to the maximum acceptable level of noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods, are at risk of permanent hearing loss after 5 years.
This interests 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 to 10 million people in the A.E.
Rome: Alemanno gave the start-up order to the Commission for the Future of the Capital.
Today we begin, in March we will finish, in June we will reap the benefits.
This is the schedule set by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the future of Capital Rome", which took place this morning, at the new seat behind the Baths of Caracalla.
In six months, President Antonio Marzano and 49 other members of the Commission will develop the directives for Rome.
In March, when they have finished, the Committee and the Council will assess the analyses and the projects, so as to present the strategic plan for Rome in June, with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and its mayor, Gianni Alemanno.
"The Commission is completely independent; all political, social and cultural ideas are represented on it, Alemanno stressed - it will have to propose development ideas for Rome, which can be used by the political decision makers, which are still the Committee and the Community Council.
No overlapping roles, but only the desire to have a setting in which to create a great project for Rome.
In March, it will have finished its work and will then disappear, because this assignment must be of precisely limited duration.
In juin-annonce the mayor- we will present the strategic plan issue from the future Rome Capital's Commission 's work. "
For those who accuse the commission to be unnecessary, given that his views will not be binding, Alemanno replies: "Everything depends on the work that the Commission will be able to do, as well as the quality of its proposals.
If the quality is there, as in France, thanks to the Attali Commission, as in Rome besides, I am sure of it, its contribution will be crucial.
Too often politics is overwhelmed by the management of everyday life and emergencies that arise from time to time.
We, on the contrary, want to look forward, and further, toward a far greater prospective, working seriously on the development of Rome and its future."
In addition, the Mayor of Rome insists on pointing out that "this committee is not a useless body or a bureaucratic group: it is absolutely free, and will not cost Roman citizens a penny, and it will serve to get information from and obtain the participation of the best minds that express the sentiments of the capital city.
To Alemanno, indeed, "it should be a draft strategic reference neither firm nor immobile, to allow our city, to improve itself, with is absolutely necessary, while thinking about its future maintaining a spirit of unity,".
A future that, says the mayor of Rome, "will not be limited to the usual local borders, but that will look further" not only as regards the future metropolitan city and its legal status of Capital, but "also as regards the role that Rome can and must have, as Capital of Europe and the Mediterranean".
Obama? The first anti-American president. This is why.
A famous American politician who wants to be considered independent, wrote: "Barack Obama will be the second anti-American president.
The first was Jimmy Carter, who, with his decisions, destroyed the US economy and had a relationship (as he still has today, as a private citizen) with the enemy Islam."
The attacks against Obama increase as the date of the elections are getting closer.
A woman from Miami has written on a website: "This person is full of ambition".
Obama is really full of himself: he believes he will win the highest office in a country which has altogether two black governors and five black senators!"
In actual fact, these are attacks which mean very little; they are obviously attacks of a racial nature, and do not answer the question of all the voters: Will he be a good president? We have, in addition, the polls, which all say that Obama will win and by a good margin.
In this case, it is again someone who speaks from the heart and not from the brain.
A Mississippi newspaper, in the South United States innards, wrote an article: once in the voting booth, we well know who the American Patriot will give his vote to.
Here is one aspect of the American mindset kept secret until the end.
"Say whatever you want, we shall see ourselves where to put the cross, on Obama or on McCain.
There are even people who swear: If Obama wins, we will leave from the United States.
Things never revealed till now, so much so that the success of the black candidate seems almost certain.
Anyway, despite all these arguments, the winning card for the Democrats is George Bush.
It was asked to 1500 people: What were the mistakes made by Bush during his term ? 89 percent replied: Iraq.
America is changing.
In Vietnam, this nation has lost 50 thousand soldiers and was sent back home with a kick in the ass.
In Iraq, 4500 soldiers have lost their lives, and Americans have not been forced to pack their bags.
Despite this, Iraq was, for most, the weakness of Bush.
Who will take the place of George W will have an enormous task to accomplish.
USA, the economic debacle is felt even among journalists: in the press is the time for deletions and many blame the Internet, this "assassin" of the print newspaper.
The Pew Research Center questioned five American hundred journalists about the status of their profession and about mind control in the future.
Well, almost all journalists are pessimistic about their future.
However, they have not openly declared to the press attaches, to be feeling less worried about the credibility.
They do not feel isolated as in the past.
The problem of American journalists, it is money, the money.
The 2008 crisis for these journalists is a crisis of destroyed economic model.
In addition, the losses incurred in the newsroom, in the room where the editors work at assembling the newspapers, are a big problem.
This is a problem that must be resolved, according to the journalists interviewed, since one hopes that traditional media such as the public understands it, will not be reduced substantially.
A clear but complex pessimism invades the American journalism.
Six in ten senior executives and journalists from printed newspapers are convinced that journalism at national level is heading the wrong way.
Locally, the executive group is at 65%.
Printed publication against broadcast.
Journalists have no difficulty in seeing where the web in going.
The larger edition homes are spawning themselves a shift towards internet, seen by many as the 'murderer' of newspaper.
The "economic pressure" that the journalists were feeling, increased up to 79%.
The 500 interviewed journalists admitted taking to technology hoping it "will do something good" for their journalism.
Today, the largest hitch in the American journalism is between those who run the newsrooms- i.e. the directors- and reporters who work for them.
56% of managers at national level, are convinced that the reporters share their values, whereas at local level, this percentage goes down to 23%.
For some, this is linked to "work safety."
The directors who plan to lose their job within 3 years, are of 47% of the national level.
Concerning journalists, we are heading towards 30%.
The one of "safe working" concerning the staff (our writers, ed) in America is still on the agenda.
Only 13% of journalists work under contract.
In such a vast nation as the United States, with 300 million people and thousands of journalists, magazines, radio, television and Internet, employers often offer what they want, and it is fast becoming an issue of taking or leaving.
Directors almost always earn big wages, whereas the editor can earn ten thousand dollars per month, besides pension and the payment of insurances.
Concerning holiday, the logic becomes complicated: x days after the first year, x days after the third, up to 15 days in all, after a certain number of years.
But, according to their disclosure, American journalists are often "sick" during the year.
It is the fault of the climate.
Unipol: Rome courthouse, Danilo Coppola stays in Grottaferrata.
The President of the second section of the criminal court in Rome, Carmelo Rinaudo, decided to reject the judgment pertaining to the estate agent, Danilo Coppola, who had asked to leave his city of Grottaferrata in order to settle in Rome.
. Coppola is investigated for bankruptcy as part of training relative to the Unipol-Bnl escalation.
During the trial, last week, he had obtained release home turned into residence requirement in Grottaferrata.
His lawyers, Michele Gentiloni and Gaetano Pecorella, had demanded that the estate agent be able to travel the route between the provincial village and a house in the capital.
According to the court, such freedom of movement (which the PM has not granted) would enable him to influence his company and to have access to the evidence against him.
Elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already been seen a few days ago, with the House of Representatives vote against the $700 billion rescue plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And yesterday’s New York Times confirms it well announcing that the current crisis divides the Republican party, even more divided between his East Coast old soul, moderated, pro-federal institutions and pro-business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to « those of Washington » and to the world of finance, powerful especially in central and southern states.
The soul, precisely, which has made itself feel in a despotic way with the vote which I mentioned at the beginning.
However what has been mentioned is only one example of the changes, the big changes that the ongoing economic earthquake pre-announce or let already guess: not only in the United States, but everywhere in the West, and may be not just there.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating phenomena hatching for some time, to the point where, in the new climate, they are solidifying and coming forth.
The first of these phenomena is the updating, the extraordinary stimulus, of the sovereign-state double category compared to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, indeed, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that have, obviously close relationships abroad, but who, above all, are involved on a large scale with the balance sheets of people and families who live in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: i.e., how to respond to the difficulties and the protests of individuals and families who are not voters.
In short, the crisis appears economically worldwide, but politically, it is here nearly national.
The political internationalization really seems to be overtaked or, have little to say about that: the obvious evidence is provided by the European Union, which as usual, shared between the various interests and the various national strategies, not succeed to decide any common policy.
And so, it is from the government of each state that all are waiting for speeches, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and especially a credits affection: when one’s going through a difficult period, only the States have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back in place.
They also possess the necessary resources and the legitimacy to use them: two priceless resources, elements which no market or international organization can ever use in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the crisis of the nation-state is moreover in perfect harmony with the continuing major importance that the most recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor somewhat related to this item: territoriality.
Indeed, paradoxically, when we were convinced to be entered from then in the Kingdom of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the equipment failure, convinced that global finance was now intended to dominate world we realized just like that, that on the contrary our future will have to settle scores more and more with little material things such as water, harvest, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another one on Earth, but which are definitively linked to a restricted area, a territory.
Thus, which is sovereign, has certainly more cards than that which is not, i.e., anyone who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and water.
I now come to the second novelty, however, which predicts a fracture.
He who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and thus Leadership.
Accordingly, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomenae .
On one side, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who will know how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a disrepute wave for the existing leaderships, economic species that have been proved inadequate and full of dark areas.
And furthermore, something even more profound, and in some sense, even worrying: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of leaders in a growing number of countries in the West.
Thus increases even more the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now to their apogee, their way of listening and of being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have same time, and to be increasingly more foreign with the opinions of the majorities.
In short, the demand for leadership is growing in a subterranean way, a powerful and multi-pronged movement of de-legitimizations of the ruling classes and the traditional political orders, which is being manifested in spontaneous electoral "revolts" and in the collective changes in mood very recently, from the conservative ascent in Bavarian Austria to the fall of the Labourites in Britain, to the rebellion of the American Congress against Bush (and it well may be that the victory of the right in Italy did not happen by chance).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, and also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their dimensions, one might say, still have more difficulty, which did not simply start today, in understanding and therefore explaining the deeper layers of Western societies and the fact that the economic crisis is magnifying, increasing and potentially creating a disturbance to an inordinate extent.
Seeing all this, to talk of a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda, seems frankly exaggerated.
But one says well, to keep one's eyes wide open, it is not without reason.
The super glue to walk on the walls.
Defeating the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue, and in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the objective of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutions has almost succeeded at it.
With an adhesive measuring barely 2.5 square centimetres, researchers have succeeded in keeping stuck a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
Study- the American magazine Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, of Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular structure of carbon, called nano tubes of carbon.
"The principle of the glue can be imagined as a series of tubes diperses as a pile of spaghetti." says Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the legs of geckos, which are overlaid by microscopic hair which ensure the animal, a perfect adherence.
Tests performed on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and sandpaper, have proved that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and also, that he "peels off easily from the walls," explains Liming Dai, researcher in the engineering faculty of University of Dayton.
Walk on the walls? – 'this material could be used as temporary scotch-tape" adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on the walls as Spiderman? Maybe that yes, but researchers think of a use much less fascinating such as the connection between electronic appliances, given that the carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could concern aerospace engineering.
For now, no super heroes.
Other Research - The University of Berkeley, in California, is doing it also, in the search for a new adhesive.
In an article in the Journal of the American Chemical Society,  California researchers introduced an adhesive made up of microfibers, like hairs, which clean dust off themselves during their movement over a surface to guarantee a perfect and constant grip.
Drugs: never with fruit juice.
caution on Pamplemousse juice, of orange and apple.
These drinks, consumed particularly in the summer because they are thirst-quenching and rich in vitamins, if combined with some vital medications, affect absorption, either amplifying or lessening their efficacy, with very serious possible consequences with respect to health.
David nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the fruit juices risks, fresh or in can, if associated with certain medicines ingestion; during the 236th American Chemical Society national meeting underway in Philadelphia, he launches a new alarm: a glass of grapefruit, orange or apple juice is enough to reduce the some vital medicines absorption, canceling their beneficial effects and putting a risk on patients' health.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized because it is held responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrythmics, antibiotics, tranquilizers, antihistamines and neurological medications up to toxic levels.
MEDICATIONS AT RISK - The Italian medications agency gave us this news in a newsletter dated two years ago, alerting doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger of this mix and to pay attention to what one drinks, if one is taking a medicine such as diazepam or methadone.
Not only grapefruit- according to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit medicines.
There is a long list of active ingredients whose effects are inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Hence, the calling of Michele Carruba, director of the department of pharmacology at the University of Milan: "These findings are in general, immediately reported to the various national and international agencies of medicines that should if needed, change the medecines informative notes.
One should always read the papers that illustrates medicines that one takes, and, if something is not clear, one shouldn't be impressed, but ask clearly to the doctor or the pharmacist "underlined the expert at the agency ANSA.
The Nobel in economics to Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize for Economy has been given to American Paul Krugman for his research on models of trade and the locations of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is also a famous columnist of The New York Times.
Krugman is one of the greatest criticism of the solutions in economy and foreign policy of the Bush administration.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, during the days of Enron's collapse, Krugman wrote, in an article published in the New York Times, that the second event would have been more crucial than the first one, in terms of consequences on the US history.
A prediction which unleashed many controversies, and which was blamed upon the economist for years, but which now has proved accurate.
"I am surprised and even a little shocked of the speed with which the memory of scandals such as the collapse of Enron or WorldCom, have disappeared from public attention," said Krugman at the end of 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, of the executive committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an "economist of great value, but also a divulger with a very aggressive style", particularly critical towards the excessive liberalism of the Bush administration.
Open Office, here is the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package.
This is the day of the release of OpenOffice.org.3.0, the open source personal productivity suite, which aims to reach still more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, providing a free alternative to the most famous Microsoft Office.
Following almost a year of work, done by volunteers, supervised by SUN Microsystem, the new package Open Office is shown to the public with several new features: from the welcome screen, and the interface which was reviewed and has become less austere, to other more important ones, such as the compatibility developed for the Apple MAC OS X operating system, and support for the new ODF format (Open Document Format) 1.2, the latest ISO standard version.
Open Office has especially been focusing on the interaction with the Office 2007 suite, and it is indeed possible to open documents with the new Microsoft extension  (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx)
Also interesting, certain function specific to particular modules, such as the one which can reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, a useful example, to send them by e-mail, or to import PDF files into graphical modules while retaining the original appearance of the page.
Still on this front, it is possible to create "PDF hybrid" documents which combine the graphics typical of the Adobe format with the elements of a spreadsheet or a text editor.
The collaboration between several person is something that had various improvements within the applications: with the calcul sheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts about changes, in development of texts, because each employee had a colour of comments for greater recognition in the review phase.
Some companies are even working to bring some functions of OpenOffice to the Web (in the cloud), and in the coming weeks, they should be releasing the final version.
The Italian version is downloadable at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.htmlet and adds up to the English version that was on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is as usual also available for the Linux operating system.
Upon request, the CD of installation can be shipped home or to the workplace.
And if the theme of gratuitousness can be a way for spread it in the houses, it is precisely in the business, that Open Office suite attempts the big challenge, already counting on various projects carried out in public administration and schools.
Not to mention the realities that offer training service, consultations and assistance, ideal for small and medium-sized firms, which might also be open to future business prospects.
Open Office is composed of five main modules: writer, for the video writing equivalent of word; CALC, is a spreadsheet that aims to replace excel; impress, meant to rival PowerPoint presentations, dBase, like the famous access, is the programme that allows us to work on databases; finally draw is the graphic module.
Target for 2008, reach 5 millions download, and considering that today there are almost 3.6 million, it is likely that, with the release of the new version, the predicted figure could even be exceed
Kohl is positive too, it is the fourth case of doping.
A new case of a positive drug result at the last Tour de France: this refers to Bernhard Kohl, the Austrian from the Gerolsteiner team, who  qualified third and was the winner of the jersey for the best climber.
It is the site of the L'Equipe newspaper which reported the news.
Kohl, 26 years old, is the fourth cyclist tested positive for Cera, the Epo of the third generation after the Italian Riccardo Riccò and Leonardo Piepoli, and German Stefan Schumacher, also from Gerolsteiner.
The blood tests carried out on the test tubes of Kohl are part of those made in recent weeks, by the laboratories in Lausanne and Chatenay-Malabry.
If the cons-analysis confirm the positivity for Cera, the Austrian will lose his third place at the Tour and will have to necessarily expect two years of elimination.
The news of Kohl's positive reaction to the third generation EPO test was confirmed by Bordry Stone, the head of the French anti-doping agency, who told the Associated Press that he had notified the Austrian authorities of the positive reaction.
The 26-year-old Austrian was placed on the podium behind the Spaniard Carlos Sastre and the American Cadel Evans, thus taking the jersey with the green dots for Best Climber.
Immigrants: New York Times wonders if Italy is racist?
Italy "as an immigrants country recently turned into a privileged destination for immigrants" welcomed with resistance.
Does this turn the beautiful country into a nation of racists? That is the question posed by the New York Times which has dedicated a long article to discussing the subject of racism in Italy, based on the case of young Abdul William Guibre, a native of Burkina Faso, killed last month in Milan for stealing a box of cookies.
This case highlights what the New York Times describes as "the paradox of the North": the northern regions are at the same time the ones where there is "more integration and more work," but also "the strongest anti-immigrant sentiment in the country and the greatest support for the Northern League."
Confirming the increasing tension between Italians and immigrants, the NYT also made reference to episodes of intolerance in Milan, Parma, Rome, Ciampino and Castel Volturno.
Not only.
Even the new legilature sought by Lega to curb immigration and facilitate the return of illegal immigrants, is cited as evidence of climate change in Italy.
Trend underlined by the Pope and also by the President of the Republic: "Giorgio Napolitano during his neeting with Benoît XVI on Quirinal, asked what the state and the church are working on together to overcome racism."
Students victims of high rents, up to 900 Euro for a room.
The renting market for students does not know any crisis
According to the latest survey of Sunia, the tenants' union, to rent a simple room can cost a student up to 900 Euros in Milan, 700 in Florenc, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very seriously aspect to the extend that exclude whole groups of youth to study right because of the very high overall costs that origin families must support - explains the responsible of studies department of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand from students has so distorted the market that a widespread increase process begin even for residents.
In most cases, the rental offers in addition include a series of violations: free-type contract, unregistered, without rental limits, sub-rentals.
For the Sunia, exceptional measures through the taxation review, are needed to calm prices.
Reading the investigation, in detail, we see that in Milan, for a one-bedroom in the area of Brianza, one needs around 450 Euros; for a studio, one goes from a minimum of 650 Euros (area of Bande Nere), to an average value of 800 (area of Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 Euros (area of Vittoria.)
In Florence, a bed costs, on average, 350/400 euros, a room around 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas close to the university, it costs 250 / 280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a simple room.
In Rome, in the areas near the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), they charge about 600 Euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euros for a simple) for the areas close to the other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can only save if you distance yourself in the outlying areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a simple in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar areas.
In Naples, you need 300/400 euros for a bed. For a single size, we spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas of Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for a bed, it takes 250 / 350 euros, at least 350 for a singles.
In smaller towns, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a great importance in the cities economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by students from outside the community, there is an anomaly: the rent asked for foreign students is increased by 25 / 30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Goodbye old Cinema Paradiso, cities are getting rid of the historic movie palaces.
The historic movie theatres are closing in favour of multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city , it is like a face without eyes."
The picture provided by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, well shows what happens in major Italian suburbs, but also in the countryside cities.
The marginalisation process of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of big multirooms, and the death of consomption of Mono rooms in the cities's central areas, is one of the major events which seems us to be inevitable and undisputable; moreover, it has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, it is often historic and full of memory places, "it is like one of my friend disappeared, someone we known, with whom we shared a bit of the road and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, the film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar and the Grand Prize at Cannes juror, and witch was telling the poetry of a provincial auditorium, and nostalgia for a way to experience cinema, maybe forever lost.
The figures provided by ANEC, the main Association of Traders, shows everything: the last five years, 316 traditional movie theaters shut down, and these are the main cities' movie houses which have paid the bill: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan and Rome, Naples, Bologna, 6, at least in less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, the Roman Emily is at the top with 82 single-room cinemas lost, followed by the Tuscany (44) and the Lombardy (41).
The evidence which confirms that the advent of the multiplex is indeed primarily responsible for their demise is that these are the three Italian regions that have the most new multi-theater movie houses: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and the same number in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian operation has expanded in an irrational fashion," observes Paolo Protti, president of the ANEC," it is useful to build new structures, but it is still necessary to ensure the survival of those that already exist, because when a movie theater closes in a city, the people who frequent it are not all necessarily prepared to go to the multiplex.
Without mentioning the missed deliberation of the credit for shopkeepers: the antecedent debt of the State is around 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the government does not abide by the existing laws.
To support the industry will require between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about these closures, decided to resolve the situation with the signing of a agreement between City Hall and ANEC, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote single-room movie houses in historic city centers and on the outskirts.
Among the expected norms, there are state tax measures in favour of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special rates for parking spaces and in certain parking garages.
"It is an initiative that I am very fond of" note Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by establishing other measures.
However, it is clear that, in order to contrast the superpower of the multiplex rooms, the traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public of today is more demanding.
Traditional movie theaters defence is a concern which has always been important for me: the closure of the Bagheria's Supercinema, place of my childhood and teenage, was the spark that convinced me to make 'New Movie House Paradiso' which I thought already 10 years ago.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and every time I walk by the Rialto  or the Quirinal de Via Nazionale, now both closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, I look the other way so as not to see the worn-down signs covered in dirt.
Links between politics and 'Ndrangheta, arrested Mayor of Gioia Tauro.
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was prepared to align the town hall's choices to the interests of the Piromalli clan."
Serious charges have been leveled by the magistrates in the Anti-Mafia Directorate of Calabria regarding the Mayor and the Vice-Mayor of Gioia Tauro, Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavione, and the Mayor of Rosarno, Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for Mafia association.
Handcuffs too for Gioacchino Piromalli, the former mediator between the clan and public administrations, and his grandson lawyer, namesake of the boss, already convicted of criminal association of a mafia type, and to pay 10 million euros.
"an affront to the legal and moral norms, and especially to common sense," the prosecutors write, the two local authorities had expressed willingness to pay for consultations to Master Piromalli.
"The clan was thus granted - the judges write - official access inside the town halls facilitating the possibilities, already considerable, of control and orientation from the public administration."
The president of the Calabrian regional committee Agazio Loiero, does not hide that 'collusions between local comittees and crime organizations, there are more than one of these " in his region:" There are places where the Mafia has a stronger influence than in others, where the collusion is almost inevitable.
But there is also a lot of politicians who resist the pressures from the Ndrangheta, heroes who are honest"
The arrests of this morning follow those of last July, following which the police announced having decapitated the Piromalli clan.
At the end of last April, the city council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved; back in 1991, and always because of alleged conditions between organised crime and the local administration, local politicians had been discharged of their duties to administer the city.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, mayor of the UDC during the dissolution, had been appointed head of a center-right coalition, after the second ballot in May 2006.
He called it a scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the city council.
He accused the Vice Interior Minister at the time, Marco Minniti, accusing him of having engineered the whole thing for political purposes, but in view of the order of incarceration signed this morning, the judges explain that the Piromalli clan had even succeeded in their request for a variance in the A3 project.
Starting interceptions ordered against Dal Torrione, the PM writes, is emerged « the availability to marry expectations of a businessman, representing a more well-known group, close to the Piromalli, unifying the choices of public administration to the interests of the clan.
When the energy is born of waves, now the big ones are engaging.
Here is an enormous source which occupies over 70% of the surface of the planet and now big global energy firms are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, here are the new renewable sources on which colossi such as Chevron have set eyes, and are now trying to lay hands.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movement of the sea has been considered for a hundred years; and in the 1970s, at the time of the first oil crisis, research was intensified.
When oil prices lowered, around 1980, the idea of exploiting the marine energy was sidelined, but now the environmentalists and the new increase of oil prices give a big rise to the sector
The World Energy Council (WEC) of London valued in 2007, that 15% of worldwide electricity need could be covered by systems exploiting seas swell.
That amount would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power stations.
And furthermore, there would be the currents and the tides..
Colossi to attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been the Enersis, who in 2005, has signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it didn't really seem revolutionary.
Two years later, still more candidates among these companies which have always been dedicated to traditional energy are banking on marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying the technologies on oceanic energy- said the spokesman of a company associated with the American oil giant, to the economic daily Wall Street Journal- and it evaluates opportunities to cooperate with us."
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit from  the US Energy Commission for the energy needed to set up a project of marine energy exploitation in Alaska.
This is a very interesting sign, especially if you consider that the US continues to extract oil in Alaska and President Bush recently set up a project for new drilling.
Outside of Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which go the route of energy derived from the sea; and while their details are not known, the amounts invested up to now indicate a growing interest, according to observers.
Technology tuning.
The experts are stating about a technology still in its infancy, from the fact that marine energy did not dispel fears concerning environmental impact.
At the time being, systems like those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small, and do not seem to create big problem to the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large-scale, however, one must use technologies with a higher environmental impact.
"And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The pressure of the waves, which moves the mud up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders inside the floaters.
The pressure causes the turbine to spin which in its turn, feeds a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through underwater cables.
For now, we have four systems of this sort in the planning stage, in anticipation of a single federal approval and part of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the contrary, already produces the energy for a commercial center and a parking lot, using six underwater turbines in the East River in New York.
The movement of the water at the tides turns the turbines' blades, creating a rotary motion which feeds a generator.
Verdant said that it had a long list of customers waiting needed permissions to draw some energy.
After the waves, tides.
A special interest, they say at the electric power Institute of Research, is deserving at the moment, the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tide is more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
And it is precisely on tides energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, with others, look toward the coasts, have invested $ 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and will invest up to 35 million in 2009.
Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will fly away to Oslo in Norway, where he will stay 26 hours and become the fourth American president in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The diploma, the medal and the $1.4 million check will be presented to him for his exceptional efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The leader of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis, and will have a busy programme.
He will go first to the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the very first time the five Committee members who have chosen him in October amongst 172 people and 33 organisations.
The schedule of the presidential couple then plans a meeting with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
The visit will reach its peak during the afternoon at a formal ceremony where Obama will be awarded the prestigious prize.
It will be the fourth American president to receive it, but only the third who will be awarded the prize in the precincts of the committee
The White House has informed in advance that Obama will speak about the war in Afghanistan during award.
The president does not want to avoid this issue because he is aware that he is awarded the prize as a president currently leading a war in two countries.
He has strengthened the war effort one more time a few days ago by sending additional units in Afghanistan, something that none of its critics will forget to stress.
During the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for 10 million Swedish crowns (approximately 1.1 million Euros).
He intends to donate to charities, but he has not decided yet in practice which one.
His busy programme will then take him along with his wife to a banquet, including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant to this price at the beginning.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling that he hadn't fully earned it.
He also repeated several times that it's not a price for him only, but for all those who defend the same values.
Right after the announcement, he said that it would be for him an "invitation to act".
A defender of nature accused of blackmail
The police of Litoměřice have accused of blackmail the president of the association Society of the protectors of nature of Litoměřice.
Several times last year he appealed for a number of proceedings related to construction sites and demanded money from investors for his personal gain in exchange for the withdrawal of those appeals, said Alena Romová, spokesman for the police in Litoměřice.
The president of the Society of Nature Preservationists of Litoměřice is Lubomír Studnička.
He is currently in detention and risks up to three-year imprisonment.
The waste sorting bins are not in the know in Brno
In Prague everyone can sort out his own beverage packaging, while in the villages of Southern Moravia you come across sorting bins on every street corner.
And in Brno?
Here, you would need to take several minutes before finding the adequate dumpsters.
I do not mean that we do not sort out Brno' waste.
But I have the feeling that councillors in our city, the second largest city, are not interested enough in this problem.
Brno is in the stone age when it comes to sorting waste, not only because people can still sort only paper, glass and PVC, but especially because of the number of bins devoted to these wastes.
Have you ever tried to drop a plastic bottle in the downtown ?
It is a whole science, which requires above all time and nerves of steel.
The only place I have found for the time being, is the place of Moravia, in front of Potrefena Husa.
Mr Onderka and his colleagues please do not bear me a grudge, but it seems damn little to me.
Without mentioning the fact that in other parts of the city it is not easy either.
And finally, many of my friends don't sort out their wastes.
Out of laziness.
It is a good step for them to reach the skips.
That does not surprise me from them.
After a festival, I have offered to go throw a few bottles of glass and PVC.
Except that I saw no coloured dump-truck on Kounicova Street.
Fortunately I found the proper place while going to take the tram.
That said, waste were overflowing.
It is after all the centre of Brno, which is supposed to represent the city at best, isn't it?!
It is probably because ecology and so-called esthetics don't really interest the Socialists in Brno too much.
That they prefer to buy the city a place in the first hockey league is a disgrace to the city throughout the country, instead of buying a few extra skips and providing more of the sort of raw materials for a cleaner Brno.
I am glad to have been able to reinforce my impression with official statistics after having taken a moment to check the internet.
According to data from the EKO-KOM Company, Brno really is the worst in the whole region of south Moravia.
The budget of Paroubek has removed money from the pensions and the sick leaves.
After the Left has grown, despite the opinion of the government, the farmers or even the bureaucrats there may be a lack of money for pensions, sick leave or housing allowances.
But also for the interest on debt of the state or internationnal judicial proceedings.
This will increase the problems of those who will govern in the second half of next year, says the finance minister Eduard Janota.
When the Social Democrats and Communists imposed the increase for some classes, they based it on the fact that the government will make loans for sensible spending, pensions or medical leave. "This only puts the problems off until later, planting mines in the ground," said Janota.
It is necessary to know that on borrowed money the interests to pay are more and more high and that it must be returned sooner or later.
The State does not really have the choice to know where to draw money.
If he does not reduce welfare or spendings, he will have to raise taxes.
To all those that the left-wing has presently risen: firemen, teachers, farmers.
And thereafter, to their children.
People will get them and should not fear for their pensions or their health insurance, of which 1.8 billion have disappeared.
But at the expense of greater indebtedness on the part of the State - next year its coffers will be short not 163 billion, but more.
Despite the efforts of minister Janota the debt is thus going to grow faster and faster and with it, the expenses related to the interests.
The State will need money to pay her back and it won't be enough to increase slightly the VAT or to reduce the maternity leave as the government did it in its anti-deficit package.
Five billion will also be missing to complete the construction of roads and railways because of the transfer of money to a few groups of voters.
It is mainly about parts which have already been decided and are underway, so it is not possible to change the projects to possibly reduce their costs.
At most to keep them, which is not free either.
This means delaying or stop 30 major sites, and the removal of European funds is also in danger, according to Karel Hanzelka's warning, ministry of transport spokesman.
The ČSSD has proposed to solve the financial deficit very deftly - it will draw from the dividends of ČEZ (producer and distributor of electrical energy), of which the State is the major shareholder to feed the transport fund.
The concern is that the rising of dividends is never certain and that it is in no way a well without a bottom.
Last year, 18 billion was browser from the ČEZ into the budget.
Each year, dividends are used to pay for cleaning up environmental damages to supplement pension accounts and even serve as a reserve for the coming pension reform.
Moreover, this device increases the real budget deficit to a level of 5.7 per cent of GDP according to EU rules.
And it is far from being the end of this carnival of transfers.
The budget for various compensations to victims of Communism and of crimes, or even the home savings accounts, decreased by nearly three billion.
It is not certain that the State can act without this money.
This is a lottery.
If we lose an international procedure, we will have to pay him anyway, notes Janota.
The minister will then have to save on the department area or, in the worst case, touch the government's budget provision.
It is also short one hundred million to fund a state project of two billion, which should allow online tracking of the expenditures of each administration.
The first stage will begin in January.
If the finance minister did not find money elsewhere, the project would have to be stopped and sanctions would take place, Janota warns.
Your next smartphone will master two operating systems.
Americans are envisaging a mobile phone in the future that will allow the user to move from one operating system to another by pressing a single button.
The projects that were revealed seem promising.
One button is enough and you switch from Windows Mobile to Android in a few seconds.
It is precisely this possibility that is the goal of American society VMware, which deals primarily with the development of virtualization software for computers.
We are going to allow you to manage two user profiles at the same time on your mobile phone.
You can alternate between them, you can see the personal and professional differences
The two will work at the same time, Srinivas Krishnamurti from the VMware company said in an interview for Computerworld magazine.
It was unveiled in November last year and it was first made a demonstration of it a few days ago.
It will be on the market in 2012.
Virtualization on smartphones is absolutely no fiction.
VMware has already successfully introduced a test version to journalists, a smartphone equipped with two operating systems.
It is a Nokia N800 modified with a RAM memory of 128 MB, which ran simultaneously the mentioned systems Windows Mobile and Android.
The development of new technologies for mobile phones is booming.
The company VMware now works with the European and American operators to test virtualisation on smartphones, and customers should have access to the devices during 2012.
The lack of snow in the mountains worries hotelkeepers.
The deserted ski trails pose a problem not only for the operators of ski lifts.
The lack of snow deters people from booking their skiing holidays in hotels and guest houses.
Thus it is still possible to get free rooms every day in winter, including Christmas and New Year.
We have plenty of hits on our site.
Internet users browse the offers, ask for prices, but do not dare to commit and book for the moment.
And if they call us, they ask immediately whether there will be snow or mud at Christmas," said Martin Jandura, operator of the Spindl.Info information portal.
If we want to spend the New Year of his dreams in Špindlerův Mlýn, we would better have to not hesitate any longer to reserve.
If we give priority to Economies and the quality of accommodation only come next, then we can try to wait a few days.
The Špindler hoteliers propose for the moment only one-week visits for the New Year.
I think they will try again for a moment to place them, but they will give up too and will accept shorter periods.
And then the number of free rooms will quickly decrease," said Jandura.
The tourist agency Ingtours of Vrchlabí also still proposes vacant beds for all periods of winter.
The week of Christmas interests us the most for the moment, it is not completely sold.
There are still unoccupied, let's say, about half the rooms in our offer.
This is why we have already prepared a handful of last-minute Christmas trips," said Petr Schiefert, Ingtours director.
The tourist agency of Vrchlabí can also offer New Year in the Krkonoše, but there are fewer available places.
The 14 first days of February are selling just as well, the remaining winter stays sell moderately.
This year, interest in winter stays has been negatively influenced by the fact that there is still no snow in Krkonoše.
The people are waiting for it to start to fall.
Nobody wants to spend winter in the mountains without snow.
If the tracks recover themselves during the week, Christmas too will be complete," thinks Schiefert.
Conversely, occupancy of the hotel Horizont in Pec pod Sněžkou is slightly higher than last year.
It was an improvement of almost five per cent.
We have some spaces left for New Year as well as for Christmas.
During the January vacation there is a great deal of interest from Poles, and February sells well too," advised Karel Rada, director of the best hotel in Pec.
The Omnia hotel near the central parking lot of Jánské Lázně is also 80 per cent full during the New Year period.
However half of the beds remains empty during Christmas at the jánské lázně newest hotel.
This year, we were pleasantly surprised by the month of January, where we have already 60 per cent of occupation at the present time.
February is a little more low for now, but as soon as the snow will fall, the interest for stays in the Krkonoše will still certainly rise said the director of the Omnia hotel, Erik Sporysch.
The hotelkeepers of Krkonoše should not however hope for more snow.
On Thursday it will be fresher and there will be rain; it should be snowy in the mountains.
But afterwards, the weather should warm up, Jiří Jakubský of the Hradec station of the Czech Hydrometeorological Institute informs us.
United States: repetition is the mother of wisdom.
It has even become amusing, the hard effort with which President Barack Obama, who has a reputation for wisdom, which mimics the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan issue, has regarded himself as quite simple.
When he eventually let his ardently awaited document leak out, it proved to be a carbon copy of the Bush scenario for Iraq from three years ago.
Not content with using the expression "as in Iraq" several times in the same text, he has in addition not hesitated to use the title of the Bush speech in January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A New Way Forward."
Meanwhile, he has personally criticised Bush's idea to send new reinforcements in Iraq consumed by the civil war as "irresponsible and a decision with disastrous consequences."
The following months have nevertheless shown that Bush's strategy, which came from the recommendations of his campaign managers, was the only one which was possible and likely to succeed, so much so that newspapers today do not speak of Iraq at all.
This has not improved the reputation of Bush, however, objectively speaking, he left his successor a far more favourable final situation than one could have hoped.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was once again the commanding generals who asked him for a troop increase, notably the commander of the operation in Afghanistan, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the reluctance of the White House despite his customary subordination..
He asked for 40,000 men to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months, but though he lacked for a better option, he had at least cheated the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
He has managed to obtain the promise of additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he was expecting 10,000 initially.
Which leads to most of the problems in the whole Obama strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan 18 months from now and to finish the entire process three years from now. The whole Obama doctrine leads to more questions than it provides answers for.
Many have doubts about the fact that an increase of half will bring the same results as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, the Iraqi society is relatively well organised and its leaders honour the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out for the exact opposite - one cannot rely on anyone and no treaty is respected.
In these conditions, difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, used to change of leader day to day according to what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain nothing more than window dressing behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will continue to proliferate.
It is particularly difficult to balance the interests of various ethnic groups given the lack of clarity about the reports, which are further complicated by the influence of Pakistan and Iran.
Even the foundation of a "quick to act state", which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The timing of Obama's strategy is perplexing given his determination.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only got worse and it is currently on the edge of chaos.
Only a purely romantic heart and out of the reality can be persuaded that the small soldiers sent to the tumult of the war in order to their "speedy return home " will bring a miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for withdrawal of the troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will consider it as the indirect admission of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit demonstrated that the Europeans' willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is decreasing.
European politicians neither know nor want to explain their electorate how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the mountains of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor which is capable of radically altering the situation is the development of the events linked to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the strengthened sanctions do not have any effect on the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves facing the very difficult question of resolving the problem by the use of military force.
It must be answered for example when, according to Obama, America will victoriously withdraw troops from Afghanistan.
Each solution of this kind will, however, drive a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only solution for Obama is the fact that three years are remaining until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to develop a new strategy in case this one would be revealed to be a flop.
The leaders of Goldman Sachs bank will not receive bonuses in cash anymore.
The senior leader employees of the American bank Goldman Sachs will no longer receive bonuses in cash this year.
The company announced it in response to strong criticism of its salary practices.
The group of 30 top executives will receive shares instead of money, which they will not be able to sell for five years.
The shares could be withdrawn from the leaders in case they would take too much risk.
According to Reuters, Goldman Sachs is thus placing itself as the leader of the effort aiming to link remuneration with the long-term performances on Wall Street.
I suppose that Wall Street is well aware of the global sense that we must take, said the former investment banker Douglas Elliott of the JPMorgan company.
The concern lies in the details, he added.
Goldman Sachs bank became the target of criticism after set aside  for itself almost $17 billion in premiums on the first three quarters of this year.
For this year, the total amount of bonuses will likely exceed $20 billion despite the measure announced today, according to Reuters.
With the arrival of the financial crisis, big bonuses in the banking sector have become a sensitive political issue in many countries.
Britain announced Wednesday that it intends to spend a single fee of 50 per cent bankers' bonuses in excess of 25,000 pounds.
France is preparing similar measures.
This year women were awarded the Nobel Prize in all areas except Physics
There were five women, a record number, who were awarded today in Stockholm from the hands of the King of Sweden Charles XVI Gustave the Nobel Prizes in technical disciplines and in literature.
In addition to the four scientists there was also the German writer from Romania Herta Müller.
Two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider were awarded with their fellow countryman Jack Szostak the Nobel Prize in Medicine for their research in the area of chromosomes.
The chemistry prize was awarded to the Israeli Ada Jonath along with the Americans Venkatraman Ramakrishnan and Thomas Steitz for clarifying the structure and function of ribosomes
The last laureate, American Elinor Ostrom with her fellow countryman Oliver Williamson, received the Nobel Prize in Economics for their analysis of economic governance.
The only technical discipline which had no female winner this year was physics.
The prize was awarded today to scientists Charles Kao for his research in the area of optical fiber and Willard Boyle with George Smith for their invention of CCD chips, which are currently on the basis of all digital cameras, fax or telescopes.
Each laureate received the diploma, the Nobel medal and the certificate of acquisition of the financial reward.
This one reached 10 million Swedish crowns in each category. (approximately 1.1 million euros).
If one of them includes several winners, they will share the reward among them.
The much awaited Nobel Peace Prize has been given this afternoon in Oslo in Norway to the American President Barack Obama.
In his speech, he acknowledged the controversial nature of his salary since he is only at the beginning of his job and since he is also the head of a country engaged in two wars - in Iraq and in Afghanistan.
In defense of his policy, he added that in certain situations war is necessary to achieve peace, even if the price is high.
