President Václav Klaus will receive on Friday morning Finance Minister Eduard Janota, who balances his stay in the government because of his disagreement with the State budget for next year as it was passed by the Chamber of Deputies
It is believed that the budget and perhaps the position of Janota in the cabinet too will be on the agenda of their meeting on Friday.
Klaus also criticizes the budget.
According to him, the deficit is too important, which is widening the public finance crisis.
It was the presidential spokesman Radim Ochvat who informed the meeting.
Janota then wants to discuss his office on Monday with Prime Minister Jan Fischer.
According to the legislation on the budget, which will be subject to the signing of Klaus, there is a deficit of 163 billion kronor that the Czech Republic will have to manage.
However, the Chamber of Deputies has approved wednesday the proposals from the left on the transfers of money and increased the remuneration of officials, the operation of social services and direct payments to farmers.
The government blamed the proposals of Social Democrats that they would indirectly increase the budget deficit.
For this reason, a violent disagreement is born between the left-wing on the one hand, the government, Klaus and the right-wing on the other hand, disagreement that calls into question the future of the Fischer cabinet which was formed by agreement between the ODS, the ČSSD and the Green Party.
Critics say that the budget, as it was voted by deputies, removes the package of saving measures passed by the Fischer government and which should, according to him, stem the debt of the State.
Klaus, who can ratify the law on the State budget but who is not obliged to do so, said today at a discussion breakfast with entrepreneurs that politicians have long neglected the "serious problem" of the "unrestrained deficiency" of public finances.
Right now there is, according to him, no favourable solution.
Only a strong government could bring an improvement, if it could rely on a consensus of political parties, according to the president.
ODS president Mirek Topolánek indicated that the budget is staggering and that the government should call into question its ulterior existence.
Petr Nečas, Vice-President of the ODS, told the ČTK that the idea of a business official supported by the ČSSD, the ODS and the Greens just doesn't fly any more.
In his reaction, Prime Minister Fischer called such words "drastic verdicts".
The head of ČSSD Jiří Paroubek reacted to Topolánek, saying that the budget deficit prepared for this year by former government of Topolánek is staggering and it will exceed 200 billion kronor.
Already on Wednesday, the ČSSD called the ratification of next year's state budget a success.
The People's Party was also satisfied.
Morgan Freeman will play Mandela in the new film of Clint Eastwood
Despite criticism that the principal roles are played by American actors, the South Africans claim that the new Hollywood film Invictus - Unbeaten will expose to the world many things about the country, its struggles and its success.
The story is about sports, relations between races and Nelson Mandela.
American actor Morgan Freeman, rewarded by an Oscar, embodies the film on Nelson Mandela's life, a tireless fighter against the racist apartheid system in South Africa and first black president.
Freeman said that it is a ninety-one years old Mandela who asked him to embodies him in the movie.
Matt Damon plays another important role.
I told him: 'If I have to embody you, I should be able to personally see you..
The 72 years old actor who has been rewarded by a price for his role in Clint Eastwood's drama Milion Dollar Baby located in the boxing environment has, for example, embodied the leader of a movement against slavery who became himself a servant, a fictitious US president, even God himself, in the movie Evan Almighty, but never someone as alive and important for so many people as Mandela.
The former South African statesman was jailed 27 years for his hard work to end the apartheid in South Africa.
He was released in 1990 and became president of the country for four years.
In 1993 he was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
Invictus is a Latin word meaning unbeaten and it is the title of a poem of the English author William Ernest Henley published in 1875.
The challenge was to talk like him.
The film tells the true story of joint efforts of Nelson Mandela and the captain of the South African rugby team François to unify the country. The newly elected President Mandela knows that his country still remains divided racially and economically after apartheid.
He is convinced to be able to unite his people by sport and decides to unite the rugby players who are among the "outsiders" at world scale.
The South African team will finally move forward in World Cup in 1995.
Freeman worked a few years to bring the story of Nelson Mandela to the big screen.
I had no other purpose than to play this role to bring it closer to reality, said Freeman.
The biggest challenge for me was of course to speak like him
The actor said that if he and the international politician had been in the same region, he would have tried to meet Mandela, dine with him, and to be in the wings before his speech.
The most important for him was to shake hands with him.
I realized that when I shake hand with you, I collect some of your energy, it is transmitted and I had the impression of knowing how you feel, he said.
It is important for me to try to become another person.
Matt Damon plays in the film as François Pienaar, captain of a national rugby team  in which there is a majority of white players.
The actor said he has six months to prepare for a role in the harsh environment of rugby.
For him, his first meeting with Pienaar at his home was a great surprise.
I remember when I arrived at the door of the house, he opened it for me and the first thing I said to Francois Pienaar was: 'I look much taller in the film ".
Despite the differences between actors and real models, Invictus under the leadership of the filmmaker Eastwood received positive opinions and one's even talk about ambitions for the Oscars.
Film critic Todd McCarthy of the newspaper Daily Variety summed up his positive review in these words: "It is a very good story, a very well made film."
On the film evaluations site rottentomatoes.com, Invictus received 76 per cent of positive feedback.
The mystery of the aura in Norway is resolved: the Russians were testing a rocket.
One was able to observe a strange light phenomenon of unknown origin above Norway.
The Russian Ministry of Defence has admitted only yesterday that he has tested an intercontinental ballistic missile not far from the Norwegian borders.
The launch, however, has been a failure again and the "Bulava" missile which was originally supposed to be the pride of the Russian army is gradually becoming the nightmare of the Russian generals and the Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
His repeated presence during the tests of the rocket has not had the expected effect on the success of the test flights.
Most of the time, either Bulava did not take off, or it was damaged in flight.
Russian newspapers talk of "Bulava" as the "missile that do not fly"
A missile that does not fly but shines
This 13th test took place normally at the beginning.
It is only at the end of the flight that there was again damages to the equipment.
It is clearly the engine of the third stage of the rocket that exploded.
This time, "Bulava" has taken off from the nuclear submarine Dmitrij Donskij which was sailing under the surface of the White Sea.
This type of missile can precisely be launched from a moving immersed boat
This is why the mysterious light over Norway caused by an unidentified flying object was probably just from a defective "Bulava."
By the way, Norwegians did not doubt any moment that this is a Russian rocket.
The generals argue that this time, one cannot talk absolutely of failure.
The two first stages of the rocket have resisted and the damage has hit the third one only.
In the previous cases, the engines have had failures on the first stage.
Even if none of the launch tests have gone smoothly, the leadership of the Ministry of Defence thinks that only 6 to 13 have been failures.
The success rate of almost 50 per cent fills the generals of optimism and they say is always a day "Bulava 'fly without problems and that it will even ten nuclear cores hypersoniques a total weight of 1.15 tonnes.
