Legendary defender Viatcheslav Fetissov will appear again in a professional match at 51 years old.
The former world champion, Olympic champion and holder of the Stanley Cup is going to lend support to his CSKA Moscow team in need and will probably go in during the Friday match against Petrograd.
Fetissov, who ended his career at 40 years old in 1998, is currently president of the CSKA.
After the injury of Denis Kuliash we urgently need another defender.
Fetissov trains regularly and agrees to help the team.
We have yet to settle a few details on the form, says the coach of the Sergey Nyemtchinov club, quoted by the AP agency.
It was not said whether the comeback of the legendary hockey player is not for only one match.
I think Fetissov is one of those who are able to strengthen the mindset of other players, said Nyemtchinov.
According to AP, in the case of his return on the ice, Fetissov would become the oldest Russian professional hockey player.
In NHL, legendary forward Gordie Howe played a whole season for Hartford and has had 15 goals and 26 assists.
The eldest of the famous quintet Fetisov, Kassatonov - Makarov, Larionov, Krutov is one of the best hockey players and among those having the most success.
Under the colors of the Soviet Union, he won the gold twice in the Olympic Games, won seven titles as world champion, he triumphed at the Canada Cup as well as in the world junior championship.
During the second part of his career, he collected tributes in NHL too where twice he has hold the Stanley Cup.
He is a member of the Temple of fame of hockey since 2001.
Hyundai has listened to the trade unions and cancels all overtime
The leadership of the Hyundai plant in Nošovice has agreed with the unions to cancel all overtime.
It is precisely because of frequent overtime that the trade unions have declared a state of emergency strike on Monday.
Spokesman Petr Vaněk of the Hyundai plant has confirmed it.
Executive management wants however to agree with the unions about a worked-Saturday this year.
We cannot abandon our production schedule, it is essential, this is why voluntary overtime hours were proposed on Saturday, December 19th, knowing that there would be two teams, said Vaněk.
The site sedmička.cz has indicated that the company has offered a bonus of 400 Czech crowns for employees who would be part of the Saturday team.
It will also be awarded afterwards for the workday of 28 November.
The company, according to Vaněk, decided to change the way it motivates its employees in exchange for overtime.
Either they can receive extra for overtime hours or they can make December 28th a vacation day as a replacement and extend their New Year's celebrations, Vaněk said.
In addition to that all employees here on Saturday will receive compensation for transportation costs and for their lunch. 
Given that overtime hours were the most urgent and heated topics under discussion and the demands of unions and of employees who spontaneously stopped production last week, the management made the decision to cancel all overtime for the month of December, Vaněk said.
Until last week, employees of the car factory were forced to work almost daily two extra hours in addition to their eight hours.
The trade unions intend to cancel the state of strike after signing the agreement.
The next negotiation between the management of the car factory and the unions should take place on Friday afternoon.
The trade union leader Petr Kuchař said on Wednesday that they were ready to stop the strike in case their claims are met and a joint document is signed.
The situation in the factory culminated last Wednesday when nearly 400 workers spontaneously went on strike because of continuous overtime hours.
They were also protesting against poor pay conditions and of alleged hazing.
The management defended itself with the statement that employees had to work overtime to meet automobile production requirements.
During the announcement of the strike on Monday, the unions have also asked that the employees who have stopped production are not subject to sanctions.
The trade unions request the society to reduce the overtime to the minimum.
Moreover, they want this year a reward of 5,000 crowns (about 209€) for these ones.
The Hyundai car factory of Nošovice currently employs 2,000 people.
She began mass production last year in November.
It has produced approximately 80,000 vehicles up to September this year, with a production capacity of 200,000 cars a year.
Czech discovery: a substance that works on "resistant" HIV viruses too.
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that could slow down the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on the viruses that have already developed an immunity to medicines.
This reality has, in some cases, the upper hand based on the fact that the combination does not act as intensively against the common variants of the virus as well as some drugs already available.
It is not possible to recover from AIDS at the moment.
Nevertheless, we can extend radically the lives of patients through a mixture of drugs that prevent the spread of HIV in the body.
Their consumption leads, however, to a number of side effects.
Plus, the repression of this increase brings about the development of so-called virus strain on which drugs do not have any effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for a method to cope with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the proliferation of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are a composite of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination is blocking the virus development in a different way than all the medicines used to date and therefore they could overcome the resistance problem.
The work of researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances on the basis of their knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their routes on the proteins of the virus.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are shaped by the boron atoms, hydrogen and carbon and connected by a metal atom, cobalt in this case.
A sneaky and resistant virus.
The protease of the HIV is a protein of the HIV virus which is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease the mature infectious particles of the virus would not develop.
If you stop the HIV protease, you will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, explain the researchers in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the  Czech Republic Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the scientific publication Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a number of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic link, which is then systematically altered.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The efficiency of this series of substances on the proteases of the HIV has been tested in test tubes as well as on its resistant variations, obtained from patients infected with HIV.
On the current version of the enzyme, the effect of metalocarboranes is not as strong as clinical medicine, however it does not weakeon on resistannt versions against which current medicines are often ineffective.
The metalocarboranes, with their unique mechanism of action and their other properties, such as their biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of additional chemical modifications, are therefore interesting compounds to study further in order to move towards the development of effective medicines against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, director of the Laboratory of structural biology at the Institute of organic chemistry and biochemistry and at the Institute of molecular genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
Dispute over the budget. The ODS attacks Fischer, who defends himself.
The President of the ODS (Civic Democratic Party), Mirek Topolanek, is describing the budget ratified for the following year "alarming" and he believes the government of Prime Minister Jan Fischer should question its existence.
The prime minister described the remarks of the ODS as drastic verdict.
He says he is taking time to analyse.
The representative of the ODS Petr Nečas declared that the idea of an administrative cabinet supported by the Čssd, the ODS and Green Party did obsviously not work anymore.
According to Nečas, the head of government should decide whether he is going to accept the support of the minority in the Chamber of Deputies who are concerned with combatting the growing deficit, or whether he wants to stay in office with the aid of the parliamentary left.
Nečas has warned that the positions of the ODS and Social Democrats regarding the issue of public debt are diametrically opposed.
The Chamber of Deputies ratified the budget for 2010 on Wednesday, however with the change proposals of up to 12 billion crowns included by the left side.
The House increased the money for officials wages, social services work and direct payments to farmers.
The government's complaint about the Social Democrats' proposals was that they have been indirectly increasing the budget deficit.
The Czech Republic should handle with a deficit of 163 billion kronor.
The ODS has left the room before the vote, playing ball with the government desire which means a modified budget is a better variant than an acting budget.
Disappointment and uselessness.
Finance Minister Eduard Janota spoke of disappointment and a sense of uselessness, Prime Minister Jan Fischer indicated that the government will still consider the current situation.
Nečas is convinced that if Janota threatened to leave office in case of ratification of the proposals of changes, the situation could be different.
According to the Czech Television, Janota has made an appointment on Monday with the Prime Minister after his passage in the government.
He said at the same time that he was wondering if he would remain in office.
His disappointment about the negociations around the budget is the reason.
If Fischer decides to continue the fight against the budget deficit, Nečas believes that the representatives of the ČSSD, who forced changes to the budget, do not have their place in the government.
The Prime Minister should also make clear that he will quit if the Congress ratifies the other laws increasing the deficit, such as those that affect the health insurance, pensions, or the reform of the law on services.
Topolánek: the ministers appointed by the ODS are not involved.
This is the case of the head of government Fischer and all the government.
The ministers appointed by the ODS did nothing prejudicial, Topolánek emphasized in a written statement from the United States.
He pointed out that the deputy ministers from some ministries avail themselves of TOP 09, which voted against the budget.
Nečas emphasized that if Fischer decides to hand in his resignation in the face of having to wage a struggle against the amount of the fiscal deficit, "it is entirely logical and reasonable that it is based on the leftist majority that is currently in the House."
That said, he should not expect support and tolerance from Democrats.
I haven't thought about it and once it will be on the schedule, so I will work on it, said Defense Minister Martin Barták, elected in the government precisely by the Democrats, from the Parliament to journalists.
Prime Minister Fischer flew off in the afternoon for a debate of the European Council in Brussels.
The ODS backed down at the request of the Prime Minister.
Nečas stressed that the ODS probably would have voted on Wednesday against the budget changes if he did not explicitly asked the House Democrats to vote on the budget.
We do not have the feeling of being orphans, we are not small children, he responded to the question of whether the ODS had not been criticized by president of the Party in the House or in the country during the  negotiations of the budget.
I have not noticed that my vote would have been lacking.
I already knew when I renounced my mandate that what would happen in the following months would be a bolchevization of the Chamber and the destruction of all that was positive, Topolánek responded in person.
According to the new schedules of the CD, there will be fewer trains for the same charges.
The Czech railways will eliminate or reduce from 13 December some less loaded regional or express trains and on the contrary will increase some others.
The total cover of transport will drop at the day of coming into effect of the new schedules of two pourcent compared to today.
Most of the pricing will not change, including the base tariffs and the reduced tariff.
For example the inhabitants of the region of Ostrava will have more connections to the capital, the railways are going to add a set of pendolino trains.
Instead, an express will stop serving Bratislava.
There will be also less fast trains on the Prague - Písek - České Budějovice line, the Prague - Letohrad direct line will be drastically reduced.
At the regional level, the largest decrease in shipments concerns the region of Hradec Králové, eight per cent in total, while Prague and its environs can be pleased about an increase.
Two night trains on the Prague - Tábor - České Budějovice line have also been cancelled and the runs of some express trains on the Prague - Písek - České Budějovice line will be reduced to only a few days a week.
Among the major changes, one can see the introduction of a new direct line from Milovice to Prague: for the time being the inhabitants of Milovice must change at Lysá nad Labem.
It is the fifteenth line of the Esko suburban system, whose opening is possible thanks to the completion of the electrification of the line between Lysá and Labem and Milovice.
The long distance rails near the capital will have their final destination at the central station in Prague (Praha Hlavní Nádraží).
The ČD will introduce more SC Pendolino lines between Prague and Ostrava and trains to Šumperk/Jeseník will leave at two-hour intervals.
Travellers will no longer be able to take the Pendolino up to Bratislava from the 13th of December.
The bill this year for regional railways: 200 million kroner more.
Express trains are ordered and paid by the Ministry of Transport which will pay the railways next year a total amount of four billion crowns to settle the visible losses, the same amount as this year. The regional trains are ordered by the regions which will pay for them by a total of eight billion next year, knowing that the government will account for almost three billion.
This year regional trains are 200 millions more expensive.
The railways have newly signed a contract for ten years, until now the duration was always of one year.
The railways like the system, which also explains why they have not resorted to an increase in the prices of the vast majority of tickets.
The changes will affect only ČD Net day tickets and reduced price eLiška Internet tickets.
For passengers without a reduction card, the price of ČD Net will increase from 450 to 600 kroner.
The price of eLiška will now depend on the journey taken, while before that it was valid between the cities of a chosen region and had a single rate of 160 kroner.
The Philippine rebels are still retaining more than 50 people, the children have been released
The rebels have kidnapped today 75 people in the southern Philippines, among them are some pupils of a primary school and their teachers.
It is the AFP agency that has reported it, but which spoke at first of only 65 hostages.
The 17 children were released after eight hours, as well as one of the teachers.
The hijacking took place in the province of Agusan del Sur.
There are reports that about 19 rebels used hostages as human shields during an escape from the police.
Local negotiators are trying to find an agreement for the remaining hostages releasing.
According to the AFP agency, the rebels belong to the New People's Army (NPA), which is the armed wing of the Communist Party of the Philippines (PPC).
According to the AFP agency, the police first pursued the kidnappers after violence that occurred when two family clans were settling some old scores between them.
Martial law was declared in the province of Maguindanao in the southern Philippines due to a recent slaughter in which 57 people were killed.
Among the victims of the massacre of the 23rd of November linked to the elections of the administration of the governor there were 30 journalists.
The governor of this southern province of the Philippines has been arrested following suspicions of involvement in the massacre, as well as his father Andal Ampatuan, the patriarch of Ampatuans' influential line.
The island of Mindanao also includes active Muslim separatists.
They did, however, renew peace talks with the Philippine government on Tuesday.
The history of South Africa concerns everyone, according to Morgan Freeman alias Mandela
Clint Eastwood's new Hollywood movie arrives in American movie theaters in the coming days; the title is Invictus (the official Czech title is  Invictus: Neporažený), and it narrates a part of the life of former South African President Nelson Mandela.
The role of the fighter against world-famous apartheid returned to Morgan Freeman, who has been chosen years ago by Mandela himself to embody.
The supporting male role of the legendary South African rugby champion has been cast to Matt Damon.
With the arrival of the film in movie houses, feedback from critics and the public is being heard.
Nelson Mandela
His full name is Nelson Rolihlahla Mandela; he was born on 18 June 1918 in Mvezu, South Africa.
In 1988 he was awarded the Sakharov Prize for his freedom of thought, in 1993 he was then awarded the Nobel Peace Prize alongside Klerk.
He was the president of South Africa from 1994 to 1999.
The film contains great expectations since it is presented at a time when on one hand South Africa is in the midst of preparations for the football World Cup, and on the other hand the media are troubled by disturbing news about a rise in racial conflicts and discrimination against inhabitants on the part of the black majority in power.
According to the Associated Press, reactions to the new film are for the moment rather positive in South Africa, despite the frequent reservations expressed about the principal roles in which Hollywood stars "strut about."
Morgan Freeman is, however, quoting his own terms, proud of the movie.
I have dreamed of this role for years, and I am well prepared.
I have also repeatedly met Nelson Mandela to - as they say - gain his energy, he said during the official premiere of the film in Los Angeles.
I think it is a good thing if you have the opportunity to remember through the movie the personality and the message of Nelson Mandela.
This is the history of the south african Republic, but it affects each individual, he added.
Wear the jersey of the national rugby team
The film based on the story by the British writer John Carlin the title being freely translated. In the role of the enemy: Nelson Mandela  depicted as the defender South African human rights during his term of presidency and his part in its creation .
Morgan Freeman is trying during the film to reconcile two racial groups of a long divided country and like Nelson Mandela in 1995 he enters dressed in the jersey of the South African national team on the field of the World Cup tournament, which South Africa had then won.
For showing up on the lawn in a jersey, which is seen in South Africa as something sacred, Mandela had been cheered at length fourteen years ago mainly by the white people and had been recognized by the white population.
Let us hope that the Soccer Championship will manage to unite people once again as a single nation, said rugby player Chester Williams, who was in 1995 the only 'black' of the national team.
It remains to be seen if the tense situation in South Africa will improve.
The white South Africans, however, are skeptical as has recently confided, in an interview for LN, Christopher Dawson, fan of rugby who has fled to Great-Britain.
The Championship starts on June 11, 2010.
A transformer worth tens of million kronor in flames in the region of Louny
A fire has engulfed in the morning a distribution center's transformer of the company Čeps near the town of Výškov na Lounsku.
According to Lukáš Marvan, spokesman for the firefighters of Ústí, there are six units operating on the fire.
At first they thought they would leave the processor to smolder, but they have changed their opinion and extinguish the fire with a mixture of water, foam and a special substance.
The cause is a technical fault, a short-circuit within the processor.
Nobody was injured and, according to the company's spokeswoman Pavla Mandátova, the incident has not jeopardized the security of transmissions.
Damages are estimated at tens of millions of crowns, the exact figure will be known once the fire is extinguished.
According to Mandátova, the broken transformer will have to be replaced by a new one.
She adds that in 10 years of activity, the Čeps company has not experienced anything similar, and that incidents like these are isolated.
The supply of electricity was not interrupted, said the spokesman for the company ČEZ North Bohemia Soňa Holingerova Hendrychova, the functioning of households, government and industry was not affected by fire the transformer station.
A.S. Čeps is the exclusive operator in the Czech territory in the transmission and the 400 KV and 220 KV power lines.
He maintains, renovates and develops 39 positions with 67 distribution transformers for transferring electrical power handling assemblies for distribution assemblies and line drawings with a length of 4339 km.
Jančura will sue for libel against three prefects of the Čssd
Today, Radim Jančura, owner of "Student Agency," will file a slander complaint against three Social Democrat administrators.
And specifically against Michal Hašek of the region of South Moravia, against Radko Martínka of the region of Pardubice and against the prefect of the Olomouc region, Martin Tesařík.
Jančura said it in Dvacet minut of rRdiožurnál.
The complaint is linked to the attempt of the company to operate regional railways in some regions.
All regions, however, have ended up signing long-term contracts with the Czechs railways.
All three attacked us and say we made the foodies, while we only made an offer for what they wanted themselves
They claim that we are more expensive than the Czech railways which is not true because we know the prices of the Czech railways which have been signed last week.
So it remains for us to defend ourselves.
It is in exchange for slanders on the company Student Agency, said Jančura to Radiožurnál.
Similarly, he said that he has evidence that no region has been in agreement with the European law.
We are preparing for that a complaint to the European Commission.
Hašek considers that Mr Jančura's complaint filing represents the continuation of his media show, which is used as free advertising for his company and himself.
I am of course willing to defend my name and the name of my area and call the other prefects to do the same.
I suppose this is an opportunity to show clearly that it is precisely Mr. Jančura manipulating public opinion and uses false and misleading arguments about regional rail transport, said Hašek
Jančura has already informed last week that it will invest several million crowns in an ad that mentioned the steps unfavorable regions.
He said to Radiožurnál that he will stop the campaign after Christmas and that he intends to resume it after New Year.
He said that the campaign will target corruption at large.
Jančura began his campaign after the regions agreed to give the exploitation of rail links to the Czech railways, for an order of about 150 billion kronor, without putting bidding forward.
According to Jančura, acting in such a way is illegal and contrary to the position of the European Court of Justice.
According to him, his criticism of rail transport in the regions has even led threats from a deputy of the ČSSD to Jančura.
The only threat was that if we did not stop, we could lose our licenses bus.
He presented himself as a member of parliament of the Čssd, I do not know who he is but I would not say his name, stated Jančura today to  Radiožurnál.
The vaccination against the pneumococcal will be free and optional
Vaccination against pneumococcus overturn old habits as soon as January
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
People are already speaking up, saying that a compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
The preparations for the introduction of free vaccination against pneumococcal are culminating.
The Pharmaceutical Institute already defines the maximum price for vaccines that health insurance will pay for.
Specialists are also quite clear about the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for children born in August.
Since January, children born last year starting August 2 can be vaccinated for free against pneumococcus.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If you started having the vaccination last year or earlier, you will have to pay for the following vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of the vaccine must be administered between the third and fifth month of the child's life.
Last year already one family out of four has voluntarily vaccinated its children against pneumococcus.
Yet parents paid 1,600 kroner, or more for a dose.
The vaccination of the youngest children requires four doses.
Experts estimate that each year health insurance companies spend 300 to 450 thousand kronor on doses of vaccine.
However, they save on medical care that non-vaccinated children would need.
Until now the State was spending about 500,000 kronor a year for all the vaccination of children.
The refunded vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package."
Pneumococcus is the cause of inflammations of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammations of meninges and blood poisonings.
According to investigations in hospitals, up to 28 deaths of children under 10 years were caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced vaccination refunded.
Will vaccination compulsory?
There are opinions regarding a possible mandatory vaccination in the future.
From January on, it must be paid by the insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský indicated that a compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
His Association promotes since long vaccination against the pneumococcus.
During an international conference in which our association took part, experts have not been really happy that we have an optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are pleased to have been able to impose at least this.
I think it is a direction that we now need to follow, said Kalovský.
But the health ministry does not want to change the process of vaccination against pneumococcus.
We are definitely not thinking in terms of the present time, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, claim doctors.
Hana cabrnochová, president of the Specialized company of pediatricians, acknowledges that a vaccine based on voluntary participation has its shortcomings.
If all children were vaccinated, we could consider a decrease of vaccination renewals. "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum, I understand the decision making the vaccination optional" said however Cabrnochová.
Experts estimate that starting next year, more than 80 per cent of new parents will vaccinate their babies.
The vaccination against pneumococcus marks a break because it is the first children vaccination, which is funded by insurances and not by the State.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance companies should free up funds for the prevention, they would therefore economize on any future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their products themselves
This is, however, linked to the concerns of paediatrician practitioners, which relates to the purchase of vaccines.
The original intent was to buy vaccines through insurance, the doctors receiving the same manner as other vaccine products provided by the state
However some deputies feared that this would allow insurance companies to "deduct the sums from health insurance."
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurances to repay them.
According to estimates, paediatricians will have to invest individually nearly 40,000 kroner per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
That will be far from being easy, according to Cabrnochová.
Son of an American artist involved in a "museum robbery."
The son of Frank Frazetta, illustrator acknowledged, was accused of trying to steal paintings worth $ 20 million (12 million GBP) in the museum of his father.
In Pennsylvania, the police said that Alfonso Frank Frazetta was arrested while he was loading 90 paintings in his vehicle and a trailer.
According to her, Mr Frazetta and another man used a mechanical shovel to force the entrance of the museum, in the Pocono Mountains region.
Mr Frazetta senior, 81 years old, is famous for his drawings of characters such as Conan the barbarian and Tarzan.
At the time of the incident, the artist was in Florida, reported The Associated Press (AP) news agency.
AP quoted an police official, according to whom the young Mr Frazetta may have been motivated by a family feud.
According to a police statement, the aforementioned Mr. Frazetta Jr., 52, claims to have been authorized by his father "to enter the museum, by any means, to transport the paintings to a storage facility," the agency reported.
Mr Frazetta senior denies having released such an authorization, said the agency.
The Labour party is defending the increase of the budgetary tax.
The ministers have defended the increase in taxes and the spending cuts announced in the pré-budget report, despite the criticism of the opposition, the companies and the unions.
The Tories said that Alistair Darling "failed" to show that he was serious about reducing the deficit when he postponed his decisions until after the elections.
The Chancellor also incurred anger by addressing the issues of low salaries and average salaries.
Among its main proposals are an increase of 0.5% in welfare insurance and a cap of 1% on public wages starting in 2011.
The wrath of Social Insurance
The trade unions have protested that the low salaries are penalised by a recession for which they are not responsible and have warned that "problems" are looming.
The lowering of the social insurance - which will allow to get about £3 billion per year - has got the business world angry, because from its point of view, it is a tax on jobs when the goal should be a economic recovery.
The increase, reserved for those who earn more than 20,000 GBP per year, will affect about 10 million workers.
Main points of the pre-Budget report
The social insurance will rise again by 0.5% from April 2011
The economy will fall even more than the expected 4.75% this year.
New 50% tax on bankers' bonuses
The rise of the tax on the benefits of companies for small firms has been abandoned
Tax rebate on electric cars and wind turbines.
Raise of 2.5% of the pensions
According to estimates of the Treasury, someone earning 30,000 GBP will lose 90 GBP per year and someone else earning 40,000 GBP will lose 190 GBP, whereas someone earning 10,000 GBP per year will gain 110 GBP.
The ministers said that their goal of halving the deficit before 2013 entailed "difficult decisions" but they insisted that 60% of the burden of additional taxes would weigh on the first 5% of employees.
Stephen Timms, Treasury Secretary, has refuted an increase of the tax and pointed out that cutting spending was a "drop in the ocean" compared to what was needed.
"These figures are important. They will allow us to halve the deficit, which will be crucial over the next four years", he told the BBC.
Mr Timms said he was confident and that the economic growth would get going again at the end of this year.
However, the forecasts of the Labour Party regarding economic growth-which will affect the amount that it will have to borrow and the speed at which the deficit will be made good-have been questioned after the Chancellor was forced to revise his initial figures.
In his speech, he said that the economy would probably decline by 4.75% this year – far worse than the decline of 3.5% predicted in April - while borrowing would be 3 billion of GDP over the prior estimate.
"Missed opportunity" '
The Conservatives who will launch this Thursday a new advertising campaign warning against the Labour Party's "debt crisis," have argued that the plan to borrow £789 billion over the next six years was not viable.
The ministers have failed to present a credible plan on how to reimburse, they added, "cynically" dodging difficult decisions until after the elections - which must be held in June 2010.
"They have not produced anything significant on what they will do", said Philip Hammond, Treasury chief secretary of the shadow cabinet. "They had the opportunity to do it and they have missed it."
"The major announcements will be made after the elections, whoever the winner."
Roger Bootle Deloitte.
The Labour insists that the schools, hospitals and police will be protected from further cuts, unlike the Tory proposals that would lead to faster and more important reduction of the deficit.
But the Lib Dems have argued that the money gathered due to the taxes increase and the spendings decrease would be used to support next year spending and not to reduce the deficit, arguing that the plans were "built on nothing".
Nick Robinson, Political Editor of the BBC, said that the timing of the announcements - such as the increase due to inflation for some disability benefits in April, mentioned above - would leave the Chancellor facing accusations of being disingenuous, with the money simply to be recovered in the following year.
However, leLabour insists that additional assistance is provided so that people in greatest need and that the situation will be reviewed in September 2010.
"false budget."
Although ministers have not published the details of spending beyond 2011, economists have argued that it was clear that the restrictions on public expenditure would only begin to be felt in the medium term.
The highly respected Institute for Fiscal Studies (Institut des Etudes Fiscales) asserted that the figures from the Chancellor, imply in the future, substantial reductions in many areas, including potentially transport, higher education, science and defence.
"The pain is in fact only delayed", said its director, Robert Chote.
"The most important announcements will be made after the election, whoever the winner," added Roger Bootle, economic adviser to the Deloitte accountancy.
"This was a pre-budget false report. The markets are well aware of it."
The FBI is investigating the 'arrests of Americans in Pakistan."
The FBI investigates the arrest, in Pakistan, of five Americans reporters suspected of  extremists links.
The men were arrested during a raid in a house in Sarghoda in Punjab's eastern province, announced the US embassy in Pakistan to the BBC.
The FBI said it was investing on whether that was the same men who had been reported missing from their home, in the US state of Virginia, the last month.
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs has said that it also sought information on these people.
Three of them are introduced as being of Pakistani descent, one of Egyptian heritage and the other of Yemeni origin.
If they are American citizens, of course we would like to know what the accusations are against them and under what conditions they are being detained," said the spokesman, Ian Kelly.
Katherine Schweit, FBI spokesman said that the agency had knowledge of the arrests and that she was in contact with the families of students who have disappeared.
"We are working with the Pakistani authorities to determine their identity and the nature of their activities there, and if they really are the students who are missing," she said.
The Pakistani embassy in Washington said that the men had been arrested in a house belonging to the uncle of one of them.
This one said that the house was already monitored by local police and that no charges had been brought yet against the arrested men.
The Secretary of State Hillary Clinton has refused to comment on the arrests, reported the  news agency Reuters, but she said that the US should "cooperate more with Afghanistan and Pakistan to try to uproot the infrastructure of terrorism that continues to recruit and train people."
The five students were reported missing from their homes by their families in northern Virginia in late November.
Amnesty condemns Iranians "abuses"
These last twenty years, human rights have been less respected than ever, according to the report of the Amnesty International association.
The report presents "repeats of violations" by the regime, before and after the June presidential election campaign.
A man named in the report asserted that he had been beaten and burnt with cigarettes. Another declared that he had been threatened with rape.
Iran has denied the previous criticism about its lack of respect for human rights.
The authorities said that such criticisms are politically motivated.
Thousands of people were arrested and dozens were killed in Iran, after the disputed election of President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad led to the largest public demonstrations since the Islamic revolution of 1979.
Dozens had been sentenced to prison and the prosecutors say that at least five people were sentenced to death.
Jon Leyne, BBC correspondent in Tehran, now in London, says that at the beginning of protests, the Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, has acknowledged some of the allegations of abuse, ordering the closure of the detention center of Kahrizak.
But since then, the authorities have not tolerated any criticism, our correspondent said.
"false confession"
Amnesty International has related the case of a 26-year-old computer student, Ebrahim Mehtari, who claimed to have been accused of "working with the Facebook networks" and protesting against the election results.
"They often hit me in the face," he was quoted as saying.
"I have been burned with cigarettes under the eyes, on the neck, on the head... they threatened to execute me and humiliated me".
After five days, he signed a false confession and was released and left in the street, still bloody and a half conscious, said Amnesty.
In August, the election's losing candidate, Mehdi Karroubi, said that protesters detained after the election were tortured to death in prison and that others have been raped.
The Iranian authorities have denied the accusations of rape but admitted that abuses had taken place.
Amnesty has also mentioned the case of a former detainee who said he was locked in a container with 75 other people, for more than eight weeks, in a detention centre in Kahrizak.
Amnesty has accepted that the Iranian parliament and judiciary create a committee to investigate the post-election unrest and the government's response, but it claimed that the mandate and the powers of these bodies were not clear and that the results of the parliamentary committee had not been made public.
The group has said that at least 90 people had been arrested, during the last three weeks, in order to prevent further demonstrations.
Ski paths built in the park of the city
More than 100 tonnes of artificial snow has been used to transform the location of Bristol in a competition track.
The Piste in the Park (a piste in the park) event has drawn 16 semi-professional skiers and snowboarders competing for cash prices.
At the top of the runway of the Brandon Hill park, a small springboard preceded a 100m long trail.
John Hickman, a fourth-year medical student, said that the view from the runway was magnificent but that it was pretty daunting.
It's a beautiful view, with all the city lights twinkling below.
Here are found some of the best skiers and snowboarders in the country - real talent, "he added.
Prices have rewarded the best aerobatics - or figures made on the runway.
After the party on Thursday night, the snow will be left to melt.
Always them and us
Can Islam be French ?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular State.
Roger Bootle Deloitte.
Some readers will be attracted by this new book, admirers of the author's last book "Why the French Do Not Like the Headscarf "(2006), an elegant and well documented study of a problem that has divided and worried the country for 15 years and whose effects are still being felt today.
Mr Bowen's last book presents much larger and much more ambitious framework.
Good anthropologist, he not only wants to know what politicians and media say about Islam in France, but what is happening in the country.
He spent many months in mosques, in schools and in colleges which now provide in France what Mr. Bozen calls "Muslim spaces" for the 5-6 million Muslims.
He knows very well to listen and replicate the debates between teachers and pupils on the issues that concern them most.
Should a Muslim must marry in a mosque or in the town hall (or both)?
Should the evolution and the gay rights be taught to young Muslims?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-musulman?
Could a  Muslim use a banking system based on interest for a loan?
These are this practical problems, he says, which are the everyday life, rather than the political dramas that concern the media.
The author identifies a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, all unknown to the public, except perhaps Tariq Ramadan, a Muslim Arab born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how to be both a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They do not push the debate to the end.
Conservatives do not believe in the idea of a French or European Islam.
The scholars and activists who have been interviewed by Mr. Bowen are generally in agreement with their counterparts, lawyers of a Sunni Islam purist associated with Saudi Arabia, which nowadays are a small part of Muslims in Europe.
Mr. Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But a compromise can only be achieved with the efforts of both sides.
He wonders just how much French politicians (and the intellectual elite which is such an intense guardian of secularity) are really committed to pluralism.
According to him, Muslims have not been spoiled, compared to Catholics, Protestants and Jews who have also had to make historic compromises with the secular Republicanism.
Rather than a growing pragmatism, it detects a "narrowness of the core values".
Can Islam be French? after reading this book, one is tempted to say "yes, but not yet."
The darkest view in the world
The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatically than any other place on the planet.
The ice composing it is melting at an alarming rate, taking with it a life that cannot survive elsewhere.
Petrol, gas, shipping and fishing are in the newly opened waters, with diplomats, lawyers and now writers in their wake.
In "On a Thin Layer of Ice," Richard Ellis, writer and illustrator, paints a natural history of the symbol of the Great North, the polar bear.
Aware of the history and complicated politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who were doing their evidence in the white bear hunting.
The meeting of Admiral Nelson, then a courageous, 14-year-old naval cadet who had nothing to fight with but the tip of his musket, is certainly a myth, but the rest is true.
The young bear cubs captured when they were swimming alongside their mother which has just been killed, were caught and sent to zoos and circuses.
In the early twentieth century, a famous show gathered 75 bears at the same time.
Even today, the dimensions of a zoo are still generally a millionth of the necessary surface for an adult living in the wild. Climate is rarely mentioned: a polar bear living in Singapore has become green as a result of algae that grew in his thick fur.
Click here for more information.
Mr Ellis tells the stories of other writers and historians and often mentions the threat posed by hunters on the survival of species.
Despite being banned in Norway, America and Russia, the killings continue in Greenland and Canada where hunters in helicopters and Inuits on snowmobiles use powerful assault rifles to hunt their prey.
Ironically, it is in the fursthest waters in the North of these two hunter nations that the ice will stay longer.
In his new book, "After the Ice," Alun Anderson, a former editor in chief of the New Scientist, offers a clear and frightening summary of the science of the Arctic and a fascinating glimpse of what may be the future there.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmosphere specialists nor oceanographers can describe the exact speed of changes.
It is not for lack of trying.
Late 19th and early 20th centuries, Fridtjof Nansen's pioneer travels gave the first information on the polar ice melting.
The submarines from the cold war then mapped changes in the relief under this one.
The surveillance satellites and the probes placed on the icebergs are of very helpful, but the bulk of work is done by tough men, camping in coldness.
Mr Anderson look at the extraordinary and tiny world of the Arctic ice dependent system formed by the brackish water lattice pressed by freezing.
But the bear mentioned above with the microscopic marvels contained in the ice, will be totally lost with the disappearance of the summer ice, scheduled between 2013 and 2050.
"In a few months, it will perhaps be our turn."
Some Marines, among the 6,000 people who placed wreaths on the graves at Arlington
Private De'Angello Robinson, 19 years old, made a seven hours trip by bus to drop a wreath on the grave of a soldier that he had never met.
For him and for the other Marines who made the trip from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina to Arlington National Cemetery to decorate the graves, this day was devoted to saluting the men and women who, one day, were in their place.
In a few months, from where we will be sent, we will risk being in their place, Robinson said about the fallen soldiers.
If it were to happen to me, I would want someone to do the same thing for me, it's why I just try to show some respect.
He was one of 6000 volunteers gathered Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans in different sections of the cemetery during the Arlington Cemetery ceremony.
In 1992, Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, launched the commemoration, and other people decided to decorate several hundred tombstones in the ceremony at Arlington Cemetery.
Now, to continue an 18-year tradition, Morrill and his wife Karen, make the journey each year, stopping in various cities on their way, to organize celebrations in honor of military personnel and victims of terrorism.
The Worcester have also founded a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across America, whose aim is to promote the event in all of the other states.
This year, volunteers have placed more than 16 million wreaths on graves at Arlington National Cemetery, around the Pentagon, on the graves at Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, in Battery Park in New York City, and on the site of the memorial for victims of United Airlines flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second year in a row, the foundation Walmart Foundation has given more than $150,000 to buy and transfer the crowns.
Charleen Hunt, 70 years old, from Westminster, said she had made the trip to Arlington in honour of her husband, a military career defunct.
Although her ​​husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said that for her, this gesture was a way of thanking those who had sacrificed.
It is a small sign the civilians can make to support our troops, she said.
It is like visiting a family grave.
Muffled up in several layers of winter clothes, the volunteers walked between the lawns and the wide hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers have chosen old graves, dating from the first and second world wars, as well as from the Vietnamese War because they are not visited so frequently as the new graves, said the organizers.
The mood was of optimism, while children played and couples held hands, resting fresh pine wreaths on the gray tombs.
Each round crown had a dark green colour, with a small red bowtie on top.
Nearby, silence hovered on Section 60, where most of the veterans of wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried.
The United Service Organizations have given 1,000 kronor to decorate the section, but the dark mood of the current wars filled the area.
People were crying without hiding, other were praying and families and friends were supporting each other in the cold air.
Some were reading aloud the names engraved in the stone while others were leaning to see the small black and white information cards, stuck into the wet soil for those whose graves had not been completed yet.
Sandra Lockwood was one of many mothers in tears, on the grave of her son.
She left Zanesfield, Ohio, and had driven eight hours to come and collect herself at the grave of Marine Gunnery Sergeant David Shane Spicer, who died in battle in July.
No one should ever forget thanks to what we are free... my son has paid for it, she said.
"Long after I am gone, I want someone to remember him."
A US citizen arrested by the Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested a US citizen who was distributing mobile phones and laptops in the country, said the services of the American Foreign Office.
The national, who has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc., based in Bethesda.
The company is working on projects for clients such as the U.S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
The consular authorities and the U.S. Interest Section in Havana are trying to have access to the detainee who was arrested on the 5th of December.
The specific charges were not made public, although under the Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreigner visitor can be arrested under the pretext of being 'dangerous'.
All the so-called revolutionary activities, including moderate protests and critical writings, bring the risk of being arrested.
The anti-government graffiti and speeches are regarded as serious crimes.
Cuba has a bloggers community which gets bigger and bigger, led by Yoani Sánchez, popular commentator who frequently writes on the way are husband and herself are monitored and harassed by the government agents.
Sánchez has made several requests to leave the country to go receive rewards but authorizations have always been refused him.
The detention of an American citizen will perhaps increase the tension between the communist government of the brothers in Cuba and the Obama administration which is pursuing a "soft" approach to improve relations with the island.
The announcement of the arrestation was first reported by The New York Times, on Friday evening.
The new US policy insists that the Cuban government advance by taking firm steps, such as the release of political prisoners and creating more space for the opposition, so that the US can reciprocate.
Mobile phones and laptops are allowed in Cuba, even though there are new and desired consumer goods in a country where the average wage of a civil servant is $15 per month.
Just this year, the Cuban government accorded its ordinary citizens the right to buy mobile telephones; they are principally used for texting or for a 15-minute conversation, which corresponds to about a day's wages.
On the island, the Internet use is extremely limited.
It is available in luxury hotels and for foreign visitors in the country, as well as in some government buildings, such as universities.
Cubans who want to connect must often give their name to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
The detention of an American in Cuba is rare.
Of the few Americans incarcerated in Cuba, most are behind bars for crimes such as drug trafficking, said Gloria Berbena, Press Attache with the U.S. Interests Section in Havana.
Berbena said she could not provide more information about the arrest.
Arrest and detention are a big mistake.
An activity which, in any other open society, would be allowed -- the distribution of free mobile phones -- is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, Director of the Americas Program of the group Human Rights Watch, which recently published a harsh report about freedom in Cuba, called "New Castro, Same Cuba," referring to the installation of Raul Castro as leader of the country to replace Fidel, his ailing older brother.
According to Vivanco, a defendant is often arrested, sentenced and imprisoned on the same day.
He said that any solution would probably be policy and that the Cuban government often causes a negative reaction in the United States, when the two countries are beginning to get a better dialogue.
The Pakistani authorities prevent a plot to send troops in Afghanistan
On Saturday, the Pakistani authorities reported an organisation suspected of preparing a plan to send five men from Northern Virginia into Afghanistan in order to kill American troops, saying that they hoped this would help to dismantle a significant network of terrorist recruiters plundering the Internet in search radicalized young men .
Investigators said they were chasing a hidden insurgent, known as Saifullah, who invited these men to Pakistan after having found them when one of them made comments approving the wave of terror on YouTube's video site on the Internet.
Once they arrived in Pakistan, these men were guided by Saifullah who tried to help them get back to the remote region of Pakistan's tribal belt, home of al-Qaeda and of its terrorist training camps.
But a representative of the Pakistani secret services who was informed about the case said Saturday that Saifullah had not managed to convince the commanders of al Qaeda that these men were not involved in the CIA plot to infiltrate the terrorist network.
Thus, they have been isolated for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the forbidden northeast mountains which had became a refuge for terrorists.
They were considered as infiltrated agents.
This is why they were rejected, said a representative of the authorities who spoke on the condition to be kept anonymous because of the confidential nature of the case.
The authorities' representative said that the men were determined and they are still trying to obtain the necessary permissions to enter into the Al Qaeda camps when they were arrested by the Pakistani law forces.
The case of these five men -- who remain in Pakistan and who are being questioned by the FBI -- emphasizes the crucial role of recruiters in the identification of potential terrorists and, perhaps more important, in determining the people who can be trusted.
Since the 11 September 2001 attacks, the American Intelligence Services' priority was to infiltrate men in al-Qaeda network.
The recruiters of the organization play the role of gate-keepers, refusing entry to those who do not show a serious commitment and those who can turn out to be spies.
According to analysts, the potential American recruits are closely studied by al-Qaeda.
But they are also very attractive to the group because of their potential access to American targets, and their propaganda value.
However, Evan Kohlmann, expert from the NEFA foundation based in the United States, said that terrorist groups must also pay more and more attention in recent years in the choice of people that they accept as the American intelligence services have become experts in their recruitment methods.
If you try to infiltrate someone into these groups, what better way than to follow its model of recruitment that so many other people have already followed? said Kohlmann.
The model is the one which is more on more on the Internet.
Tens of thousands of protestors in Copenhagen request an "action" for the climate.
Tens of thousands of protesters marched in the streets here Saturday, calling for greater action on climate control on the part of the negotiators working in the Palace des Congrès at the Bella Convention Center in the city.
The number of demonstrators was estimated at 100,000 people, but 25,000 according to police estimates.
This event has gone relatively smoothly, although a small number of masked activists has lit some explosives close to a set of government buildings, located in town-centre.
On a day in which little happened during United Nations-sponsored talks on climate, thousands of activists took to the streets holding signs in English saying, "There is no planet B," and one in Spanish, which said, "The Earth says that she has had enough."
Several celebrities have joined the protests, including the Danish top model and photographer, Helena Christensen, who said that travelling to the homeland of her mother, Peru, has opened her eyes on the heartbreaking problems the country is facing because of the impact of climate change that is already happening."
This is one reason why I decided to join the great march -- to spread the word and appeal to the leaders in the entire world to make fair, ambitious and committed decisions, she said.
This isn't an easy task, but it must be taken, it is not possible anymore to avoid it.
Police prevented the demonstrators to come too close to the Bella Centre and said they had arrested 19 people because they were wearing a mask or they were in possession of pocket knives.
Police prevented the demonstrators to come too close to the Bella Centre and said they had arrested 19 people because they were wearing a mask or they were in possession of pocket knives.
According to a passerby who requested anonymity because of his involvement in the climate talks, the activists, who wore masks and black clothes, lit a number of explosives near the main waterway in Copenhagen, which is surrounded by several ministries.
They were launching them near the buildings, he said, adding that these were first rockets, followed later by "a few big explosions".
Inside the Convention Centre, people were gathered around television screens to follow the march throughout the afternoon.
But it seems that demonstrators have failed to revive the awareness of key authorities such as Su Wei, China representative on climate.
When he was asked if he thought that a demonstration would have a positive impact on international deliberations, he said in English "In fact, this is something I was not aware of.
He then continued in Mandarin, saying "the event being important, I cannot hear what happens outside".
He observed that marching could seem harmful or useful, depending on the outlook.
It shows the interest of the public and the various sectors on the subject of climate change, he said.
On the other hand, "you can also say that they disrupt the talks or that they are damaging to the freedom of others."
The results of the tests show tenacious differences between races
The federal report last week on the results in mathematics brought  good news for public schools in Washington D.C.
Although the District is still far behind the leading institutions, the report shows that the Grade 4 and Grade 5 (cm1-cm2) are showing much greater progress in the last two years than in cities such as Atlanta, Chicago and New York.
But what stands out in the latest figures from the National Assessment of Educational Progress (Evaluation nationale du progrès de l'enseignement) is the persistent gap between the results for African-Americans and those for Whites, both locally and nationally.
The average results for white children in Grade 4(CM1) from Washington D.C. have risen over the past two years from 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500), but those of their African-American classmates increased by only three points, from 209 to 212.
The achievement gap has actually risen between 2007 and 2009, from 53 to 58 points.
The progress of African-Americans in Grade 8 (4th year) remains generally constant, falling just one point from 245 to 244.
The average result among whites was not included in the test results because the sample was not sufficiently significant.
The overview over a period of six years is no more encouraging.
In 2003, the gap between blacks and whites in the Grade 4 class (CM1), when the first NAEP district report was published, was 60 points (262 to 202).
Although the results achieved by children in both groups have increased during this period, the difference has only decreased to 58 points.
Last week, some advocates in the District have expressed concern that rising celebrated by the head of educational institutions group  Michelle A. Rhee and the Mayor Adrian M. Fenty (Democrat) were powered by the white students who were already good elements.
That would mean that we have elevated the aggregate by considering the elements at the top of the ladder, which is problematic and embarrassing, has said Jeff Smith, Director of D.C. Voice, a non-profit group that defends the equality in the education of the District.
I am not jumping for joy for one or two points earned, said Kwame R. Brown (related Democrat), a member of the Council of D.C. and whose daughter was in grade 4, Eaton Elementary (elementary school).
Often critical of the style of management of Rhee, Brown said that the message of the results of tests is that the middle schools (colleges) of the city are desperate for attention.  Often critical of Rhee's management style, Brown said that the message from the results of tests is that the city's middle schools are in desperate need of attention.
Really, you always want to see the positive signs and I respect this.
But what is frightening, is that we do not spend enough time and energy on our middle schools.
Rhee said that the district should continue to find better ways to meet the needs of students in difficulty.
This autumn, for example, some teachers have been trained to use a new reading method, the Wilson Reading System, which aim primary school and beginning of middle school pupils who have not included the foundations of reading earlier in their school route and who are lagging behind their peers.
Every day, the mathematics programs, for grades Kindergarden through sixth focus on games and experiences based in real life, as they have been put in place in the district by the former head Clifford Janey, she must also be credited for the progress of the NAEP that was reported last week.
I just simply believe that we must continue to work to provide better interventions for these pupils who are below the level of their class,  Rhee said.
Others argue that the results of the NAEP raise the question of whether Rhee can keep raising the overall results of the system while providing with money and resources the schools with fewer good results in order to reduce the gap.
This is a dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a trainer of education at the University of Berkeley in California who studied the results of tests of the cities.
The conventional political solution is to allocate your resources and management reforms to schools in the poorest neighborhoods of Washington.
Also this targeting can have political consequences which hassles this important program.
But the problem, of course, is that like other school superintendents, she is trying to use middle class whites and blacks.
We focus to ensure the development of a system of good schools.
We need to strengthen our school districts so that all families, regardless of where they originate, should be confident that their children can get an excellent public education.
Janey, now superintendant of schools in Newark, declared in an interview this week that one of the essential elements in reducing the achievement gap was for the traditional public school year length, currently at 180 days in the District of Washington, to be competitive with the charter schools.
About 200 days are needed to have the strength to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with his teachers union last year for 185 days, which he considers a "starting point" to yet achieve an increase in the next contract.
Turning higher education into a promise for the future
The bus stopped at Gettysburg College with a long whistle.
Graciela Rodriguez, age 12, comes down from it and blinks for a moment at the sight of the white columns, brick facades, and green lawns.
The parents of Graciela had only been able to complete high school, in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela herself, who was born in Silver Spring and lives in Riverdale, had never set foot on a university campus.
Also, when she and other students in 8th Grade (fourth) of the group explored Gettysburg where school fees are $38 690 per year, her attitude was less one of a new impressed student than of an enthusiastic one.
Great This is where I am going to study! exclaimed Graciela who would like to study medicine, while the guide was leading them towards the entrance of the building of science.
Yay, really? she said dreamy, when we pointed out to her the low ratio between professor of law and student.
The University of Pennsylvania was the seventh the children visited during their three-day journey of discovery and now, they had completely incorporated the message: The question is not whether you are going to college:
The question is where.
Although this question is still largely asked for the large number of American children born from Hispanic immigrant parents who have left the school or became parents while they were teenagers, they are also hundreds of thousands to benefit from the university system that will enable them to enter the middle class.
In fact, one second generation Hispanic out of five pursues his studies at the school -- a notable success when you consider that both of his immigrant parents, for the most part from Mexico or Central America, entered the United States without having finished school.
Their success is important, researchers say, they open the way for the following generations who will play an important role in the workforce of the country.
The researchers who study fighters claim that they have a natural affinity with school and an innate need to succeed.
Many are also those whose parents set high aims for their children and who find ways to compensate their lack of familiarity with the American schools.
Coaching programs also play a very important role to help Graciela and millions of children like her to reach university -- especially if her efforts are regular and on a long-term.
When you look at children from low-income families with parents who do not have experience and skills to help them navigate the system, any intervention, at any time, will not help, said Patricia Gándara, researcher at Davis, University of California, who has studied Latin-American students.
We must think to offer a support network for these children, from kindergarten through high school.
The federal program, which has funded the visit of the universities of Graciela is a good example.
Known as Gear UP (prepare yourself), it provides more than $300 million per year to local school systems to organize programs in preparation for college which begin when students from low income families are in High School and continue until the end of the High School years.
Since 1999, the program has been followed by more than 10 million students, with more than 60 percent going to university, according to the US Department of Education.
The oil Ministry of Iraqi obtains agreements with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite the concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has managed to attract some major oil companies to rebuild its infrastructure in difficulty during two auctions that ended Saturday.
The 10 agreements brokered by the Iraqi Ministry of oil with the foreign oil companies suggests that the oil companies in China, Russia and Europe are about to play a major role in the restoration of the oil industry in Iraq, quashed by decades of war and sanctions.
American companies are spread with a participation in only two of the 10 auctioned fields.
Seven American companies had paid to participate in the second auction, which began on Friday.
The only one who had made a bid has lost.
Two American companies have received contracts for the fields auctioned in June.
The weak representation of American oil giants in the opening of the oil sector in Iraq has surprised analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors, after six years of war, and instead of American companies, it is Asian and European companies which are paving the way, said Ruba Husari, editor of Iraq Oil Forum, a news site on the Internet.
It will take a long time before another offer is made in Iraq.
Concerns about security, reinforced by massive coordinated bombings Tuesday, and political instability since American military troops were withdrawing have slowed down the American oil companies, preventing them from entering more forcefully into Iraq which has the third largest crude oil reserves in the world, analysts say.
The American companies were in some cases at a disadvantage because of their rivals, especially the Chinese and the other government-controlled energy companies, which had significantly lower labor costs and which were more prepared to take risks because they did not have to report to shareholders.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies that obtained contracts with the ministry.
The largest American companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, who kept strong ties with the Iraqi oil ministry and brought them their technical advice, have left empty-handed.
The Russian companies Lukoil and Gazprom were the two main shareholders in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
Chinese National Petroleum Corp., owned by the state, has raised more the offer on contracts than other companies and left with significant holdings in contracts for two major fields.
We all know that China is becoming a major economy, as well as a technological power, said Assam jihad, spokesman for the oil ministry.
We are confident that Chinese society will be equal with its competitors and fulfill its commitments in Iraq.
The companies pre-selected to submit auction bids made offers which were then compared to the price per barrel which the ministry was prepared to spend to stimulate production above current levels for each area.
One of the main organisers of Al Qaeda would have been killed in Pakistan
It seems that an American missile which struck along the border with Afghanistan has killed one of the organizers of al-Qaeda operations, this week, American counter-intelligence authorities said Friday.
If the information is confirmed, it would be the second deadly attack against one of the terrorist leaders this autumn.
Saleh al-Somali was one of two Arab men suspected of having been killed by a pair of rockets fired into their car, on Tuesday, near the town of Miran Shah, in the province of North Waziristan, according to American sources and Pakistani authorities in the region.
Local authorities have said the missiles were fired by a pilotless aircraft of the type used by the CIA, inside the lawless tribal border of Pakistan.
They were driving a white car, heading towards the Afghan border, when the car was struck, said a member of the Pakistani Civil Secret Service, speaking by telephone from Miran Shah.
The authorities said that the suspected local militants rushed in and rapidly confiscated what remained of the "totally shattered bodies."
It was completly impossible for local authorities to check the identity of the victims, but the two American anti-terror representatives gave unspecified evidence that Somali was one of the dead.
Somali was described as being one of the al-Qaeda military organizer Responsibles who ran the terrorist operations of the group outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
His role was to organize plots throughout the entire world, said one of the authorities, who requested anonymity citing the sensitive nature of the air strikes inside Pakistani territory.
Given its main role, this included probably attack conspiracies against the US and Europe.
He has followed the strategic instructions of the leaders of al-Qaeda and has translated them into plans of action for possible terrorist attacks.
A second representative of the American authority has said that Somali had risen quickly in the ranks of al-Qaida and had very good relations with other extremist groups in the region.
It is perhaps not known to the greater American public, but it does not diminish the threat that it constitutes for us and our allies, said the second official representative.
If his death is confirmed, Somali would be the second major figure of al-Qaeda or the second Taliban leader killed since September, when a similar attack killed Najmuddin Jalolov, leader of a faction of militants in the tribal belt, as well as three other operatives.
The pace of attacks performed by CIA's drones has decrease since the summer, of about six operations per months to two, according to the figures provided by the Long War Journal, a tempered website by a non-profit group.
This decline is perhaps due to improved tactics from the terrorist groups that have progressed in order to reduce their vulnerability while also ruthlessly killing the suspected informants, the site says.
The UN correspondent to Kabul withdraws
The UN special envoy in Afghanistan, Kai Eide, said Friday that he would resign in March, ending a tumultuous tenure marred by allegations of extended corruption during the UN backed presidential elections.
Eide's departure happens as the Obama administration has decided to send 30,000 additional soldiers in Afghanistan.
The UN envoy has said that he supported this increase, but he has expressed his concern regarding the timing of the United States for a withdrawal of troops which would start in 18 months and which would force the other governments of NATO to withdraw their forces.
We need to accelerate the development of our security forces in Afghanistan, send the right signal to the Afghans and remind them that they can trust the international community, said Eide in a telephone interview from Kabul.
Our commitment must be long-term.
The Norwegian diplomat also urged the US and the other military powers to increase the number of international officials helping the political transition in Afghanistan.
The military increase must be copied by civilians, he said.
Eide said he did not resign but that he would keep the commitment that he had made to his family, in March, to spend only two years in Kabul.
He said he wanted to inform the United Nations.
The Secretary General Ban Ki-moon now knows that he has time to find a replacement.
I just said it was better to start looking for my successor, said Eide.
When I came here, there had been a gap of two months between the departure of my predecessor and my arrival.
According to representatives of the UN, Ban has already begun to seek a replacement.
The representatives affirm that the name Staffan di Mistura has been cited; he is an Italian-Swiss citizen who recently chaired a UN mission to Baghdad and Jean-Marie Guéhenno, a Frenchman who previously directed UN peacekeeping operations.
Eide's reputation in Afghanistan has been hurt after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, accused him in September to favor President Hamid Karzai during the presidential elections and hide the evidence of a massive electoral fraud.
Eide denied this allegations but he said that accusations to Galbraith -- which has been dismiss -- "have damaged the mission because there was already a big dose of skepticism regarding the international observation of elections."
Eide said he had proposed the appointment of a civilian representative to co-ordinate the rescue of American forces in Afghanistan.
He also urged the UN Executives to allow his successor to hire more staff from the US and other Western countries than what is attributed to the mission in Afghanistan, saying that this would give them more confidence in the way their money is spent.
Eide has expressed his frustration concerning the limits of his power in Afghanistan, saying that the heavy regulations on recruitment from the UN disturbed his chances to bring new talent.
The UN's rules are such that I was able to recruit only one person since May, he said.
It is catastrophic and it cannot last.
