Defense Secretary Robert M. Gates said Friday that the major world powers would soon impose "serious additional sanctions" on Iran because of its failure to engage in talks on the nuclear ambitions.
Gates, speaking in front of 300 American soldiers in northern Iraq, for a one week visit in the war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq, has played down the possibility of a military action against the Islamic Republic.
There is no good option in Iran, he said, in response to a soldier's question on such an outcome possibility.
One of the things that weighs the most on me, is that if I learnt a thing in Iraq over the past six years, it is the unpredictable side inherent to the war.
The Obama administration is considering a set of sanctions aimed at the military and political elite of Iran, but Gates has pointed out that some of these sanctions could also affect the Iranians in the street.
He said that a "combination of incentives and punishments" might be needed to persuade the Iranian government that it would in fact have worse security with nuclear weapons "because" his people would suffer greatly with these sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement of the White House spokesman, Robert Gibbs, the administration has joined the European leaders in warning that Iran will face the "probable" consequences if it does not bring its nuclear program in full compliance with the UN Security Council and its supervisory body, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
Iran keeps on saying that it wants to develop its nuclear experience on peaceful purposes only.
In the Geneva talks, on October 1st, it indicated that it would resume the dialogue on the reduction of its nuclear program and agreed to abandon a major part of its stock of enriched uranium, in exchange for fuel desperately needed for a medical research reactor.
The administration has prompted such an agreement, a mean to develop confidence on both sides and win time for negotiations.
Since then, Iran appears to have distanced itself from the proposals in the agreement - in part, say experts, because the Iranian leadership is divided on whether or not to deal with the United States.
Frankly, I think the inflexibility of Iran with respect to some of the proposals of the international community to which they had in fact agreed at the beginning of October, prompted the international community, including the Russians and the Chinese, to join forces on items they had not previously considered, in terms of serious additional sanctions against the Iranians, said Gates.
President Obama has set December 31st as the deadline for Iran to respond to the proposals, before he turns to other options, including the pursuit of what Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called "accumulated sanctions."
In a statement on Thursday in New York, the Iranian mission to the United Nations condemned what it calls "the baseless allegations" of some members of the Security Council on the nuclear activities of Iran and said that it agreed to continue talks with the United States and five other major world powers, "in order to get a long-term satisfactory solution".
Gates, who was to return to Washington late on Friday, has met during the morning, Iraqi Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki, before flying to the oil rich region of Kurdish in order to meet the leaders of the troops in Kirkuk, Kurdish and Irbil.
Tensions persist between Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq, particularly on the borders, property rights and the share of income.
Gates has urged both sides to reduce the potential conflict in order to avoid delays to American plans for the reduction in the number of American troops, from 115,000 to 50,000 before the end of August.
Gates also wants to ease the anxiety of Kurds concerning the pending  withdrawal. The American authorities quoted Gates saying to Massoud Barzani, president of the regional government of Kurdistan : "We will protect your security, prosperity and your autonomy within a unified Iraq."
"We won't abandon you."
In an aging China, a change of direction
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters preaching to them, "Mother Earth is too tired to welcome more children" and "Another baby is another grave."
They have so far learned the lesson that the authorities of Shanghai government, alarmed by the low birth rate in their city and the population ageing, have radically changed direction this summer and have begun to encourage young couples to have more than one child; their reaction was instantaneous and firm: never.
We have already given all our time and all our energy to one child.
We have no second left, said Wang, 31 years old, director of human resources and father of an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of one-child policy in China, creating two generations of unique children notoriously with good cheeks and spoiled, nicknamed the "Little Emperors', a population crisis is threatening the country.
According to the UN, the average birth rate is 1.8 children per couple less than six when the policy was implemented.
As for the distribution of the population, it is envisaged that the number of residents greater than 60 years will explode from 16.7 percent of the population by 2020 to 31.1 percent by 2050. This figure is well above the global average of around 20 percent.
That imbalance is even worse in the coastal rich cities with a highly educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for nearly 22 percent of the population of residents registered in Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning Commission said that fertile couples should have babies to "help to reduce the proportion of the aging population and prevent a lack of labor in the future."
Shanghai is about to become "as old - but not as rich, however - as developed countries such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual reduction
Written in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is to this day undoubtedly the most controversial requirement introduced by the communist government.
Couples who transgress this policy may have to pay huge fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and to suffer discrimination at the workplace.
The Chinese authorities missioned the police to help the country to avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while lawyers for human rights have denounced the abuse in implementing this policy.
In rural areas, law-enforcement representatives forced women pregnant with their second child to have an abortion.
Moreover, many couples have resorted to selective abortions, leading to an abnormally high boys-girls ratio.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including for residents of cities, members of ethnic minorities and the cases in which a man and a woman already have only one child -- and in 2007, they toned down their harsh slogans quite a bit.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at Beijing University, said that central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one partner is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time at all, the posters urging families to have only one child have been replaced with copies of the regulations detailing who has the right to have a second child and how to request authorization.
The city government dispatched family planning authorities and volunteers to meet with couples in their homes, and to slide brochures under their doors.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
According to the head of Family Planning, the response has been disappointing.
Disappointing answer
Although officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for records of couples wanting a second child following the launch of the campaign, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The town of Huinan, with a population of 115,000 inhabitants, for example, still receives only four to five requests per month.
Disappointed officials in Shanghai say that, despite the campaign, the number of births in the city, in 2010, is still expected to be only around 165 thousand -- slightly higher than 2009 but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, the person in charge of the committee of family planning in the municipality of Caolu in Shanghai, said that the financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to provide for their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife Liu Juanjuan, 26, have said that they would really love to have two children and that they are legally authorized to do so.
But like many Chinese, they have only the minimum health insurance and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners wrongly consider that the one-child policy is a problem of rights, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the first child of the couple.
It's true, they are robbing us of the chance of having more than one child.
But the problem is not only the law.
It is the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, chief human resources, said she wanted an only child because she was one herself. "We were the centre of the family and were used that everyone was looking after us."
We are not used to taking care of someone else and we really do not want to take care of others."
Chen zijian, 42 years and owner of a society of translating said it more bluntly.
For couples where both are working, middle class, who are lowering the birth rate, he says, one must be selfish to succeed well.
People between 20 and 30 years old have grown up watching their parents fight during the rise of capitalism in China and they do not want to live the same way, he is quoted as saying.
Even one child asks a lot of time to his parents, he says.
A mother must abandon at least two years of her social life.
Then there are the problems of space -- "You need to change your apartment" -- and planning -- "when your child is only 9 months old, you must write his CV to obtain a place in the best nursery school."
Most of his friends are ready for that experience once, said Chen, but not twice.
Our generation is the first one to benefit from a higher standard of living, he says.
We do not want too many sacrifices.
The UN group plans projects for emissions reducing
The climate conference, sponsored by the UN - characterised so far by disorganised posturing and mutual recriminations -- is back in the spotlight on Friday, because of the publication of a document outlining the ambitious cuts in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations bearing most of the burden in the near future.
The text which could provide the foundations of a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, has emphasized the remaining barriers, as much as it has lighted up the path to take.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the negotiations which don't have much time left, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Written by a special working group from ONU, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to cope with climate change, on short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and new emerging economies could reduce their production of carbon and what would be the upper limit of the rise in global temperature that those responsible would be prepared to tolerate.
It gives a great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Washington Representative of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page text about the negotiations to concentrate on what the Executive Secretary of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, Yvo de Boer, said was "the full picture" regarding climate change.
It shows the guidelines of a potential agreement in which the industrialized nations would collectively reduce their emissions in 2020, by 25 to 45 percent compared with 1990 levels, while the main developing countries, during the same period, would reduce theirs by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union has also revied negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help the poorest countries to adapt to the impact of climate change -- to cope with floods and droughts or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal squabbling occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, the representative of the United States in the climate negotiations rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, as compared to the voluntary efforts made by the major emerging economies, where the latter were not being funded by developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration is becoming more tough toward China than the Bush administration has been two years ago.
The United States is not going to sign an agreement without efforts and actions of major developing countries, said Stern who also regretted that the text is not insistent enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern has made his comments one hour after the Chinese foreign affairs deputy, He Yafei had said that the principal US negotiator, either lacked "common sense", or was "highly irresponsible" for having said earlier that week that the US would not financially help China fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the main world powers at stake, some flaws appeared both within the Third World and between the industrial world and the Emerging Economies.
The battle now is more relevant to the rescue of individual economies than that of saving the planet, with China and the United States cutting back on their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries are ignoring scientific needs to act more boldly.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of the reduction of greenhouse gases, even if the vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make the big emitters accountable for their actions.
This is really a game in which has developed a new economic hegemony, said Ulate, which is also adviser on the climate for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some countries which are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty, in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that negotiations will lead, at the least, to a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States that includes 43 states, has drafted a 24-pages treaty proposal, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, director of the climate division of the European Commission, has said that the action of the small island states has "put political pressure on the whole political process, in part because they are now unified and are asking the emerging economies such as China and India, to act.
The debates have become an urgent matter, while the delegates were focussing on the fact that they had to solve most of the issues pending before the heads of governments come to an agreement.
High level officials such as Indian Environment Minister, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese deputy minister descended from their plane and ran into the Bella Center building to attend meetings behind closed doors and information conferences, in order to make complaints which will be considered in the course of the following week.
The real picture of the gathering -- during which 13,000 people come in and out of the Palais des Congrès every day -- activist guitar players performing nightly shows, mocking the countries which, according to them, betray each other and whose proposals are made and distributed on paper rather than by emails -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than on Wednesday, 60 heads of governments will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the big boys playground, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice-president of Conservation International worldwide politics.
The trucks are arriving.
In Great Britain, the first 225km/h train will redefine the Monday Syndrome.
At 5:13 am, Monday morning, a whistle will burst through the night to signal the departure of a train that will mark a transportation revolution in Great-Britain.
The country's first high-speed commuter train will reach 225 km/h, as it runs from Ashford, in Kent, to London's St. Pancras station, covering the 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the transport minister, will be joined by Lady Kelly Holmes in the first commuter train Javelin outside London.
He hopes that the new service will allow Great-Britain to include an international network of fast and reliable trains, and will link the large conurbations of Midlands, North and Scotland to London.
Little rundown slums will become flourishing suburbs, business travel times will be much shorter and the change from air travel and car travel to train travel will reduce the country's carbon emissions while lessening congestion on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties adhere to this project.
But the ten billion pounds needed to build a new rail network, the inevitable battle of schedule and fears of dangers to the environment may slow down the British high-speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company founded in January to make a feasibility report for the government, will turn in its report to Lord Adonis on December 30.
That will permit him to get a detailed map of the route for the next planned stage of the TGV network.
The new line linking London to West Midlands will be drawn in the five metres of the urban area and sites where the impact on the environment can be controversial.
In the countryside, the map will be drawn up to 25 metres of the final route.
It is equally expected that HS2 presents three options for a larger high-speed network, go towards the north.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
The preferred options are put at the forefront of a Y configuration in which a high-speed line will go as far as the West Midlands.
The line will diverge into two at or near Birmingham, with one branch heading toward the west of the Apennines at Manchester and Scotland and another going toward the northeast, toward Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will cross Scotland.
"It seems it will be the best option of performance", a professional of railways said.
When it is finished, the journey time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first branch, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to a trip of one hour currently.
The proposals will allow trains to travel to 400km / h, making the UK grid the fastest in the world.
The original route is designed to allow trains of 400m in length that are able to carry 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can operate on a London - Birmingham line.
A terminal that can handle 20000 passengers per hour would be necessary.
Given the space constraints, it is intended that an existing station will be expanded to receive the high-speed network.
Experts of the rail industry say that only St. Pancras International or Euston offer this possibility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether he feels the project must be put in place, but more lengthy public consultation and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be made before a general election.
Even if he launches the machine, the network will have to be built piece by piece.
The trains will initially have to use the existing rail lines north of Birmingham, except where high speed lines already exist, meaning that the travel times between London and Scotland will remain longer than three hours.
This solution seems to be the best to ensure a passage from planes to trains, constituting a reference point for the revolution of railways.
The taxpayers pay back the loan of 75 000 GBP for the orangery of Tory
Alan Duncan, a leading Tory member of parliament, has cost the taxpayer thousands of pounds per year to pay for the cost of an orangery built in in his home constituency.
The head of the party which has been demoted by David Cameron for having complained that members of parliament had "maintained," has increased its loan of 75 000 GBP to build an extension in Oak to its second home in Rutland.
He had been allowed to have the extra interest, amounting to hundreds of pounds per month, paid by the taxpayer.
The Commons authorities received complaints at the time and were not interrogated by Sir Thomas Legg, who controls members' spending. Last night, Mr Duncan stated that complaints could not be any "clearer and more simple."
Mr Duncan, one of the richest members of the parliament, is the owner of a two storey house in a village of his constituency of Rutland - Melton.
The nearby houses were sold for nearly a million pounds.
The ground floor includes a kitchen, a living room and a dining room, but the salary office claims that Mr Duncan needed more space.
Last year, he added a veranda to the house, describing it in his plans as an orangery.
The neighbours describe it as a "veranda for fun."
Mr Duncan was not asked to give an explanation for the increase in borrowing during a recent investigation made by the Standards and Privileges Committee of the House of Commons, concerning his disposition of previous loans.
The Committee has cleared him last month of the charge of infringement of rules, after an investigation of his spendings.
In 2004, Mr. Duncan has changed the legal security of the loan of 271.406 GBP from his property in London to the home in his constituency that he has bought in 1991, the year before becoming a member of parliament.
The documents published this week show that Mr Duncan was claiming approximately 1,400 GBP per month of interest on loans up to March last year.
In April, its claims have increased by more than 1,800 GBP per month.
The interest rate on the RBS loan of Mr. Duncan has not been changed at this time, suggesting that all increases were intended to finance the loan of 75,000 GBP.
The RBS variable standard interest rate fell from 7.94 percent in December 2007 to 4 percent in March of this year, without budging since then.
The latest publication of the authorities of the Commons shows that Mr Duncan continued to ask 1,250 GBP in May.
Mr Duncan has lost his post as head of the shadow cabinet in September, after an undercover journalist allegedly filmed him saying that members of parliament had to survive "on a budget" after the spending scandal.
"Actually, it is now national, you have to live "on budget" and you are treated as "sh.t"
He said: "I spent my money on my garden and I asked for a small part, based on what was correct.
And I could have asked a hell of a lot more, but I didn't. "
The member of parliament, a millionaire since his former job as an oil negotiator, started to have to explain his expense spending, in May, after it emerged that he had asked for thousands of pounds for his garden, before agreeing with the office in charge of expenditures that it "could be considered excessive."
An activist has dug a £-shaped hole in the lawn of Mr Duncan, in protest after it was revealed that he had asked for 4,000 GBP during three years.
Asked about the increase in borrowing last night, Mr. Duncan said: "It was for capital improvements, approved by both the office that handles expenses and then by Legg."
He added: "There is no problem of a cop-out or development or rules utilisation or whatever.
It was completely clear, in the rules, allowed, etc.
It could not be clearer or more simple."
Believers, come everybody to see Brighton's Advent calendar.
The bathing boxes of Brighton have found a new means of promotion for the winter months, an interactive Advent calendar.
Beyond, a group of alternative church which encourages the spiritual exploration of creativity, invited 24 owners to decorate their cabin for every day of December, using Christmas' songs as theme.
The event began on December 1st, when visitors were allowed to visit the rear cabin, from 5:30 to 6:30 p.m. each day, with patés and hot wine served free of charge.
The Christmas carols chosen so far include: "I Saw Three Ships; O Come, O Come; Emmanuel and "The First Noel," for which the cabin is presenting the work of Janette Tozer, a local artist.
Martin Poole, 50 years old, an assistant marketing of Hove TV, is an unpaid priest from the diocese of Chichester and director of beyond.
He said: "We want religion to be closer to the people in a post-Christian society.
"As a Church, why do we expect that people would enter into a strange old building? It seems to me that the Church should be closer to the people and celebrate in a more exciting manner.
"The idea of the Advent calendar in the beach hut came just after a conversation with some friends, during a dinner.
Brighton is such a creative and vibrant place and we are trying to experiment and to represent that through spirituality."
Strong mobilization in Copenhagen and across the world concerning the climate
Throughout the world and in Copenhagen, where police made hundreds of arrests, tens of thousands of people demonstrated Saturday to demand an ambitious and binding agreement with regard to the fight against global warming.
At least 30 thousand people, according to the police, about a hundred thousand, according to the organizers, marched in the cold in the Danish capital, outside the United Nations Climate Change Conference, which is charged with leading by Friday to an agreement which could come into force on January 1st of 2013.
For Connie Hedegaard, the Danish president of the climate conference, the growing mobilization for climate control throughout the world, as illustrated by these protests, has contributed to making "the political price" of failure in Copenhagen very high.
The incidents in the Danish capital occurred shortly after the departure of the motorcade, when a group of 300 demonstrators, all dressed in black, smashed windows with bricks and hammers, said an AFP journalist.
Riot police officers immediately intervened ruthlessly.
In total, police announced the arrest of 600 to 700 people, mainly, according to them, members of the "Black Bloc," the various ultra-violent splinter groups which were out in force at the NATO summit in Strasbourg, France, in April.
The Climate Justice Action (CJA) coalition, one of the organizers of the demonstration, denounced the conditions in which hundreds of protesters have been arrested "without distinction"; stressing that hundreds of them "were still detained in the street on Saturday evening, handcuffed and kept in a seated position despite the extreme cold."
From the Parliament, the procession, rather good child, went towards the Bella Center, site of the negotiations.
The demonstrators stopped some 500 meters away from the building, without trying to enter it.
A stage had been put up to accommodate the expected speakers, before a candlelight evening with the participation of Cape Town former South African archbishop, Desmond Tutu.
Most of the demonstrators had come by bus and train from large cities in Europe, but many Asians, including some Chinese people and Koreans, were also present as well as Africans.
Nearly 3,000 people, the majority  in sky  blue raincoats, had  first gathered in the morning in Copenhagen at the appeal of Friends of the Earth, who intended to form a "blue tide" for "Justice for the climate".
Today, we come down in the streets to seek compensation for ecological debt for the South, explained Lidy nacpil Philippines campaigner of  the Jubilee South coalition in Copenhagen.
We cannot continue to say: we have time, has estimated the Beninese singer Angélique Kidjo.
There are rivers drying up in Africa, watercourses where one can walk as it had never been possible before.
For the first time in the history of the climate diplomacy, born in 1992 with the adoption of the UN Convention, the anti-globalisation movement has brought himself closer to the environmental organizations.
The French MEP José Bové, a figure of alter-globalism, explained having come to Copenhagen to "link environmental justice and social justice": "Today, there is no disconnect between the fight against climate change and the fight for another world."
The Asia-Pacific region, home of many islands particularly vulnerable to global warming, had given the kick-off of the demonstrations.
A few 50,000 persons, according to the organizers, were down the streets in Australia.
In Manila, a few hundred people, mostly students, marched in red, sporting bandanas praising solar energy.
In Hong Kong or Jakarta, but also in Canada, few hundreds demonstrators crowds are also formed reclaiming bold action against climate change.
In France, the demonstrations organised by the "350" network have gathered a few hundred people, particularly in Paris, Marseilles (South), Lille (North), Bordeaux (West) and Lyons (East).
In Geneva a few dozens of people assembled.
Separatist Abkhazia has elected its President, Georgia denounced a "joke"
Abkhazia has elected its president on Saturday, a little more than one year after Moscow's recognition of this pro-Russian separatist region of Georgia, whereas Tbilisi denounces a "farce".
Some 131,000 people were expected to participate in the first election since the Russia-Georgia war in August 2008 for the control of South Ossetia, another Georgian breakaway territory recognized by Russia
The polling stations closed at 17H00 GMT.
The turnout was 58% a few hours before the closure, according to officials from the Electoral Commission of Abkhazia.
The first interim results were to be announced during the night between Saturday and Sunday.
The five candidates on the ballot, including the outgoing president, Sergey Bagapch, absolutely reject the idea of reunification with Georgia, which has condemned the holding of the election.
This election is a farce.
From his side, Georgian President Mikheïl Saakachvili "regrets that Abkhazia has fallen under total occupation from Russia," his spokesman, Manana Manjgaladzé, said.
Besides Russia, only Nicaragua and Venezuela have recognized the independence of this territory of 216,000 inhabitants, while the rest of the world considers it a part of Georgia illegally occupied by Russian troops.
After having parted with Georgia during the 1992-1993 conflict, which has done thousands of deaths, Abkhazia seeks to show through this election that it is ready to join the international community.
This process is one stage of our new life, our new era as an independent state, Svetlana Kvartchia, a 54-year-old historian who confirmed having voted for Mr Bagapch, told the AFP.
She was among the voters who went to the polling station in a Soukhoumi school, the capital, in a beautiful white building with a few palms in the entry.
The issue of Russian domination is at the heart of the presidential election in this region of sumptuous landscapes, along the coast of the Black Sea.
Large signboards showing Mr Bagapch alongside Russian president and prime minister, Dmitry Medvedev and Vladimir Putin, are set everywhere in this small territory with 216,000 inhabitants.
In Gali, in the West of the country, the leader of the district, Beslan archba, gave a warm reception to Russian officials who came to supervise the progress of the poll.
We, people of Abkhazia, are grateful, he said during a brief ceremony, in reference to Moscow support, in particular, the decision to recognize Abkhazia's independence.
I hope that your country will soon be recognised by the United Nations, responded Ostrovski Alexei, a member of the Russian parliament, raising a glass of vodka.
On its side, the opposition represented at the ballot by the former Vice President Raúl Khadjimba and two businessmen, Zaous Ardzinba and Beslan Boutba, criticizes agreements concluded with Moscow last year, such as the one ceding to Russia control over the Abkhazian railways for 10 years ago.
The fifth candidate, Vitali Bganba, says he supports neither the current leadership, nor the opposition.
A majority of 50% plus one vote is needed to win the election.
If no candidate meets this threshold, a second round must be held within two weeks.
Climate: demonstrations throughout the world, incidents in Copenhagen.
Tens of thousands of people marched Saturday throughout the world, calling for an ambitious and binding agreement at the Climate Conference in Copenhagen, where police, on the alert, arrested nearly 700 people in connection with a major demonstration.
Thirty thousand people according to the police, hundreds of thousands according to the organizers, marched in the afternoon cold in the Danish capital, which is hosting until December 18th delegates from 193 countries, in search of an agreement which would become effective on the 1st of January 2013.
Leaving from the Parliament, the wake, generally well behaved, went in the direction of the Bella Center, where the negotiations are taking place.
The demonstrators stopped some 500 meters away from the centre, without trying to enter it.
A stage had been put up to accommodate the expected speakers, before a candlelight evening with the participation of Cape Town former South African archbishop, Desmond Tutu.
A few moments after the departure of the procession, a group of several hundred demonstrators, all dressed in black and armed with bricks and hammers, broke the windows, an AFP journalist stated.
Anti-riot policemen immediately surrounded them and stepped in ruthlessly, throwing several of them to the ground.
The police announced the arrest of 600 to 700 people, saying that they were mainly members of the "Black Bloc," the various ultra-violent splinter groups which especially made their presence known at the NATO summit in Strasbourg, in eastern France, in April.
In the late afternoon, a policeman was injured in the jaw by a paving stone and four cars burned near a squatter's dwelling in incidents that led to the arrest of 20 people, according to the police.
We have our eye on the extremist groups, warned police spokesman Henrik Jakobsen, while the security forces' helicopters were in the sky.
Most of the demonstrators, who came by bus and by trains from major cities of Germany, from London, Amsterdam or Milan, were of European origin.
But many Asians, including a number of Chinese and Koreans, were also present and Africans too.
Nearly 3,000 people, the majority  in sky  blue raincoats, had  first gathered in the morning in Copenhagen at the appeal of Friends of the Earth, who intended to form a "blue tide" for "Justice for the climate".
Today, we are out in the streets to seek compensation for the ecological debt for the South, explained Lidy Nacpil Philippino campaigner for the Jubilee South Coalition in Copenhagen.
We cannot continue to say: we have time, has estimated the Beninese singer Angélique Kidjo.
There are rivers which are drying up in Africa, there are streams in which one can walk as one never could before.
For the first time in the history of the climate diplomacy, born in 1992 with the adoption of the UN Convention, the anti-globalisation movement has brought himself closer to the environmental organizations.
The French MEP José Bové, the face of alter-globalism, told the AFP that he came to Copenhagen to "link climate justice and social justice": "Today, there is no disconnect between the fight against global warming and the fight for a new world."
Oxfam mobilized several celebrities, including Danish model Helena Christensen the former UN Commissioner concerned with refugee affairs Mary Robinson, who had to address the crowd.
The Asia-Pacific region, home of many islands particularly vulnerable to global warming, had given the kick-off of the demonstrations.
A few 50,000 persons, according to the organizers, were down the streets in Australia.
In Manila, a few hundred people, students for most, marched, dressed in red and using bandanas boasting solar energy in front of the town hall of the capital of the Philippines.
In Hong Kong or Jakarta, few hundreds of demonstrators also rallied to call for an action against the climate change.
In France, the demonstrations organised by the "350" network have gathered a few hundred people, particularly in Paris, Marseilles (South), Lille (North), Bordeaux (West) and Lyons (East).
In Geneva a few dozens of people assembled.
History and geography have been strengthened by the reform of the high school, according to Chatel.
National Education Minister Luc Chatel said in an interview to appear in the JDD Sunday that history and geography were "strengthened" by the general school reform, despite their teaching no longer being compulsory in the final year of High School.
From here on, first level pupils will all have four hours weekly of the same program as a shared common culture, says Mr. Chatel.
For the minister, "we have to stop being hypocritical" because, according to him, "Level S is no longer a science level," but "essentially, attracts the best pupils".
Social Study and Economy courses and Litterature courses cannot remain underestimated in front of Scientific courses, he continues by pointing out : "I have neither heard many historians and intellectuals who are outraged by the absence of History and Geography courses in the final year in technology high school.
On Saturday, an IFOP poll published in L'Humanité revealed that nearly seven out of ten French people (69%) disapproved of the government project to abolish the compulsory teaching of History/Geography in the Senior year of High School. Many scholars and teachers have also criticized this elimination, as well as the left and some elected members of the right.
The minister however added that removing the philosophy of the Scientific Bacalaureate programme was "out of the question".
Luc Chatel has also defended the reform of teacher training, while 16 organizations (of students and unions) have called for a day of action on Tuesday to protest against the project, which, according to them,  sacrifices the educational training of future teachers.
In master (M2), they will pass an eligibility test at the beginning of the year which will cover their discipline, then at the end of the year an admission test which will cover their capacity to teach, has explained the minister.
They will also follow internship positions during the year of M2 then will be during a first year in front of pupils as trainee teachers.
If you add up all the courses offered before the competition, you already get more presence in front of the pupils, more than 300 hours, he continued.
Finally, the minister says he will propose "the individual right to training, something that does not exist in national education."
He also reaffirms the project to remove the schoolcards "by 2012."
At Normale Sup, experts have 15 minutes to convince over the climate
Fifteen minutes to talk about the challenges of the Copenhagen summit: it is the challenge that was accomplished Saturday morning by Jean Jouzel, vice-president of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) invited by the Normal School of Ulm street.
Jean Jouzel, also a Nobel Peace Prize winner, inaugurated the first of the "Ernest" conferences, a day consisting of a series of 15-minute, filmed lectures by experts, which are open to the public, stated an AFP journalist.
We wanted to do something that catches people and makes them want to know more, said outside the conference Edouard Hannezo, 22 years old, one of the organisers of this day that takes its name from the one given by the students to the fish in the school's pond.
We choose around twenty speakers among experts in their discipline and we select them for their charismatic side, he specified.
On global warming, "we can talk for hours, but we can also speak of the key objectives in a few minutes", Jean Jouzel told the AFP, speaking without notes, but using charts, in front of about 50 people.
This is part of our role of scientific, he pointed out, hoping that the auditors will remember that "the Copenhagen conference is based on an extremely serious scientific file".
The videos derived from these conferences will be put online on the site of the school from the 15th of December.
The next day "Ernest" is scheduled for February, followed by others at a bimonthly pace.
Late payments: anger of prison guards, planned actions.
The unions of prison guards called on Friday for a "general mobilization" to demand the payment, between now and the end of the year, of bonuses and overtime whose payment was pushed out to January for budgetary reasons.
Fo-pénitentiaire (2nd overseers' syndicate) has asked the personnel who will not be in service to show on Tuesday morning in front of the prisons and "block" them to "denounce the theft of their ownings."
The CGT-penitentiary (3rd trade union of the profession) calls upon them to "meet in general meetings in various prisons for strong action", judging as "a disgrace and unacceptable" the non-payment  in December for "overtime, night bonuses, Sundays, and holidays" worked in October.
And the first trade union of supervisors, the union of independent Federal prisons (UFAP / UNSA), "called for a general mobilisation (...) to make evident the discontent and anger".
The leadership of the prison administration and the Justice Ministry explain that extra hours have greatly increased in 2009 and have not all been budgeted for, but they assure that the remainder will be paid for in January.
The Chancellery said at the end of the day that Michele Alliot-Marie had sent a letter to the wardens unions guaranteeing that this payment would be made next month.
I know the efforts done by the staff for the operation and the modernization of our prison system, wrote the minister of justice in this letter.
I asked the administration department of the prison to set in motion with no delay a serie of measures to ensure that this situation, born of a bad assessment of the overtime hours, does not happen again in the future, says Mrs Alliot-Marie.
The pay of December will be small, except for the staff of direction receiving the famous functions and objectives premiums, deplored the UFAP / UNSA, for whom "the budgetary constraints are easy to blame".
It is a real scandal, has incensed the Marseilles' Interregional FO union, in announcing its decision to boycott until further notice "all the meetings and summons".
The staff will not work on their Sundays and holidays if those of October are not given legal status in December, the same goes for overtime, also threatens fo rhône-alpes-auvergne.
Now that we are increasing our tasks and our missions without increasing our staff, it is truly wrong to dare to go after our workers' money, the prison union in Bordeaux believes.
According to the trade unions, the situation is not the same in all regions, some being less badly off than others.
But in any case it doesn't add up, has noticed the UFAP's secretary-general, Jean-François forget.
