Johnny Hallyday was operated on again in Los Angeles because of "major lesions" after an operation in France, but the situation is "under control" according to his entourage, while RTL says that the singer has been placed in an artificial coma to help him avoid pain and complications.
The 66 years old rocker was re-operated during the night of Wednesday to Thursday at the Los Angeles Cedars-Sinaï hospital after that American doctors had noted "lesions resulting from the operation" of the disc herniation performed in Paris on November 26, said his press service in Paris, specifying that these injuries "needed a restorative operation".
However, the singer's press service wanted to be reassuring, stating that the situation was "under control", while announcing that a new medical bulletin would be communicated later in 48 hours.
According to RTL, partner of the last tour of the singer, Johnny Hallyday would however have been plunged into an artificial coma to avoid "pain and complications".
It is only in 48 hours that we will have a little more assurance on the state of the patient when he will have opened an eye, adds RTL.
When questioned by AFP, the press service has neither confirmed nor commented on the information.
RTL also says that, "according to some sources" no drain would have been put after the first operation in Paris.
The rocker was operated at the international clinic of Park Monceau for this slipped disk.
The operation, scheduled for several days had been practised by the neurosurgeon Stéphane Delajoux, a renowned doctor in the midst of arts.
This one was not available on Thursday evening to comment on the information from RTL.
Following the operation he has practiced on Johnny Hallyday, the singer was hospitalized Monday in the Cedars-Sinaï hospital of Los Angeles, for an infection following the intervention.
The singer Eddy Mitchell, Johnny Hallyday's friend, estimated Thursday on RTL that his friend had "a bad patch" but said also "no worries" for the rocker, who is a "fighter".
He had called me just before leaving for Los Angeles, and I told him that it was bullshit because spending 12 hours on a plane after such an operation, it is not feasible, Eddy Mitchell said.
On Wednesday evening, the producer of the singer, Jean-Claude Camus, had wanted reassuring, asserting that Johnny Hallyday " reacted in a satisfactory way to antibiotics " and that the infection was "diked".
Mr Camus also said he had spoken with Laeticia, wife of the singer, and had not noticed any particular concern.
But the singer's health problems have only gotten worse since July when he was hospitalized for nine days following a fall on his yacht.
Two months later to general surprise, Johnny Hallyday was revealed to have been gotten an operation for a "small colorectal cancer', then a slight infection.
Late September, the singer went back again as planned on his long "66 Tour", presented as his farewell tour.
But since then, every health problem is abundantly discussed. Fans and journalists noticed the singer's difficulty in moving around on stage.
In mid-November, his entourage was even forced to deny a new hospitalization.
Euro-2009 /Small Pool: Bousquet's First-Place Win In His Favorite Distance 
The Frenchman Frédérick Bousquet, triple medalist at the 2009 World Championships in the Olympic pool, achieved on Thursday an international title in a distance he particularly favours, the 50-meter free-style, during the Euro-2009 short-course Championships in Istanbul.
The first day of this contest where the wetsuits are allowed for the last time saw only three world records beaten whereas a flood was expected.
One has been improved by the Hungarian Evelyn Verraszto on 200 metres individual medley swimming and the two others by Russia in 4×50 metres medley swimming relay.
A disappointment for Bousquet, who had his eye on the world record in the 50m freestroke, in which he holds the record in the long pool (20.94).
In one of the two major swimming distances, the 50m freestroke, it was the 28-year-old Frenchman who won in 20 sec 53 in a final in which ten swimmers started rather than the usual eight, a first on the international level.
Bousquet outdistanced the Croatian Duje Draganja (20.70) and the Russian Sergey Fesikov (20.84) but didn't succeed in lowering the world score (20.30) as he had planned it.
One can always dream bigger dreams, and under the circumstances, I had said that if the world record was within my reach, I was going to attempt it.
Like Bousquet, almost all of the swimmers were wearing polyurethane suits, which will be banned from 1st January.
The cause of 238 world records since February 2008, these combinations finish their saga in Istanbul, which hosted the first ones in 1999, at the same competition.
The use of combinations was not helpful this time for the German Paul Biedermann, double world champion in the pool this summer in Rome, world records to boot.
The young swimmer did not succeed in lowering the record he held in the 400 m freestyle (3:32.77) but nevertheless imposed by showing the second best time of his career (3:34.55), ahead of the Russian Nikita Lobintsev (3:35.75) and the Dane Mads Glaesner (3:36.82).
I didn't try my best for this course.
I knew I could not break a world record at that time, but I managed to defend my title and I have accomplished my mission.
Lobintsev will be a serious rival in the future, said Biedermann.
USA: a panel of a sarcophagus that belonged to Zola appraised at $1.5 million
A panel from a Roman sarcophagus that belonged to the French writer Emile Zola was appraised Thursday at 1.5 million dollars, clearly far above its estimate, announced Sotheby's, the art seller. 
This two metres long on 63 cm high front display, dating from the third century A.D., was estimated between 150,000 and 250,000 dollars.
The marble, "representing four dionysian scenes in a sophisticated, architectural setting, with satyrs and devotees of Bacchus all around, is a rare piece. There are only four or five of them in the world," Florent Heintz, Vice-President of Auctions of Ancient Roman and Egyptian Art at Sotheby's "explained to the AFP on Tuesday.
It was sold among a hundred of lots.
The sale is still underway but this lot is certainly the one on which buyers have the most bids so far, said a spokesman for Sotheby's, Dan Abernethy, to the AFP.
The discovery of the acquisition of this marble by Emile Zola, dates back to a few days.
The panel remained in Rome for almost 300 years in the famous collection of the Borghese family, then appeared successively in the home of French actress Cécile Sorel, who made it an element of her bath in her Parisian townhouse, and in the home of Paul Reynaud, a minister at the time of the Third Republic in France and Council President briefly before Marshal Pétain came to power.
A grey area of about fifty years was remaining.
Sifting through the database of the Louvre Museum, Florent Heintz has found that this panel was part of a "Emile Zola succession" opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of "Thérèse Raquin" and of the portrayal of "Rougon-Macquart."
Zelaya's aborted attempt of departure from Honduras to Mexico
Mexico decided on Thursday that conditions were not ripe for the transfer onto its territory of Manuel Zelaya, the toppled President of Honduras, who was denied a safe-conduct pass by the revolutionary government.
For now, after a night-time telephone conversation with President Zelaya, everything seems to indicate that the possibility of achieving this transfer has not been met, said the Mexican foreign minister, Patricia Espinosa.
Having arrived on Wednesday in El Salvador to pick up Mr. Zelaya, the  Mexican government plane left to return to its place of origin, according to a source in the Director General's office of the Immigration Department.
The rebel government wanted to force Mr Zelaya to "resign" and to seek political asylum abroad to give him a free ticket.
But the dethroned President refused, because he wanted to travel to Mexico as an invited sitting head of state.
The rebel government "has had another failure in wanting me to give up my position (...), they wanted me to resign", Mr. Zelaya said Thursday on Radio Globo, on which he often speaks since the beginning of the political crisis which has been going on for five months in the Central American country.
I can stay here ten years, here I have my guitar, added while playing a few chords the deposed president, who took refuge in brazilian embassy in Tegucigalpa for two months and a half.
The Mexican Embassy has submitted a request to us for a safe-conduct pass, but unfortunately we cannot accept it because it contains no request for asylum, the Minister of the Interior of the rebel government, Oscar Raul Matute, said Wednesday on Honduran radio station HRN.
I do not seek asylum in any country, Manuel Zelaya had answered in an interview to the Telesur channel, which is based in Caracas.
A possible departure from Honduras will have to occur as president of the Honduran people, he pointed out.
Rumours of Mr Zelaya's leaving had mobilised on Wednesday supporters of former president, who came to unite around the Embassy of Brazil, where the military have strengthened their siege.
Brazilian Foreign Minister Celso Amorim criticised the position of the revolutionary government.
This demonstrates the marginal nature of this government towards international standards, he estimated.
Zelaya, who became close to the Venezuelan socialist president Hugo Chavez, was overthrown on June 28th, the day he held a popular referendum to prepare for his re-election, against the advice of the Supreme Court, the army and the Congress.
Exile to Costa Rica, he returned unexpectedly on September 21st and took refuge in the Brazilian Embassy.
If he leaves, he will be arrested for the crime of "high treason" of which the court accused him, according to the revolutionary government.
The rebel president Roberto Micheletti has managed to hold a presidential election on November 29 to replace Mr Zelaya.
Porfirio Lobo was elected during the controversial election recognised by the United States but disputed by Latin American countries such as Venezuela, Argentina or Brazil.
Three days later, Congress voted overwhelmingly against the return to power of Mr. Zelaya until the end of his term on January 27th.
