The bond market has lowered.
The yield of 10-year Treasury bonds has risen to 3,482% against 3,423% on Tuesday evening and the yield of 30-year bonds to 4,492% against 4,408% the previous day.
Cuba: hundreds of supporters of power jeer at the "Ladies in White."
A few hundred supporters of the Cuban regime shouted down, Thursday, wives of political detainees gathered in Havana for the global day of human rights, and impeded another demonstration in which about ten dissidents were arrested.
About forty 'women in white', the wives and relatives of political prisoners, were booed in the street by supporters of the government  of Raul Castro as they marched towards the centre of the capital demanding the release of political prisoners, reported a journalist of the AFP.
"Down with the Yankees!", "Mercenaries!", "The street belongs to the revolutionaries!", "Long live Fidel and Raul!" chanted the supporters of power to the rebels with their fists lifted high.
These last ones were escorted by plain-clothes officers who came to "protect them."
The day before, a similar demonstration took place against the "women in white" in Havana, without any injuries or arrests.
But in the Havanese neighborhood of Vedado, dozens of dissidents who were about to show on Thursday for the International Day of Human Rights have been, them, picked up by plain-clothes officers, ascertained a journalist of the AFP.
The policemen have forced into civil vehicles the dissidents who have been vilified by government supporters, according to this journalist.
The arrests of dissidents in similar circumstances last few hours in general.
Recipients of the 2005 Sakharov prize of the European Parliament, the "women in white", had organized an unauthorized march to "ask for the release of all political prisoners," around 300 prisoners according to the dissidents, said one of their leaders, Laura Pollan, whose husband Hector Maceda is serving a sentence of 20 years in prison.
Mr Maceda is part of the group of 75 Cuban dissidents arrested in March 2003, 53 of whom remain behind bars.
Cuban authorities consider opponents as "mercenaries" or "agents" in the pay of their enemy, the United States.
Extremely rare, Cuban television reported on Thursday's demonstration of pro-government against "cons-revolutionaries".
Cuba, headed by a single party, the Communist Party, is regularly accused by NGOs of European and American to flout the rights and freedoms, including speech.
A fanatic kills a man in his 80s with a knife and injures 5 in Clichy-la-Garenne
A gunman armed with two knives killed an octogenarian and wounded five others in the city of Clichy-la-Garenne (Hauts-de-Seine), at rush hour, Thursday evening.
According to the first elements of the investigation, the attacker, aged 28 years, would have struck with two knives and for undetermined reasons, an octogenarian in or before a pharmacy at 85 Boulevard Jean-Jaurès, we learned from police sources and from witnesses.
Badly wounded, the old man, born in 1929 according to an official of the police union Alliance, died in hospital from his injuries.
In or in front of the same pharmacy, he ran into a couple, whose wife was pregnant.
The husband, in his thirties, intervened and was injured.
The first two victims, severely injured, were admitted to the hospital where the octogenarian died.
The life of the other injured person is in danger, vital organs are apparently affected, according to the police sources.
The pregnant woman then made a malaise and was hospitalized "in shock", according to a police source.
The gunman, who appeared under the influence of alcohol or drugs, according to police sources, would then fled into the street, always boulevard Jean Jaurès.
It would have wounded two bystanders, apparently at random: a thirty and forty, the latter seriously.
The scenario remained confused in the evening.
He was armed with two butcher knives that he was carrying crossed behind his back, explained Arnaud Pressé, an Alliance Union official in Hauts-de-Seine.
Several passers-by, including young people, according to testimonies gathered by the AFP, tried to control the madman.
I saw a chap around 30 years old with a green jacket.
Three young people have tried to intercept it.
They did not succeed because the guy was tough, reported Alberto, barman in a nearby bar.
A crowd fell on him, including a municipal police officer who broke his wrist, he added.
Always Boulevard Jean-Jaures, at the height of No. 61, two municipal police officers, including their manager, attempted to detain the gunman were injured with fists, according to police sources.
The events occurred in one of clichy-la-garenne's main street, where many shops are.
Passers-by came to tell me that there was a person injured outside.
I went out, I saw a 70-year-old person on the ground, I put him in recovery position, and I saw a very important wound to the abdomen, Frédéric Allione, a 35-year-old pharmacist, told the AFP.
Five minutes later a second person, in his 30s, arrived, suffering knife wounds.
These are numbers of the national police who arrested the man without identity papers.
The Nanterre prosecutor took from the investigation the departmental service of judicial police in Hauts-de-Seine (sdpj 92).
The gunman was hospitalized Thursday night.
He had not yet been heard in its custody.
A police source has not ruled out that he is committed to a psychiatric hospital.
According to another police source, it took six police officers to overpower him at the Clichy police station where he was taken away.
He was "in an overexcitement state" like "all this kind of maniacs whose strengths increase greatly under the effect of action".
USA: Polanski's lawyer calls again to drop charges
The lawyer of the franco-polish film-maker Roman Polanski has called once again Thursday in Los Angeles (California, in the western United States), for the abandonment of the prosecution against his client, currently under house arrest in Switzerland because of a morals charge over 30 years ago.
Hummel Chad, the lawyer of the director of the "Pianist", has denounced in front of three judges of the Second District of California court serious procedural errors at the time of the facts, in 1977.
I am calling for the abandonment of the charges here and now, said Mr Hummel, before adding that the behaviour of the judge in charge of the case at the time, Laurence Rittenband, "sent shivers down the back '.
According to him, Judge Rittenband -- who has since died -- would have spoken, before pronouncing his sentence, with a prosecutor who would have told him that Roman Polanski deserved to be sent to prison -- which is a serious error in procedure.
This discussion was revealed in the documentary "Roman Polanski: Wanted and Desired" (Roman Polanski, Wanted and Desired), from the very mouth of the prosecutor in question, David Wells.
But Mr Wells had finally declared the end of September that he had "lied" to the author of the documentary.
In case the court refuses to abandon the prosecution, Mr Hummel has called for holding a trial, which would allow him to present the evidence of his arguments.
The charge has also reiterated the case already developed in the first instance, namely that no charges drop could be seriously considered as Roman Polanski did not intend to stand before the court.
The film-maker, aged 76, had fled the United States in 1978, before his sentencing for "unlawful sexual intercourse" with a 13-year-old minor.
He has never set foot in the United States since.
The Assistant District Attorney for Los Angeles County, Phyllis Asayama, thus declared that Roman Polanski "must be present at the hearing."
In this case, do we want to send the message, not only to (Roman Polanski) but also to other defendants, that it is possible to escape?, asked Mrs Asayama.
For her, the filmmaker "requests a favour of the court, while scorning its authority."
One of the three judges who now have 90 days to make their decision, he also stressed that "there were other alternatives to flight."
Mr Hummel was not the only one who ask to drop the charges against Roman Polanski.
Samantha Geimer's lawyer, the victim, has also claimed, once again, the end of the prosecutions.
Pointing out that her client no longer puts up with being harasseded at each new development in the Polanski case, she added: "Nobody in this room can say that the procedure was fair.
Thirty-two years is enough. "
Roman Polanski was arrested the 26 September in Switzerland on an american extradition warrant.
After more than two months behind bars, he was placed under house arrest in his chalet in Gstaad, pending a possible extradition.
Wall Street ends without direction, held back by the rising of the dollar
The New York Stock Exchange closed without direction on Friday, in a market torn between better than expected indicators in the United States and the rise of the dollar: the Dow gained 0.63% but the Nasdaq lost 0.03%.
According to the final figures at closure, the Dow Jones industrial average rose to 65.67 points at 10,471.50 points, while the Nasdaq, mainly technological, has abandoned 0.55 point at 2,190.31 points.
The widened index Standard & Poor's 500 has risen by 0.37% (4.06 points) to 1,106.41 points.
Honestly, the market is very calm, noted Mace Blicksilver, Marblehead Asset Management.
It remains within narrow margins, the volume of trade has become very weak and I think it will remain the case until the end of the year.
The trend was sustained by the publication of economic indicators which were better than expected, which "helped improve the market's view as to the strength of the economic recovery," the Charles Schwab analysts summarized.
In the US, retail sales rose by 1.3% in November for the second consecutive month and much more than expected.
US consumer confidence was also clearly up in December, at 73.4 against 67.4 the previous month, according to the preliminary estimate of the University of Michigan index.
The indices were, however, slowed by a new progression of the dollar, at the highest level for two months against the Euro, which "pushes towards the bottom those sectors which are sensitive to the economic situation," explained Owen Fitzpatrick, of Deutsche Bank.
Technology stocks lost ground as well.
The bond market has decreased.
The yield of 10 year treasuries has risen to 3,540% against 3,482% on Wednesday evening and 30 years ones to 4,497% as opposed to 4,492% the previous day.
The election of Miss World once again in South Africa
After a month's journey through South Africa, the 112 candidates for the title of Miss World are preparing to take on Saturday the final stretch to realise their dream: to be elected the most beautiful woman in the world in front of a billion viewers.
During this great display of beauty organized for the second consecutive year in the vicinity of Johannesburg, five of them have already secured their tickets to the semi-finals.
Miss Japan Eruza Sasaki, Perla Beltran Acosta of Mexico, Mariatu Kargbo of Sierra Leone, Kaiane Aldorino of Gibraltar and Yanbing Ma of Canada have been elected Miss sports or Miss top model during their stay in Africa.
It has been a real whirl.
Visit beautiful cities such as Port Elizabeth, Durban and Cape Town, it was extraordinary.
I have seen plenty of things and lived so many experiences!, exclaims Miss Sierra Leone.
This competition, which is held for the ninth time in South Africa, is broadcast on Saturday directly from Midrand, north of Johannesburg, starting at 5 p.m.. (3 p.m. GMT).
I could not dream about a better country to put back my crown.
This experience was fascinating.
I am glad to have lived it twice, emphasizes Miss World Ksenia Sukhinova in the heat of the southern summer.
For the young Russian, her second stay in South Africa has been marked by many exchanges with the candidates and the rediscovery of "breathtaking landscapes in this country."
After a month of galas, rehearsals, meetings with the press and safari, the Misses now focus on competition.
The Indian Pooja Chopra hopes to follow the steps of Priyanka Chopra, elected in 2000 and present at this election, and those of Aishwarya Rai in 1994, who both became Bollywood stars.
It is the dream of every woman to be crowned the most beautiful of the world but it is not only about the appearance.
We are the ambassadors of our countries and I want to return home with the crown, flings Miss India with a broad smile.
According to the organisers, music and dance will punctuate this 59th edition.
Candidates will parade in traditional costume and of course in a swimsuit.
The show will be hosted by Chinese television anchorwoman Angela Chow, South African ex-beauty queen Michelle McLean and Miss World committee member Steve Douglas.
South Africa showed that it knew how to welcome the world with a warmth and pride that is difficult to match, warrants Julia Morley, president of Miss World.
Like last year, the candidates went on a safari, visited the famous township of Soweto, this time by bicycle, and tasted the local cuisine.
A exceptional fact, they also met South African President Jacob Zuma and shake hands.
Not likely for a head of state, notices Miss Sierra Leone.
Their happiest memory will no doubt remain the draw in Cape Town (southwest) for the football World Cup in June 2010, a way for the country to do a little more promotion for the event.
I went with people I thought I would never be able to approach.
I will no doubt return for the 2010 Miss Universe Pageant, says Miss Italy, Alice Taticchi, enthusiastically.
